{"title_page": "Austin K. Doyle", "text_new": "{{short description|United States Navy Vice admiral}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Austin K. Doyle\n| image         = Austin K Doyle.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       = Vice Admiral Austin K. Doyle (at right) October 1955\n| birth_name    =\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1898|11|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Port Richmond, Staten Island]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1970|7|12|1898|11|7}}\n| death_place   = [[Pensacola, Florida]]\n| placeofburial = [[Barrancas National Cemetery]], Pensacola, Florida\n| allegiance    = {{flagu|United States|1916}}\n| branch        = {{Flagcountry|United States Navy|1916}}\n| serviceyears  = 1916\u20131958\n| rank          = [[Vice admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]]\n| unit          =\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n| awards        = [[Legion of Merit]] (2)<br />[[Navy Cross]] (2)\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n| signature     =\n}}\n'''Austin Kelvin Doyle''' (7 November 1898 \u2013 12 July 1970) was an American naval officer, [[Vice admiral (United States)|vice admiral]], chief of [[United States Taiwan Defense Command]] and [[Naval Air Training Command]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hg5BB5V2hd4C&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&source=bl&ots=nDhjiwdFSs&sig=ACfU3U0-vkp009O59bT1eBUJ1yXxjQjgiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiez-rX47noAhUTOSsKHWE-AZs4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&f=false|title=The United States Navy and Defense Unification, 1947-1953|first=Paolo Enrico|last=Coletta|date=March 27, 1981|publisher=University of Delaware Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> who subsequently served captain of the [[United States Navy]] for ''[[USS Hornet (CV-12)|USS Hornet]]'', ''[[Escort Carrier]]'', ''[[USS Saratoga (CV-60)|USS Saratoga]]'', and ''[[USS Nassau (LHA-4)|USS Nassau]]'' in [[World War II]]. After serving in US navy for forty years, he retired in 1958. Austin also served as a [[Rear admiral (United States)|rear admiral]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/07/14/archives/adm-austin-doyle-held-taiwan-post.html|title=Adm. Austin Doyle, Held Taiwan Post|date=July 14, 1970|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Coletta|first=Paolo Enrico|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hg5BB5V2hd4C&pg=PA171&dq=Austin+K.+Doyle&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7wKTCtrroAhWHVBUIHfFJBpUQ6AEIJjAA|title=The United States Navy and Defense Unification, 1947-1953|date=1981|publisher=University of Delaware Press|isbn=978-0-87413-126-0}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nDoyle was born in [[Port Richmond, Staten Island]], New York and then moved to [[Pensacola, Florida]] when he spent about twenty years. In 1919, he attended [[Naval Academy]] at Annapolis where he did his graduation. He then joined the [[United States Navy Department]] for 41 years. [[President of United States]] conferred numerous military decorations upon him for his contribution to the US during World War II. In 1945 and 1946, he was awarded two [[Navy Cross]] awards and later, in the same year, government conferred two [[Legion of Merit]] military awards upon Doyle in recognition of his duty as commanding officer of an escort carrier in May 1943.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/20371|title=Austin Doyle - Recipient -|website=valor.militarytimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSBgbojkC6sC&pg=RA20-PA24&lpg=RA20-PA24&dq=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&source=bl&ots=eFGpLe6FhD&sig=ACfU3U2oSszQ_cMfps9lE_DyVxi1fEob0Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiez-rX47noAhUTOSsKHWE-AZs4ChDoATAIegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&f=false|title=Naval Aviation News|date=March 27, 1948|publisher=Chief of Naval Operations and Naval Air Systems Command, Navy Department|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAustin was married to Jamie Reese Doyle of Pensacola. He had four children, including three sons and a daughter. Apart from this, he had two siblings, a brother and a sister. Doyle had five grandchildren.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Death==\nDoyle was suffering from multiple ailments and was subsequently admitted to [[Pensacola Naval Air Station]] hospital and died at the same medical institute on 12 July 1970. He is buried at [[Barrancas National Cemetery]] in Pensacola, Florida.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|2935617}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doyle, Austin}}\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New York City]]\n[[Category:United States Navy vice admirals]]\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Pensacola, Florida]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Barrancas National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|United States Navy Vice admiral}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Austin K. Doyle\n| image         = Austin K Doyle.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       = Vice Admiral Austin K. Doyle (at right) October 1955\n| birth_name    =\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1898|11|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Port Richmond, Staten Island]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1970|7|12|1898|11|7}}\n| death_place   = [[Pensacola, Florida]]\n| placeofburial = [[Barrancas National Cemetery]], Pensacola, Florida\n| allegiance    = {{flagu|United States|1916}}\n| branch        = {{Flagcountry|United States Navy|1916}}\n| serviceyears  = 1916\u20131958\n| rank          = [[Vice admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]]\n| unit          =\n| battles       = [[World War II]]\n| awards        = [[Legion of Merit]] (2)<br />[[Navy Cross]] (2)\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n| signature     =\n}}\n'''Austin Kelvin Doyle''' (7 November 1898 \u2013 12 July 1970) was an American naval officer, [[Vice admiral (United States)|Vice admiral]], chief of [[United States Taiwan Defense Command]] and [[Naval Air Training Command]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hg5BB5V2hd4C&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&source=bl&ots=nDhjiwdFSs&sig=ACfU3U0-vkp009O59bT1eBUJ1yXxjQjgiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiez-rX47noAhUTOSsKHWE-AZs4ChDoATAAegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&f=false|title=The United States Navy and Defense Unification, 1947-1953|first=Paolo Enrico|last=Coletta|date=March 27, 1981|publisher=University of Delaware Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> who subsequently served captain of the [[United States Navy]] for ''[[USS Hornet (CV-12)|USS Hornet]]'', ''[[Escort Carrier]]'', ''[[USS Saratoga (CV-60)|USS Saratoga]]'', and ''[[USS Nassau (LHA-4)|USS Nassau]]'' in [[World War II]]. After serving in US navy for forty years, he retired in 1958.  Austin also served as a [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear admiral]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/07/14/archives/adm-austin-doyle-held-taiwan-post.html|title=Adm. Austin Doyle, Held Taiwan Post|date=July 14, 1970|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Coletta|first=Paolo Enrico|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hg5BB5V2hd4C&pg=PA171&dq=Austin+K.+Doyle&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7wKTCtrroAhWHVBUIHfFJBpUQ6AEIJjAA|title=The United States Navy and Defense Unification, 1947-1953|date=1981|publisher=University of Delaware Press|isbn=978-0-87413-126-0}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nDoyle was born in [[Port Richmond, Staten Island]], New York and then moved to [[Pensacola, Florida]] when he spent about twenty years. In 1919, he attended [[Naval Academy]] at Annapolis where he did his graduation. He then joined the [[United States Navy Department]] for 41 years. [[President of United States]] conferred numerous military decorations upon him for his contribution to the US during World War II. In 1945 and 1946,  he was awarded two [[Navy Cross]] awards and later, in the same year, government conferred two [[Legion of Merit]] military awards upon Doyle in recognition of his duty as commanding officer of an escort carrier in May 1943.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/20371|title=Austin Doyle - Recipient -|website=valor.militarytimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSBgbojkC6sC&pg=RA20-PA24&lpg=RA20-PA24&dq=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&source=bl&ots=eFGpLe6FhD&sig=ACfU3U2oSszQ_cMfps9lE_DyVxi1fEob0Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiez-rX47noAhUTOSsKHWE-AZs4ChDoATAIegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=admiral+Austin+K.+Doyle&f=false|title=Naval Aviation News|date=March 27, 1948|publisher=Chief of Naval Operations and Naval Air Systems Command, Navy Department|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAustin was married to Jamie Reese Doyle of Pensacola. He had four children, including three sons and a daughter. Apart from this, he had two siblings, a brother and a sister. Doyle had five grandchildren.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Death==\nDoyle was suffering from multiple ailments and was subsequently admitted to [[Pensacola Naval Air Station]] hospital and died at the same medical institute on 12 July 1970. He is buried at [[Barrancas National Cemetery]] in Pensacola, Florida.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|2935617}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doyle, Austin}}\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New York City]]\n[[Category:United States Navy vice admirals]]\n[[Category:1898 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Pensacola, Florida]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Burials at Barrancas National Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Eddie891", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austin_K._Doyle"}
{"title_page": "Anton Schmid", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n |honorific_prefix = \n |name             = Anton Schmid\n |honorific_suffix = \n |image            = Anton-Schmid- low res.tif\n |image_upright    = \n |alt              = \n |birth_date       = {{birth date|1900|01|09|df=y}} \n |birth_place      = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n |death_date       = {{death date and age|1942|4|13|1900|01|09|df=y}}\n |death_place      = Stefanska Prison, [[Vilnius]], [[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]\n |death_cause      = Convicted by a military court and executed\n |placeofburial    = \n |placeofburial_label = \n |placeofburial_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}}-->\n |awards           = [[Righteous Among the Nations]]\n |known_for        = [[Rescuers of Jews during the Holocaust|Saving Jews during the Holocaust]]\n |spouse           = Stefanie Schmid\n |children         = Gerta Schmid\n |occupation       = Electrician\n |module           = {{Infobox military person | embed = yes\n|allegiance       = \n|branch           = {{army|Austria-Hungary}}<br>{{army|Nazi Germany}}\n|branch_label     = Branch\n|serviceyears     = 1918<br>1939\u20131942\n|serviceyears_label = \n|rank             = ''[[Feldwebel]]''\n|rank_label       = \n|servicenumber    = \n|unit             = ''Landeswehr'' Battalion 898<br>Feldkommandantur 814\n|commands         = \n|battles          = [[World War I]]\n*[[Italian front (World War I)|Italian front]]\n{{hr}}[[World War II]]\n|battles_label    = \n|awards           = \n}}\n}}\n'''Anton Schmid''' (9 January 1900 \u2013 13 April 1942) was an Austrian recruit in the ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' who saved Jews during the [[Holocaust in Lithuania]]. A devout but apolitical Roman Catholic and an electrician by profession, Schmid was conscripted into the [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] during [[World War I]] and later into the ''Wehrmacht'' during [[World War II]]. Put in charge of an office to return stranded German soldiers to their units in late August 1941, he began to help Jews after being approached by two pleading for his intercession. Schmid hid Jews in his apartment, obtained work permits to save Jews from the [[Ponary massacre]], transferred Jews in ''Wehrmacht'' trucks to safer locations, and aided the [[Vilna Ghetto]] underground. It is estimated that he saved as many as 300 Jews before his arrest in January 1942. He was executed on 13 April.\n\nAfter the war, Schmid was recognized as [[Righteous Among the Nations]] by [[Yad Vashem]] for his efforts to help Jews and was seen as a symbol of the few Germans who defied their government's extermination program. His reception was more conflicted in Germany and Austria, where he was still viewed as a traitor. The first official commemoration of him in Germany did not occur until 2000, but he is now hailed as an example of [[civil courage]] for ''[[Bundeswehr]]'' soldiers to follow.\n\n== Early life ==\nAnton Schmid was born in [[Vienna]], then [[Austria-Hungary]], on 9 January 1900. His father was a baker, and both of his parents were devout [[Roman Catholic]]s from [[Nikolsburg]], [[Moravia]] (now Mikulov, [[Czech Republic]]). They had Schmid baptized and educated him in a Catholic elementary school. After graduation, he apprenticed as an electrician.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} Schmid was drafted into the [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] in 1918{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} and survived intense battles during the [[Italian Front (World War I)|retreat from Italy]] in the final months of [[World War I]]. He became an electrician and opened a small radio shop on {{illm|Klosterneuburger Stra\u00dfe|de|Klosterneuburger_Stra\u00dfe|de|Liste_der_Stra\u00dfennamen_von_Wien/Brigittenau#K|display=1|vertical-align=sup|}}, [[Brigittenau]], Vienna where he employed two Jews. Allegedly, as a young man he was in love with a Jewish girl.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}}{{sfn|Kurier|2013}} Schmid, who was married and had one daughter,{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=1}} did not belong to any organizations besides the [[Catholic Church]].{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}}\n\nGerman historian [[Wolfram Wette]] describes him as a non-[[ideological]] [[humanitarian]] whose [[Antifascism|opposition to Nazism]] stemmed purely from his respect for human life. According to {{illm|Hermann Adler (writer)|de|Hermann_Adler_(Schriftsteller)|fr|Hermann_Adler_(\u00e9crivain)|lt=Hermann Adler}}, one of the Jews who Schmid rescued, he was a \"simple sergeant\" and \"a socially awkward man in thought and speech\" who did not read newspapers or books. Little is known about Schmid's life before [[World War II]].{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} After the [[Anschluss|German annexation of Austria]] in 1938, Schmid made a [[citizen's arrest]] of a man who broke the window of a Jewish neighbor and helped some Jewish friends escape into nearby [[Czechoslovakia]].{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}}{{sfn|Kurier|2013}} After the outbreak of war upon the [[German invasion of Poland]] in September 1939, he was drafted into the [[Heer (Wehrmacht)|German army]], but was not expected to serve on the front lines due to his age. According to Wette, he was a \"civilian in uniform\" who did not conform to military culture.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=501\u2013502}}{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|pp=246\u2013247}} At first he was stationed in Poland and Belarus.{{sfn|Priemel|2008|p=391}}\n\n==Rescue actions in Vilnius==\n{{further|The Holocaust in Lithuania|Vilna Ghetto}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-B10160, Wilna, Juden, litauischer Polizist.jpg|thumb|right|Lithuanian collaborator with Jewish prisoners, July 1941]]\n\nIn late August 1941, after the [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], he was transferred to the ''Landeswehr'' Battalion 898 in [[Vilnius]], then part of the [[Reichskommissariat Ostland]] German occupation zone. Schmid was reassigned to an office called Feldkommandantur 814, whose personnel were charged with collecting German soldiers who had been separated from their units and reassigning them.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=75}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|p=391}} Although Schmid interrogated the soldiers strictly, he sympathized with them\u2014many were in fact suffering from [[combat fatigue]]\u2014and avoided charging them with military offenses such as desertion or cowardice in the face of the enemy, which could have resulted in a death sentence.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=76}}\n\nDuring the first week of September alone, 3,700 Jews were rounded up and murdered, most at the [[Ponary massacre|Ponary killing pits]] outside of town. Schmid could see the collection point outside the window and witnessed scenes of great brutality. The first Jew who he helped was Max Salinger, a [[Polish Jew]] from [[Bielsko Biala]] fluent in Polish and German; most likely Salinger approached Schmid. Schmid gave Salinger the paybook of Private Max Huppert, a ''Wehrmacht'' soldier who had been killed, and employed him as a typewriter in the office. Salinger survived the war.{{sfn|Wette|2014|pp=75\u201376}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} The second Jew who Schmid rescued was a 23-year-old [[Lithuanian Jewish]] woman named Luisa Emaitisaite. Emaitisaite had managed to dodge the roundups one day but was caught outside the ghetto after curfew, which was punishable by death. Hiding in a doorway, she saw Schmid walking past and begged for his help. Schmid hid her in his apartment temporarily and later hired her for the office, where her knowledge of several languages and stenography was helpful. Her work permit protected her and she also survived the war.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=76}} These examples show that Schmid did not set out to help Jews, but instead that his rescue actions were driven by their appeals for help.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=75}}\n\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=25em|I want to tell you how this all came about. The Lithuanian military herded many Jews to a meadow outside of town and shot them, each time around two thousand to three thousand people. On their way they killed the children by hurling them against the trees, etc., you can imagine.|source=Anton Schmid in a letter to his family, 9 April 1942{{efn|According to Schoeps, Schmid could not say that the Germans were responsible for the massacres because of military censorship.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=503}} The full text of the letter is printed in {{harvtxt|Bartrop|2016|p=352}} and {{harvtxt|Wette|2014|p=79}}.}}}}\n\nAs part of the ''Wehrmacht'' policy of [[Nazi plunder|economic exploitation of conquered territories]], a section was added for carpentry and upholstery, which Schmid directed. Due to the lack of willing, skilled Lithuanian workers, many Jews were employed.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|pp=391\u2013392}} In October 1941, many permits were cancelled with a view to murdering many of the Jews in the ghetto. Schmid's office, with 150 Jewish workers at the time, was only allocated 15 permits, which covered 60 Jews including holders and family members.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=77}} The Jews called these certificates \"leave from death papers\" because they usually prevented the police and SS from rounding up and murdering the holders.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} The other 90 Jews begged Schmid to drive them in ''Wehrmacht'' trucks to the nearby town of [[Lida]], Belarus, where they believed that they would be safer. Schmid did so, temporarily saving them from death at Ponary, and made several trips to Lida with other Jews.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=77}} Later, Schmid managed to obtain more of these life-saving permits and eventually employed 103 Jews in various jobs.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|pp=392\u2013393}} According to testimony, Schmid treated his workers\u2014both Jews and [[German mistreatment of Soviet prisoners of war|Soviet prisoners of war]]{{sfn|Wette|2014|pp=76\u201377}}\u2014humanely and even managed to rescue some who had been taken to [[Luki\u0161k\u0117s Prison]] for execution.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}\n\nFrom November 1941 until his arrest in January, Schmid hid Hermann Adler, a Bratislava-born Jewish resistance member, and his wife Anita under false papers in Schmid's apartment in Vilnius.{{sfn|Wette|2007|p=281}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=503\u2013504}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=77}} Adler introduced Schmid to key figures in the Vilna Ghetto resistance movement, including [[Mordechai Tenenbaum]], the leader of the 1943 [[Bia\u0142ystok Ghetto uprising]], and [[Haika Grossman|Chaika Grossman]]. Schmid's apartment was used as a meeting place for Jewish partisans; during a meeting on New Year's Eve 1941, Tenenbaum made Schmid an honorary member of the Vilna Zionist Organization. Schmid, Adler, and Tenenbaum devised a plan to rescue Jews from the Vilna Ghetto by transporting them to [[Bia\u0142ystok Ghetto|Bia\u0142ystok]], Lida, and [[Grodno Ghetto|Grodno]], considered to be safer. Under the pretext that he was moving necessary Jewish workers to the places where they were most needed, he transported some 300 Jews from Vilna. Although Schmid did aid the Jewish resistance movement where he could, the partisans in the Vilna Ghetto did not have weapons at this time, so Schmid did not help armed Jewish rebels.{{sfn|Wette|2014|pp=77\u201378}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=502\u2013503}}\n\n{{quotebox|align=left|width=24em|We all must die. But if I can choose whether to die as a murderer or a helper, I choose death as a helper.|Anton Schmid in a statement to Hermann Adler{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=507}}}}\n\nBecause of his aid to the Jewish resistance movement, Schmid was arrested at the end of January 1942 and imprisoned at Stefanska Prison in Vilnius.{{sfn|Lustiger|2000}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=78}} He was sentenced to death on 25 February and executed on 13 April. The trial record does not survive, so researchers are unsure who denounced him or exactly what offenses he was charged with.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=78}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|p=402}} In his final letter to his family, Schmid wrote, \"I have just acted as a human and I did not want to hurt anyone.\"{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=503}} He was one of only three ''Wehrmacht'' soldiers who were executed for helping Jews.{{sfn|Timm|2015}} By the summer of 1942, his office no longer employed any Jews.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} It is unknown how many Jews he managed to save,{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} but the number has variously been estimated at 250{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=247}} or 300.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}}\n\n== Commemoration and legacy ==\n=== Austria ===\nAccording to Schmid's widow, many of her neighbors called her late husband a traitor and someone smashed her windows.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=505}}{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=3}} Austria did not recognize Schmid as a victim of Nazism until the late 1950s, which denied his widow and daughter financial support to which they would otherwise have been entitled.{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=3}} However, Salinger traveled to Vienna after the war and told Stefanie Schmid of what her husband had done, and attempted to support her financially.{{sfn|Kurier|2013}} In 1965, [[Simon Wiesenthal]] obtained Stefanie Schmid's address from a friend in Tel Aviv. The [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] arranged for Schmid to travel to Vilnius with her daughter and son-in-law despite Communist travel restrictions and funded a new gravestone with the inscription \"Here Rests A Man Who Thought It Was More Important To Help His Fellow Man Than To Live\".{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=505}} On 11 December 1990, a memorial plaque was erected outside his home in Vienna and unveiled by Mayor [[Helmut Zilk]]. A street in Vienna was named after him in March 2003,{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=504}} and ''[[Kurier]]'' described him as \"Austria's [[Oskar Schindler]]\".{{sfn|Kurier|2013}}\n\nIn January 2020 the [[Rossauer Barracks]] has been renamed to [[Robert Bernardis|Bernardis]]-Schmid-Kaserne.<ref>https://science.orf.at/stories/2997923</ref>\n\n=== Israel ===\n{{quotebox|width=30em|align=left|During the few minutes it took Kovner to tell of the help that had come from a German sergeant, a hush settled over the courtroom; it was as though the crowd had spontaneously decided to observe the usual two minutes of silence in honor of the man named Anton Schmid. And in those two minutes, which were like a sudden burst of light in the midst of impenetrable, unfathomable darkness, a single thought stood out clearly, irrefutably, beyond question \u2013 how utterly different everything would be today in this courtroom, in Israel, in Germany, in all of Europe, and perhaps in all countries of the world, if only more such stories could have been told.|source=[[Hannah Arendt]], ''[[Eichmann in Jerusalem]]''{{sfn|Wette|2007|pp=279\u2013280}}}}\n\nA report on Schmid's New Year's Eve meeting with Jewish resistance members was carried by Jewish courier Lonka Koziebrodzka to the [[Warsaw Ghetto]] and preserved in the [[Ringelblum Archive]]. Already Schmid was described as one of the \u05d7\u05b2\u05e1\u05b4\u05d9\u05d3\u05b5\u05d9 \u05d0\u05bb\u05de\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea  \u05d4\u05b8\u05e2\u05d5\u05b9\u05dc\u05b8\u05dd (khasidei um\u00f3t ha'ol\u00e1m, \"[[Righteous Among the Nations]]\").<ref name=milestones>{{cite web |title=The Promise. \"A Golden Star of David\" {{!}} Milestones {{!}} A Tribute to the Righteous Among the Nations |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/yv/en/exhibitions/righteous/milestone01.asp |publisher=Yad Vashem |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> The first published account of Schmid's rescue was in the prose poem ''Ges\u00e4nge aus der Stadt des Todes'' (\"Songs from the City of Death\"), published in 1945 in Switzerland by Hermann Adler, who dedicated chapter eight to Schmid. Adler stated that the Jews in the ghetto said [[Mourner's Kaddish|Kaddish]] for Schmid. According to Schoeps, Adler describes Schmid's rescue activities \"in the manner of a saintly legend\".{{sfn|Wette|2007|p=281}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=504}} Testimony about him from Tenenbaum and [[Yitzhak Zuckerman]] was included in the [[Scrolls of Fire]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Anton Schmid as described by the leaders of Jewish resistance |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/righteous/stories/schmid/tenenbaum-testimony.html |publisher=[[Yad Vashem]] |accessdate=17 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Abba Kovner]], a former member of the Vilna Ghetto resistance, testified about Schmid at the trial of Nazi war criminal [[Adolf Eichmann]]. It was from Schmid that Kovner first heard of Eichmann; Schmid told Kovner that he had heard a rumor that \"there is one dog called Eichmann and he arranges everything\". Kovner emphasized that Schmid had offered his help selflessly, without accepting any payment.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=504}} In 1964, [[Yad Vashem]], the official Israeli memorial to the Holocaust, awarded Schmid recognition as Righteous among the Nations for his efforts to save Jewish lives during the Holocaust.<ref>{{cite web |title=Anton Schmid |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/righteous/stories/schmid.html |publisher=[[Yad Vashem]] |accessdate=17 October 2018 |ref=yad |language=en}}</ref> His widow traveled to Jerusalem for the ceremony and planted a tree in the [[Garden of the Righteous Among the Nations|Garden of the Righteous]].{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=248}}<ref name=milestones/> Schmid was one of the first Germans or Austrians to be bestowed with this honor.{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=4}} Many Jews, including [[Simon Wiesenthal]], have described Schmid as \"like a saint\".{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=4}}\n\n=== Germany ===\nThe ''[[Bundeswehr]]''{{`s}} first official commemoration of a German soldier who had risked his life to save Jews during the Holocaust occurred on 8 May 2000, when it renamed a military base in [[Rendsburg]] \"{{ill|Feldwebel-Schmid-Kaserne|de}}\" in honor of his courage. Schmid's name replaced that of General [[G\u00fcnther R\u00fcdel]], a German officer who fought in both world wars and sat as an honorary judge in Nazi [[People's Court (Germany)|People's Courts]], which delivered summary verdicts ordering the execution of thousands of people following the [[20 July plot]] to assassinate [[Adolf Hitler]].{{sfn|Torgovnick|2008|p=159}}{{sfn|Cohen|2000}}{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=248}} However, later research found that R\u00fcdel had only overseen one trial and advocated for acquittal.{{sfn|Wette|2007|p=279}} The renaming represented a sea change in German attitudes towards the ''Wehrmacht''{{`s}} role in the war that coincided with the opening of a [[Wehrmacht exhibition|controversial exhibition]] focusing on [[Wehrmacht criminality|''Wehrmacht'' criminality]].{{sfn|Torgovnick|2008|p=159}}{{sfn|Cohen|2000}}{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=248}}\n\nBy invitation of German Federal Minister of Defense [[Rudolf Scharping]], President [[Heinz Fischer]] attended the barracks naming ceremony as President of the National Council of Austria in Rendsburg. Scharping praised Schmid's \"bravery and courage\" and stated that he is a new example for the German soldier of today. In an indication of how disobedience to Nazi authorities was still a sensitive subject in Germany, he added that: \"We are not free to choose our history, but we can choose the examples we take from that history.\" The commanding officer protested the removal of R\u00fcdel's name and refused to attend.{{sfn|Cohen|2000}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=505}} American historian [[Fritz Stern]] wrote that honoring Schmid \"strengthens our democratic spirit\" and is a repudiation of postwar attitudes in which German resistance was taboo.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=505\u2013506}} The barracks was closed down in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spurensuche/Feldwebel-Schmid-Kaserne |url=https://www.oksh.de/mitmachen/lernen/medienkompetenz-mk-fuer-schule/spurensuche/spurensucheortsliste/spurensuchefeldwebel-schmid-kaserne/ |website=Offener Kanal Schleswig-Holstein |accessdate=20 October 2018 |language=de}}</ref> On 22 June 2016 the Bundeswehr barracks in [[Blankenburg (Harz)]] were named after Schmid.{{sfn|Scheidl|2016}}\n\nAccording to Schoeps, Schmid is \"probably the most remarkable\" of all the ''Wehrmacht'' rescuers in Vilnius, because he not only helped Jewish refugees but furthered Jewish resistance. Other ''Wehrmacht'' rescuers, such as Major [[Karl Plagge]], worked within the system to save Jews.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}} Wolfram Wette described Schmid as \"one of the gold grains hidden under the heap of rubble\"{{efn|{{lang-de|zu den Goldk\u00f6rnen geh\u00f6rt, die unter dem grossen Schutthaufen}}}} in the history of Nazi Germany, as there were so few Germans willing to risk their lives to help Jews. According to Wette, Schmid brings a \"message of courageous humanity\"{{efn|{{lang-de|Botschaft der mutigen Menschlichkeit}}}} that can serve as a guide for Germany's present and future.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=78}} Schmid was profiled in a [[Canton of Lucerne]] publication focusing on people who have exhibited [[civil courage]].{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} {{As of|2009}}, the Third Reich's treason convictions of ''Wehrmacht'' soldiers have not been annulled.{{sfn|Deggerich|2009}}\n\n<gallery caption=\"Memorials for Anton Schmid\" widths=\"200px\" heights=\"180px\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Anton Schmid tree.jpg|Tree in the [[Garden of the Righteous Among the Nations|Garden of the Righteous]]\nFile:AntonSchmidUnteroffizier.11A.JPG|Sign at a memorial event in Austria in 2011\nFile:Anton Schmid roundabout, Haifa.jpg|Roundabout in [[Haifa]], Israel\nFile:Ruedel Kaserne Haupteingang.jpg|Feldwebel-Schmid-Kaserne, [[Rendsburg]], Germany\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|22em}}\n'''Print sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bartrop |first1=Paul R. |authorlink1=Paul R. Bartrop |title=Resisting the Holocaust: Upstanders, Partisans, and Survivors |date=2016 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |isbn=9781610698788 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Resisting_the_Holocaust.html?id=iLbyjgEACAAJ |language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Priemel |first1=Kim C. |title=Into the grey zone: Wehrmacht bystanders, German labor market policy and the Holocaust |journal=[[Journal of Genocide Research]] |date=September 2008 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=389\u2013411 |doi=10.1080/14623520802305743 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Schoeps |first1=Karl-Heinz |title=Holocaust and Resistance in Vilnius: Rescuers in \"Wehrmacht\" Uniforms |journal=[[German Studies Review]] |date=2008 |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=489\u2013512 |ref=harv|jstor=27668589 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Torgovnick |first1=Marianna |title=The War Complex: World War II in Our Time |date=2008 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=9780226808796 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZiU0YLUqn0AC |language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | title = The Wehrmacht: History, Myth, Reality | last = Wette | first = Wolfram|authorlink=Wolfram Wette | location = Cambridge, Mass. | publisher = Harvard University Press | year = 2007 | isbn = 9780674025776|ref=harv| title-link = The Wehrmacht: History, Myth, Reality }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wette |first1=Wolfram|editor-last=M\u00fcller|editor-first=Julia |title=Menschen mit Zivilcourage. Mut, Widerstand und verantwortliches Handeln in Geschichte und Gegenwart|trans-title=People with civil courage. Courage, resistance and responsible action in past and present |date=2014 |pages=74\u201382 |chapter-url=https://27-januar.lu.ch/-/media/27_Januar/Dokumente/Menschen_mit_Zivilcourage_2015/Zivilcourage_Inhalt_09_Wette_Anton_Schmid.pdf |ref=harv |language=de |chapter=Ein Judenratter aus der Wehrmacht. Feldwebel Anton Schmid (1900\u20131942)|trans-chapter=A rescuer of Jews from the Wehrmacht. Sergeant Anton Schmid (1900\u20131942)|location=Lucerne|publisher=[[Kanton Luzern]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Web sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Roger|authorlink=Roger Cohen |title=New Model For Soldiers In Germany |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/09/world/new-model-for-soldiers-in-germany.html|date=9 May 2000 |accessdate=17 October 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en|ref =harv}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Jeanrond |first1=Werner |authorlink1=Werner Jeanrond |title=Some Modern Saints? Anton Schmid (1900\u201342) |url=http://trinitycollegechapel.com/media/filestore/sermons/JeanrondSchmid201013.pdf |publisher=[[Trinity College Cambridge]] |ref=harv |date=20 October 2013}}\n*{{cite news |title=\u00d6sterreichs \"Oskar Schindler\"|trans-title=Austria's Oskar Schindler |url=https://kurier.at/chronik/oesterreich/anton-schmid-oesterreichs-oskar-schindler/24.898.536 |accessdate=20 October 2018 |work=[[Kurier]] |date=31 August 2013 |ref={{sfnref|Kurier|2013}} |language=de}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Lustiger |first1=Arno |title=Feldwebel Anton Schmid |url=http://www.rsw.hd.bw.schule.de/shal/people/aschmid.htm |accessdate=20 October 2018 |work=www.rsw.hd.bw.schule.de |date=3 June 2000 |ref=harv |language=de}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Scheidl |first1=Hans Werner |title=Der Gerechte: Feldwebel Schmid wird Namenspatron|trans-title=The Righteous: Sergeant Schmid is named patron |url=https://diepresse.com/home/zeitgeschichte/5012613/Der-Gerechte_Feldwebel-Schmid-wird-Namenspatron |accessdate=19 October 2018 |work=[[Die Presse]] |date=10 June 2016 |language=de|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web\n  | website=[[Badische Zeitung]]\n  |last=Timm\n  |first=Sylvia  \n  | url = http://www.badische-zeitung.de/waldkirch/verdienstorden-der-bundesrepublik-fuer-historiker-wolfram-wette--104266163.html\n  | archiveurl = \n  | archivedate = \n  | title = Verdienstorden der Bundesrepublik f\u00fcr Historiker Wolfram Wette\n  |trans-title=Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany for Historian Wolfram Wette\n  | date = 4 May 2015\n  | access-date = 22 December 2016\n  | language =\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n*{{cite news |last1=Deggerich |first1=Markus |title=The Last Taboo: Will Germany Finally Rehabilitate Nazi-Era 'Traitors'? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/the-last-taboo-will-germany-finally-rehabilitate-nazi-era-traitors-a-604076.html |accessdate=20 October 2018 |work=Spiegel Online |date=28 January 2009 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commonscat|Anton Schmid (Unteroffizier)|Anton Schmid}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wette |first1=Wolfram |authorlink1=Wolfram Wette |title=Feldwebel Anton Schmid: ein Held der Humanit\u00e4t|trans-title=Sergeant Anton Schmid: a Hero of Humanity |date=2013 |publisher=S. Fischer |location=Frankfurt am Main |isbn=978-3-10-091209-1 |language=de}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wieninger |first1=Manfred |title=Die Banalit\u00e4t des Guten: Feldwebel Anton Schmid|trans-title=The banality of good: Sergeant Anton Schmid |date=2014 |publisher=Theodor Kramer Gesellschaft |isbn=9783901602566 |edition=1. |language=de}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Holocaust Lithuania}}\n{{Righteous footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmid, Anton}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:Austro-Hungarian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Austrian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Austrian Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Executed German Resistance members]]\n[[Category:Austrian people executed by Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Electricians]]\n[[Category:Austrian Catholics]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholics in the German Resistance]]\n[[Category:Catholic Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Moravian-German descent]]\n[[Category:People from Brigittenau]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:People executed for treason against Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n |honorific_prefix = \n |name             = Anton Schmid\n |honorific_suffix = \n |image            = Anton-Schmid- low res.tif\n |image_upright    = \n |alt              = \n |birth_date       = {{birth date|1900|01|09|df=y}} \n |birth_place      = [[Vienna]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n |death_date       = {{death date and age|1942|4|13|1900|01|09|df=y}}\n |death_place      = Stefanska Prison, [[Vilnius]], [[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]\n |death_cause      = Convicted by a military court and executed\n |placeofburial    = \n |placeofburial_label = \n |placeofburial_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}}-->\n |awards           = [[Righteous Among the Nations]]\n |known_for        = [[Rescuers of Jews during the Holocaust|Saving Jews during the Holocaust]]\n |spouse           = Stefanie Schmid\n |children         = Gerta Schmid\n |occupation       = Electrician\n |module           = {{Infobox military person | embed = yes\n|allegiance       = \n|branch           = {{army|Austria-Hungary}}<br>{{army|Nazi Germany}}\n|branch_label     = Branch\n|serviceyears     = 1918<br>1939\u20131942\n|serviceyears_label = \n|rank             = ''[[Feldwebel]]''\n|rank_label       = \n|servicenumber    = \n|unit             = ''Landeswehr'' Battalion 898<br>Feldkommandantur 814\n|commands         = \n|battles          = [[World War I]]\n*[[Italian front (World War I)|Italian front]]\n{{hr}}[[World War II]]\n|battles_label    = \n|awards           = \n}}\n}}\n'''Anton Schmid''' (9 January 1900 \u2013 13 April 1942) was an Austrian recruit in the ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' who saved Jews during the [[Holocaust in Lithuania]]. A devout but apolitical Roman Catholic and an electrician by profession, Schmid was conscripted into the [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] during [[World War I]] and later into the ''Wehrmacht'' during [[World War II]]. Put in charge of an office to return stranded German soldiers to their units in late August 1941, he began to help Jews after being approached by two pleading for his intercession. Schmid hid Jews in his apartment, obtained work permits to save Jews from the [[Ponary massacre]], transferred Jews in ''Wehrmacht'' trucks to safer locations, and aided the [[Vilna Ghetto]] underground. It is estimated that he saved as many as 300 Jews before his arrest in January 1942. He was executed on 13 April.\n\nAfter the war, Schmid was recognized as [[Righteous Among the Nations]] by [[Yad Vashem]] for his efforts to help Jews and was seen as a symbol of the few Germans who defied their government's extermination program. His reception was more conflicted in Germany and Austria, where he was still viewed as a traitor. The first official commemoration of him in Germany did not occur until 2000, but he is now hailed as an example of [[civil courage]] for ''[[Bundeswehr]]'' soldiers to follow.\n\n== Early life ==\nAnton Schmid was born in [[Vienna]], then [[Austria-Hungary]], on 9 January 1900. His father was a baker, and both of his parents were devout [[Roman Catholic]]s from [[Nikolsburg]], [[Moravia]] (now Mikulov, [[Czech Republic]]). They had Schmid baptized and educated him in a Catholic elementary school. After graduation, he apprenticed as an electrician.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} Schmid was drafted into the [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] in 1918{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} and survived intense battles during the [[Italian Front (World War I)|retreat from Italy]] in the final months of [[World War I]]. He became an electrician and opened a small radio shop on {{illm|Klosterneuburger Stra\u00dfe|de|Klosterneuburger_Stra\u00dfe|de|Liste_der_Stra\u00dfennamen_von_Wien/Brigittenau#K|display=1|vertical-align=sup|}}, [[Brigittenau]], Vienna where he employed two Jews. Allegedly, as a young man he was in love with a Jewish girl.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}}{{sfn|Kurier|2013}} Schmid, who was married and had one daughter,{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=1}} did not belong to any organizations besides the [[Catholic Church]].{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}}\n\nGerman historian [[Wolfram Wette]] describes him as a non-[[ideological]] [[humanitarian]] whose [[Antifascism|opposition to Nazism]] stemmed purely from his respect for human life. According to {{illm|Hermann Adler (writer)|de|Hermann_Adler_(Schriftsteller)|fr|Hermann_Adler_(\u00e9crivain)|lt=Hermann Adler}}, one of the Jews who Schmid rescued, he was a \"simple sergeant\" and \"a socially awkward man in thought and speech\" who did not read newspapers or books. Little is known about Schmid's life before [[World War II]].{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} After the [[Anschluss|German annexation of Austria]] in 1938, Schmid made a [[citizen's arrest]] of a man who broke the window of a Jewish neighbor and helped some Jewish friends escape into nearby [[Czechoslovakia]].{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}}{{sfn|Kurier|2013}} After the outbreak of war upon the [[German invasion of Poland]] in September 1939, he was drafted into the [[Heer (Wehrmacht)|German army]], but was not expected to serve on the front lines due to his age. According to Wette, he was a \"civilian in uniform\" who did not conform to military culture.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=501\u2013502}}{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|pp=246\u2013247}} At first he was stationed in Poland and Belarus.{{sfn|Priemel|2008|p=391}}\n\n==Rescue actions in Vilnius==\n{{further|The Holocaust in Lithuania|Vilna Ghetto}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-B10160, Wilna, Juden, litauischer Polizist.jpg|thumb|right|Lithuanian collaborator with Jewish prisoners, July 1941]]\n\nIn late August 1941, after the [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], he was transferred to the ''Landeswehr'' Battalion 898 in [[Vilnius]], then part of the [[Reichskommissariat Ostland]] German occupation zone. Schmid was reassigned to an office called Feldkommandantur 814, whose personnel were charged with collecting German soldiers who had been separated from their units and reassigning them.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=75}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|p=391}} Although Schmid interrogated the soldiers strictly, he sympathized with them\u2014many were in fact suffering from [[combat fatigue]]\u2014and avoided charging them with military offenses such as desertion or cowardice in the face of the enemy, which could have resulted in a death sentence.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=76}}\n\nDuring the first week of September alone, 3,700 Jews were rounded up and murdered, most at the [[Ponary massacre|Ponary killing pits]] outside of town. Schmid could see the collection point outside the window and witnessed scenes of great brutality. The first Jew who he helped was Max Salinger, a [[Polish Jew]] from [[Bielsko Biala]] fluent in Polish and German; most likely Salinger approached Schmid. Schmid gave Salinger the paybook of Private Max Huppert, a ''Wehrmacht'' soldier who had been killed, and employed him as a typewriter in the office. Salinger survived the war.{{sfn|Wette|2014|pp=75\u201376}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} The second Jew who Schmid rescued was a 23-year-old [[Lithuanian Jewish]] woman named Luisa Emaitisaite. Emaitisaite had managed to dodge the roundups one day but was caught outside the ghetto after curfew, which was punishable by death. Hiding in a doorway, she saw Schmid walking past and begged for his help. Schmid hid her in his apartment temporarily and later hired her for the office, where her knowledge of several languages and stenography was helpful. Her work permit protected her and she also survived the war.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=76}} These examples show that Schmid did not set out to help Jews, but instead that his rescue actions were driven by their appeals for help.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=75}}\n\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=25em|I want to tell you how this all came about. The Lithuanian military herded many Jews to a meadow outside of town and shot them, each time around two thousand to three thousand people. On their way they killed the children by hurling them against the trees, etc., you can imagine.|source=Anton Schmid in a letter to his family, 9 April 1942{{efn|According to Schoeps, Schmid could not say that the Germans were responsible for the massacres because of military censorship.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=503}} The full text of the letter is printed in {{harvtxt|Bartrop|2016|p=352}} and {{harvtxt|Wette|2014|p=79}}.}}}}\n\nAs part of the ''Wehrmacht'' policy of [[Nazi plunder|economic exploitation of conquered territories]], a section was added for carpentry and upholstery, which Schmid directed. Due to the lack of willing, skilled Lithuanian workers, many Jews were employed.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|pp=391\u2013392}} In October 1941, many permits were cancelled with a view to murdering many of the Jews in the ghetto. Schmid's office, with 150 Jewish workers at the time, was only allocated 15 permits, which covered 60 Jews including holders and family members.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=77}} The Jews called these certificates \"leave from death papers\" because they usually prevented the police and SS from rounding up and murdering the holders.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} The other 90 Jews begged Schmid to drive them in ''Wehrmacht'' trucks to the nearby town of [[Lida]], Belarus, where they believed that they would be safer. Schmid did so, temporarily saving them from death at Ponary, and made several trips to Lida with other Jews.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=77}} Later, Schmid managed to obtain more of these life-saving permits and eventually employed 103 Jews in various jobs.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|pp=392\u2013393}} According to testimony, Schmid treated his workers\u2014both Jews and [[German mistreatment of Soviet prisoners of war|Soviet prisoners of war]]{{sfn|Wette|2014|pp=76\u201377}}\u2014humanely and even managed to rescue some who had been taken to [[Luki\u0161k\u0117s Prison]] for execution.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}\n\nFrom November 1941 until his arrest in January, Schmid hid Hermann Adler, a Bratislava-born Jewish resistance member, and his wife Anita under false papers in Schmid's apartment in Vilnius.{{sfn|Wette|2007|p=281}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=503\u2013504}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=77}} Adler introduced Schmid to key figures in the Vilna Ghetto resistance movement, including [[Mordechai Tenenbaum]], the leader of the 1943 [[Bia\u0142ystok Ghetto uprising]], and [[Haika Grossman|Chaika Grossman]]. Schmid's apartment was used as a meeting place for Jewish partisans; during a meeting on New Year's Eve 1941, Tenenbaum made Schmid an honorary member of the Vilna Zionist Organization. Schmid, Adler, and Tenenbaum devised a plan to rescue Jews from the Vilna Ghetto by transporting them to [[Bia\u0142ystok Ghetto|Bia\u0142ystok]], Lida, and [[Grodno Ghetto|Grodno]], considered to be safer. Under the pretext that he was moving necessary Jewish workers to the places where they were most needed, he transported some 300 Jews from Vilna. Although Schmid did aid the Jewish resistance movement where he could, the partisans in the Vilna Ghetto did not have weapons at this time, so Schmid did not help armed Jewish rebels.{{sfn|Wette|2014|pp=77\u201378}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=502\u2013503}}\n\n{{quotebox|align=left|width=24em|We all must die. But if I can choose whether to die as a murderer or a helper, I choose death as a helper.|Anton Schmid in a statement to Hermann Adler{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=507}}}}\n\nBecause of his aid to the Jewish resistance movement, Schmid was arrested at the end of January 1942 and imprisoned at Stefanska Prison in Vilnius.{{sfn|Lustiger|2000}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=78}} He was sentenced to death on 25 February and executed on 13 April. The trial record does not survive, so researchers are unsure who denounced him or exactly what offenses he was charged with.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}}{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=78}}{{sfn|Priemel|2008|p=402}} In his final letter to his family, Schmid wrote, \"I have just acted as a human and I did not want to hurt anyone.\"{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=503}} He was one of only three ''Wehrmacht'' soldiers who were executed for helping Jews.{{sfn|Timm|2015}} By the summer of 1942, his office no longer employed any Jews.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} It is unknown how many Jews he managed to save,{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=502}} but the number has variously been estimated at 250{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=247}} or 300.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}}\n\n== Commemoration and legacy ==\n=== Austria ===\nAccording to Schmid's widow, many of her neighbors called her late husband a traitor and someone smashed her windows.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=505}}{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=3}} Austria did not recognize Schmid as a victim of Nazism until the late 1950s, which denied his widow and daughter financial support to which they would otherwise have been entitled.{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=3}} However, Salinger traveled to Vienna after the war and told Stefanie Schmid of what her husband had done, and attempted to support her financially.{{sfn|Kurier|2013}} In 1965, [[Simon Wiesenthal]] obtained Stefanie Schmid's address from a friend in Tel Aviv. The [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] arranged for Schmid to travel to Vilnius with her daughter and son-in-law despite Communist travel restrictions and funded a new gravestone with the inscription \"Here Rests A Man Who Thought It Was More Important To Help His Fellow Man Than To Live\".{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=505}} On 11 December 1990, a memorial plaque was erected outside his home in Vienna and unveiled by Mayor [[Helmut Zilk]]. A street in Vienna was named after him in March 2003,{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=504}} and ''[[Kurier]]'' described him as \"Austria's [[Oskar Schindler]]\".{{sfn|Kurier|2013}}\n\nIn January 2020 the [[Rossauer Barracks]] has been renamed to [[Robert Bernardis|Bernardis]]-Schmid-Kaserne<ref>https://science.orf.at/stories/2997923</ref>.\n\n=== Israel ===\n{{quotebox|width=30em|align=left|During the few minutes it took Kovner to tell of the help that had come from a German sergeant, a hush settled over the courtroom; it was as though the crowd had spontaneously decided to observe the usual two minutes of silence in honor of the man named Anton Schmid. And in those two minutes, which were like a sudden burst of light in the midst of impenetrable, unfathomable darkness, a single thought stood out clearly, irrefutably, beyond question \u2013 how utterly different everything would be today in this courtroom, in Israel, in Germany, in all of Europe, and perhaps in all countries of the world, if only more such stories could have been told.|source=[[Hannah Arendt]], ''[[Eichmann in Jerusalem]]''{{sfn|Wette|2007|pp=279\u2013280}}}}\n\nA report on Schmid's New Year's Eve meeting with Jewish resistance members was carried by Jewish courier Lonka Koziebrodzka to the [[Warsaw Ghetto]] and preserved in the [[Ringelblum Archive]]. Already Schmid was described as one of the \u05d7\u05b2\u05e1\u05b4\u05d9\u05d3\u05b5\u05d9 \u05d0\u05bb\u05de\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea  \u05d4\u05b8\u05e2\u05d5\u05b9\u05dc\u05b8\u05dd (khasidei um\u00f3t ha'ol\u00e1m, \"[[Righteous Among the Nations]]\").<ref name=milestones>{{cite web |title=The Promise. \"A Golden Star of David\" {{!}} Milestones {{!}} A Tribute to the Righteous Among the Nations |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/yv/en/exhibitions/righteous/milestone01.asp |publisher=Yad Vashem |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> The first published account of Schmid's rescue was in the prose poem ''Ges\u00e4nge aus der Stadt des Todes'' (\"Songs from the City of Death\"), published in 1945 in Switzerland by Hermann Adler, who dedicated chapter eight to Schmid. Adler stated that the Jews in the ghetto said [[Mourner's Kaddish|Kaddish]] for Schmid. According to Schoeps, Adler describes Schmid's rescue activities \"in the manner of a saintly legend\".{{sfn|Wette|2007|p=281}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=504}} Testimony about him from Tenenbaum and [[Yitzhak Zuckerman]] was included in the [[Scrolls of Fire]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Anton Schmid as described by the leaders of Jewish resistance |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/righteous/stories/schmid/tenenbaum-testimony.html |publisher=[[Yad Vashem]] |accessdate=17 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Abba Kovner]], a former member of the Vilna Ghetto resistance, testified about Schmid at the trial of Nazi war criminal [[Adolf Eichmann]]. It was from Schmid that Kovner first heard of Eichmann; Schmid told Kovner that he had heard a rumor that \"there is one dog called Eichmann and he arranges everything\". Kovner emphasized that Schmid had offered his help selflessly, without accepting any payment.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=504}} In 1964, [[Yad Vashem]], the official Israeli memorial to the Holocaust, awarded Schmid recognition as Righteous among the Nations for his efforts to save Jewish lives during the Holocaust.<ref>{{cite web |title=Anton Schmid |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/righteous/stories/schmid.html |publisher=[[Yad Vashem]] |accessdate=17 October 2018 |ref=yad |language=en}}</ref> His widow traveled to Jerusalem for the ceremony and planted a tree in the [[Garden of the Righteous Among the Nations|Garden of the Righteous]].{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=248}}<ref name=milestones/> Schmid was one of the first Germans or Austrians to be bestowed with this honor.{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=4}} Many Jews, including [[Simon Wiesenthal]], have described Schmid as \"like a saint\".{{sfn|Jeanrond|2013|p=4}}\n\n=== Germany ===\nThe ''[[Bundeswehr]]''{{`s}} first official commemoration of a German soldier who had risked his life to save Jews during the Holocaust occurred on 8 May 2000, when it renamed a military base in [[Rendsburg]] \"{{ill|Feldwebel-Schmid-Kaserne|de}}\" in honor of his courage. Schmid's name replaced that of General [[G\u00fcnther R\u00fcdel]], a German officer who fought in both world wars and sat as an honorary judge in Nazi [[People's Court (Germany)|People's Courts]], which delivered summary verdicts ordering the execution of thousands of people following the [[20 July plot]] to assassinate [[Adolf Hitler]].{{sfn|Torgovnick|2008|p=159}}{{sfn|Cohen|2000}}{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=248}} However, later research found that R\u00fcdel had only overseen one trial and advocated for acquittal.{{sfn|Wette|2007|p=279}} The renaming represented a sea change in German attitudes towards the ''Wehrmacht''{{`s}} role in the war that coincided with the opening of a [[Wehrmacht exhibition|controversial exhibition]] focusing on [[Wehrmacht criminality|''Wehrmacht'' criminality]].{{sfn|Torgovnick|2008|p=159}}{{sfn|Cohen|2000}}{{sfn|Bartrop|2016|p=248}}\n\nBy invitation of German Federal Minister of Defense [[Rudolf Scharping]], President [[Heinz Fischer]] attended the barracks naming ceremony as President of the National Council of Austria in Rendsburg. Scharping praised Schmid's \"bravery and courage\" and stated that he is a new example for the German soldier of today. In an indication of how disobedience to Nazi authorities was still a sensitive subject in Germany, he added that: \"We are not free to choose our history, but we can choose the examples we take from that history.\" The commanding officer protested the removal of R\u00fcdel's name and refused to attend.{{sfn|Cohen|2000}}{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=505}} American historian [[Fritz Stern]] wrote that honoring Schmid \"strengthens our democratic spirit\" and is a repudiation of postwar attitudes in which German resistance was taboo.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|pp=505\u2013506}} The barracks was closed down in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spurensuche/Feldwebel-Schmid-Kaserne |url=https://www.oksh.de/mitmachen/lernen/medienkompetenz-mk-fuer-schule/spurensuche/spurensucheortsliste/spurensuchefeldwebel-schmid-kaserne/ |website=Offener Kanal Schleswig-Holstein |accessdate=20 October 2018 |language=de}}</ref> On 22 June 2016 the Bundeswehr barracks in [[Blankenburg (Harz)]] were named after Schmid.{{sfn|Scheidl|2016}}\n\nAccording to Schoeps, Schmid is \"probably the most remarkable\" of all the ''Wehrmacht'' rescuers in Vilnius, because he not only helped Jewish refugees but furthered Jewish resistance. Other ''Wehrmacht'' rescuers, such as Major [[Karl Plagge]], worked within the system to save Jews.{{sfn|Schoeps|2008|p=501}} Wolfram Wette described Schmid as \"one of the gold grains hidden under the heap of rubble\"{{efn|{{lang-de|zu den Goldk\u00f6rnen geh\u00f6rt, die unter dem grossen Schutthaufen}}}} in the history of Nazi Germany, as there were so few Germans willing to risk their lives to help Jews. According to Wette, Schmid brings a \"message of courageous humanity\"{{efn|{{lang-de|Botschaft der mutigen Menschlichkeit}}}} that can serve as a guide for Germany's present and future.{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=78}} Schmid was profiled in a [[Canton of Lucerne]] publication focusing on people who have exhibited [[civil courage]].{{sfn|Wette|2014|p=74}} {{As of|2009}}, the Third Reich's treason convictions of ''Wehrmacht'' soldiers have not been annulled.{{sfn|Deggerich|2009}}\n\n<gallery caption=\"Memorials for Anton Schmid\" widths=\"200px\" heights=\"180px\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Anton Schmid tree.jpg|Tree in the [[Garden of the Righteous Among the Nations|Garden of the Righteous]]\nFile:AntonSchmidUnteroffizier.11A.JPG|Sign at a memorial event in Austria in 2011\nFile:Anton Schmid roundabout, Haifa.jpg|Roundabout in [[Haifa]], Israel\nFile:Ruedel Kaserne Haupteingang.jpg|Feldwebel-Schmid-Kaserne, [[Rendsburg]], Germany\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|22em}}\n'''Print sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bartrop |first1=Paul R. |authorlink1=Paul R. Bartrop |title=Resisting the Holocaust: Upstanders, Partisans, and Survivors |date=2016 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |isbn=9781610698788 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Resisting_the_Holocaust.html?id=iLbyjgEACAAJ |language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Priemel |first1=Kim C. |title=Into the grey zone: Wehrmacht bystanders, German labor market policy and the Holocaust |journal=[[Journal of Genocide Research]] |date=September 2008 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=389\u2013411 |doi=10.1080/14623520802305743 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Schoeps |first1=Karl-Heinz |title=Holocaust and Resistance in Vilnius: Rescuers in \"Wehrmacht\" Uniforms |journal=[[German Studies Review]] |date=2008 |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=489\u2013512 |ref=harv|jstor=27668589 }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Torgovnick |first1=Marianna |title=The War Complex: World War II in Our Time |date=2008 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |isbn=9780226808796 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZiU0YLUqn0AC |language=en|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | title = The Wehrmacht: History, Myth, Reality | last = Wette | first = Wolfram|authorlink=Wolfram Wette | location = Cambridge, Mass. | publisher = Harvard University Press | year = 2007 | isbn = 9780674025776|ref=harv| title-link = The Wehrmacht: History, Myth, Reality }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wette |first1=Wolfram|editor-last=M\u00fcller|editor-first=Julia |title=Menschen mit Zivilcourage. Mut, Widerstand und verantwortliches Handeln in Geschichte und Gegenwart|trans-title=People with civil courage. Courage, resistance and responsible action in past and present |date=2014 |pages=74\u201382 |chapter-url=https://27-januar.lu.ch/-/media/27_Januar/Dokumente/Menschen_mit_Zivilcourage_2015/Zivilcourage_Inhalt_09_Wette_Anton_Schmid.pdf |ref=harv |language=de |chapter=Ein Judenratter aus der Wehrmacht. Feldwebel Anton Schmid (1900\u20131942)|trans-chapter=A rescuer of Jews from the Wehrmacht. Sergeant Anton Schmid (1900\u20131942)|location=Lucerne|publisher=[[Kanton Luzern]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Web sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Roger|authorlink=Roger Cohen |title=New Model For Soldiers In Germany |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/09/world/new-model-for-soldiers-in-germany.html|date=9 May 2000 |accessdate=17 October 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en|ref =harv}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Jeanrond |first1=Werner |authorlink1=Werner Jeanrond |title=Some Modern Saints? Anton Schmid (1900\u201342) |url=http://trinitycollegechapel.com/media/filestore/sermons/JeanrondSchmid201013.pdf |publisher=[[Trinity College Cambridge]] |ref=harv |date=20 October 2013}}\n*{{cite news |title=\u00d6sterreichs \"Oskar Schindler\"|trans-title=Austria's Oskar Schindler |url=https://kurier.at/chronik/oesterreich/anton-schmid-oesterreichs-oskar-schindler/24.898.536 |accessdate=20 October 2018 |work=[[Kurier]] |date=31 August 2013 |ref={{sfnref|Kurier|2013}} |language=de}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Lustiger |first1=Arno |title=Feldwebel Anton Schmid |url=http://www.rsw.hd.bw.schule.de/shal/people/aschmid.htm |accessdate=20 October 2018 |work=www.rsw.hd.bw.schule.de |date=3 June 2000 |ref=harv |language=de}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Scheidl |first1=Hans Werner |title=Der Gerechte: Feldwebel Schmid wird Namenspatron|trans-title=The Righteous: Sergeant Schmid is named patron |url=https://diepresse.com/home/zeitgeschichte/5012613/Der-Gerechte_Feldwebel-Schmid-wird-Namenspatron |accessdate=19 October 2018 |work=[[Die Presse]] |date=10 June 2016 |language=de|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web\n  | website=[[Badische Zeitung]]\n  |last=Timm\n  |first=Sylvia  \n  | url = http://www.badische-zeitung.de/waldkirch/verdienstorden-der-bundesrepublik-fuer-historiker-wolfram-wette--104266163.html\n  | archiveurl = \n  | archivedate = \n  | title = Verdienstorden der Bundesrepublik f\u00fcr Historiker Wolfram Wette\n  |trans-title=Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany for Historian Wolfram Wette\n  | date = 4 May 2015\n  | access-date = 22 December 2016\n  | language =\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n*{{cite news |last1=Deggerich |first1=Markus |title=The Last Taboo: Will Germany Finally Rehabilitate Nazi-Era 'Traitors'? |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/the-last-taboo-will-germany-finally-rehabilitate-nazi-era-traitors-a-604076.html |accessdate=20 October 2018 |work=Spiegel Online |date=28 January 2009 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commonscat|Anton Schmid (Unteroffizier)|Anton Schmid}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wette |first1=Wolfram |authorlink1=Wolfram Wette |title=Feldwebel Anton Schmid: ein Held der Humanit\u00e4t|trans-title=Sergeant Anton Schmid: a Hero of Humanity |date=2013 |publisher=S. Fischer |location=Frankfurt am Main |isbn=978-3-10-091209-1 |language=de}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wieninger |first1=Manfred |title=Die Banalit\u00e4t des Guten: Feldwebel Anton Schmid|trans-title=The banality of good: Sergeant Anton Schmid |date=2014 |publisher=Theodor Kramer Gesellschaft |isbn=9783901602566 |edition=1. |language=de}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Holocaust Lithuania}}\n{{Righteous footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmid, Anton}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian people]]\n[[Category:Austro-Hungarian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Austrian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Austrian Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Executed German Resistance members]]\n[[Category:Austrian people executed by Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Electricians]]\n[[Category:Austrian Catholics]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholics in the German Resistance]]\n[[Category:Catholic Righteous Among the Nations]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Moravian-German descent]]\n[[Category:People from Brigittenau]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:People executed for treason against Germany]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton_Schmid"}
{"title_page": "Anti-Slavery Society", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Anti-Slavery Society Convention 1840|align=right|size=300px|caption=The painting of the [[World Anti-Slavery Convention (1840)|1840 Anti-Slavery Convention]] at [[Exeter Hall]]. Move your cursor to identify delegates or click the icon to enlarge.<ref name=npg>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?search=ap&npgno=599&eDate=&lDate= The Anti-Slavery Society Convention, 1840], [[Benjamin Robert Haydon]], 1841, [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]], London, NPG599, Given by [[Anti-Slavery International|British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]] in 1880</ref>}} \n{{Slavery}}\n\nThe '''Anti-Slavery Society''' was the everyday name of two different British organisations.\n\nThe first was founded in 1823 and was committed to the [[Abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolition of slavery in the British Empire]]. Its official name was the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions. This objective was substantially achieved in 1838 under the terms of the [[Slavery Abolition Act 1833]]. \n\nA successor organisation, the [[British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]], was formed in 1839 to fight for global abolition. After the end of slavery in the United States, the British organisation re-focussed. Through mergers and name changes, it is now known as [[Anti-Slavery International]].\n\n==Precursors==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2012}}\nThe elimination of [[slavery]] throughout the world was frequently in the mind of early [[Abolitionism|abolitionists]]. The committee which established the [[Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade]] in 1787 campaigned for an end to the [[Atlantic slave trade|transatlantic slave trade]] from [[Western Africa]] to [[the New World]], a trade then dominated by Britain.\n\nThe [[Slave Trade Act 1807]] made the trade illegal in the British Empire, but brought no change to the condition of enslaved people. Following this, British abolitionists turned their attention to abolishing slavery itself, first in [[British colonies]], and later in the US and the colonies of other European powers (e.g., in South America), and in parts of the world where it had long been legal, such as in the Middle East, Africa, and China.\n\n==The Anti-Slavery Society of 1823==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2012}}\n\nThe first British organisation to refer to itself as the Anti-Slavery Society began in 1823. Founding members included [[William Wilberforce]] and [[Thomas Clarkson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oup.com/oxforddnb/info/freeodnb/shelves/slavery/ |title=Slavery and abolition |publisher=Oup.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref> Its official name was the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions.\n\nIts work included supporting the first [[slave narrative]] to be published by a Black woman, [[Mary Prince]], ''The History of Mary Prince, A West Indian Slave'' (1831). The publishers were sued by the family from which she had escaped. The book was much sought after, running into three editions in the year of its publication.\n\nA wide range of views emerged among the members. Broadly, there were abolitionists who insisted on the full working out of the gradual process of abolition and amelioration (which had its successes), and the generally younger, more radical members, whose moral outlook regarded slavery as a mortal sin to be ended forthwith. [[Elizabeth Heyrick]]'s 1824 pamphlet \"Immediate, not Gradual, Abolition\" gave the tone to the argument.\n\nThe latter group, including [[Joseph Sturge]] and many others, publicly campaigned throughout Britain. The idea was to engender public pressure for a new parliamentary act to outlaw slavery, rather than continue the gradualism of Whitehall's negotiations, mainly with colonial governments. In 1831 [[George Stephen (abolitionist)|George Stephen]] and Joseph Sturge formed a [[ginger group]] within the Anti-Slavery Society, the Agency Committee, to campaign for this new act of Parliament. This campaign, and public pressure, led to the [[Slavery Abolition Act]] of 1833, though it contained compromises which they disliked.\n\nJamaican mixed-race campaigners such as [[Louis Celeste Lecesne]] and [[Richard Hill (Jamaica)]] were also members of the Anti-Slavery Society.\n\nThe [[indentured labour]] schemes were particularly opposed by Sturge and the Agency Committee; the full working out of the Act would take several years, with slavery eventually being abolished throughout the British West Indies on 1 August 1838. In response to the new legislation, other members of the Anti-Slavery Society considered their work over. The original purpose, as reflected in the name of the society (abolition in the British dominions), had, they thought, been achieved.\n\n==The Anti-Slavery Society of 1839==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2012}}\nWith abolition of slavery throughout the British dominions achieved, British abolitionists in the Agency Committee of the Anti-Slavery Society considered that a successor organisation was needed to tackle slavery worldwide. Largely under the guidance of Joseph Sturge, the committee duly formed a new society, [[British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]] on 17 April 1839.<ref>[http://www.antislavery.org/english/what_we_do/antislavery_international_today/frequently_asked_questions.aspx About Anti-Slavery International] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626074739/http://www.antislavery.org/english/what_we_do/antislavery_international_today/frequently_asked_questions.aspx |date=26 June 2010 }} antislavery.org</ref><ref>Patricia Hollis (1974). Pressure from without in early Victorian England. p.39.</ref> It became widely known as the Anti-Slavery Society, as had the earlier society.\n\nThe first secretary was [[John Harfield Tredgold]], the first treasurer, [[George William Alexander]] of [[Stoke Newington]]. Along with the founding committee, which included the Anglican [[Sir Thomas Buxton, 1st Baronet|Thomas Fowell Buxton]], the Quaker [[William Allen (Quaker)|William Allen]], and the Congregationalist [[Josiah Conder (editor and author)|Josiah Conder]], they organised the first [[World Anti-Slavery Convention]] in London in 1840. [[Thomas Clarkson]] was the key speaker, and the Convention attracted people from nations around the world where slavery was practiced. In 1944, a Journalist [[James Ewing Ritchie]] issued a paper to the society on sugar trade and slavery.<ref>Ritchie, James Ewing. 1944. ''[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/52820/52820-h/52820-h.htm Thoughts on Slavery and Cheap Sugar, a Letter to The Members and Friends of The British And Foreign Anti-Slavery Society.]''</ref>\n\nThe convention had been advertised as a \"whole world\" convention, but the delegates representing anti-slavery societies in the United States included several women, among them [[Lucretia Mott]] and [[Elizabeth Cady Stanton]], who later were instrumental in the movement for women's rights. Convention leaders refused to seat the women delegates from America, and prominent male abolitionists such as Thomas Knight were outraged. He went on to form his own society. \n\nIn the 1850s, under Louis Chamerovzow, the society helped [[John Brown (fugitive slave)|John Brown]] write and publish his autobiography a decade before the [[American Civil War]] ended slavery in the United States.\n\nThe second secretary of the Anti-Slavery Society, appointed under the honorary secretaries [[Joseph Cooper (abolitionist|Joseph Cooper]] and [[Edmund Sturge]], was the Rev. Aaron Buzacott (1829\u201381), the son of a South Seas missionary also named [[Aaron Buzacott]]. With American slavery abolished in 1865, Buzacott worked closely with Joseph Cooper in researching and publishing work designed to help abolish slavery in elsewhere, particularly in the Middle East, Turkey and Africa.\n\n==Twentieth century and now==\nIn 1909, the society merged with the [[Aborigines' Protection Society]] to form the Anti-Slavery and Aborigines' Protection Society, whose prominent member was [[Kathleen Simon, Viscountess Simon]]. In 1990 the name was changed to [[Anti-Slavery International]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[American Anti-Slavery Group]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.antislavery.org Anti-Slavery International]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930194208/http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/portrait.asp?search=sp&sText=Anti-Slavery+Society&rNo=0 Anti-Slavery Society Convention 1840]\n*[http://www.anti-slaverysociety.org Anti-Slavery Society]\n\n[[Category:Abolitionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Abolitionist organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1839]]\n[[Category:1823 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1839 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Anti-Slavery Society Convention 1840|align=right|size=300px|caption=The painting of the [[World Anti-Slavery Convention (1840)|1840 Anti-Slavery Convention]] at [[Exeter Hall]]. Move your cursor to identify delegates or click the icon to enlarge.<ref name=npg>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?search=ap&npgno=599&eDate=&lDate= The Anti-Slavery Society Convention, 1840], [[Benjamin Robert Haydon]], 1841, [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]], London, NPG599, Given by [[Anti-Slavery International|British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]] in 1880</ref>}} \n{{Slavery}}\n\nThe '''Anti-Slavery Society''' was the everyday name of two different British organisations.\n\nThe first was founded in 1823 and was committed to the [[Abolitionism in the United Kingdom|abolition of slavery in the British Empire]]. Its official name was the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions. This objective was substantially achieved in 1838 under the terms of the [[Slavery Abolition Act 1833]]. \n\nA successor organisation, the [[British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]], was formed in 1839 to fight for global abolition. After the end of slavery in the United States, the British organisation re-focussed. Through mergers and name changes, it is now known as [[Anti-Slavery International]].\n\n==Precursors==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2012}}\nThe elimination of [[slavery]] throughout the world was frequently in the mind of early [[Abolitionism|abolitionists]]. The committee which established the [[Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade]] in 1787 campaigned for an end to the [[Atlantic slave trade|transatlantic slave trade]] from [[Western Africa]] to [[the New World]], a trade then dominated by Britain.\n\nThe [[Slave Trade Act 1807]] made the trade illegal in the British Empire, but brought no change to the condition of enslaved people. Following this, British abolitionists turned their attention to abolishing slavery itself, first in [[British colonies]], and later in the US and the colonies of other European powers (e.g., in South America), and in parts of the world where it had long been legal, such as in the Middle East, Africa, and China.\n\n==The Anti-Slavery Society of 1823==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2012}}\n\nThe first British organisation to refer to itself as the Anti-Slavery Society began in 1823. Founding members included [[William Wilberforce]] and [[Thomas Clarkson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oup.com/oxforddnb/info/freeodnb/shelves/slavery/ |title=Slavery and abolition |publisher=Oup.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref> Its official name was the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions.\n\nIts work included supporting the first [[slave narrative]] to be published by a Black woman, [[Mary Prince]], ''The History of Mary Prince, A West Indian Slave'' (1831). The publishers were sued by the family from which she had escaped. The book was much sought after, running into three editions in the year of its publication.\n\nA wide range of views emerged among the members. Broadly, there were abolitionists who insisted on the full working out of the gradual process of abolition and amelioration (which had its successes), and the generally younger, more radical members, whose moral outlook regarded slavery as a mortal sin to be ended forthwith. [[Elizabeth Heyrick]]'s 1824 pamphlet \"Immediate, not Gradual, Abolition\" gave the tone to the argument.\n\nThe latter group, including [[Joseph Sturge]] and many others, publicly campaigned throughout Britain. The idea was to engender public pressure for a new parliamentary act to outlaw slavery, rather than continue the gradualism of Whitehall's negotiations, mainly with colonial governments. In 1831 [[George Stephen (abolitionist)|George Stephen]] and Joseph Sturge formed a [[ginger group]] within the Anti-Slavery Society, the Agency Committee, to campaign for this new act of Parliament. This campaign, and public pressure, led to the [[Slavery Abolition Act]] of 1833, though it contained compromises which they disliked.\n\nJamaican mixed-race campaigners such as [[Louis Celeste Lecesne]] and [[Richard Hill (Jamaica)]] were also members of the Anti-Slavery Society.\n\nThe [[indentured labour]] schemes were particularly opposed by Sturge and the Agency Committee; the full working out of the Act would take several years, with slavery eventually being abolished throughout the British West Indies on 1 August 1838. In response to the new legislation, other members of the Anti-Slavery Society considered their work over. The original purpose, as reflected in the name of the society (abolition in the British dominions), had, they thought, been achieved.\n\n==The Anti-Slavery Society of 1839==\n{{Refimprove section|date=November 2012}}\nWith abolition of slavery throughout the British dominions achieved, British abolitionists in the Agency Committee of the Anti-Slavery Society considered that a successor organisation was needed to tackle slavery worldwide. Largely under the guidance of Joseph Sturge, the committee duly formed a new society, [[British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society]] on 17 April 1839.<ref>[http://www.antislavery.org/english/what_we_do/antislavery_international_today/frequently_asked_questions.aspx About Anti-Slavery International] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626074739/http://www.antislavery.org/english/what_we_do/antislavery_international_today/frequently_asked_questions.aspx |date=26 June 2010 }} antislavery.org</ref><ref>Patricia Hollis (1974). Pressure from without in early Victorian England. p.39.</ref> It became widely known as the Anti-Slavery Society, as had the earlier society.\n\nThe first secretary was [[John Harfield Tredgold]], the first treasurer, [[George William Alexander]] of [[Stoke Newington]]. Along with the founding committee, which included the Anglican [[Sir Thomas Buxton, 1st Baronet|Thomas Fowell Buxton]], the Quaker [[William Allen (Quaker)|William Allen]], and the Congregationalist [[Josiah Conder (editor and author)|Josiah Conder]], they organised the first [[World Anti-Slavery Convention]] in London in 1840. [[Thomas Clarkson]] was the key speaker, and the Convention attracted people from nations around the world where slavery was practiced. In 1944, a Journalist [[James Ewing Ritchie]] issued a paper to the society on sugar trade and slavery<ref>Ritchie, James Ewing. 1944. ''[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/52820/52820-h/52820-h.htm Thoughts on Slavery and Cheap Sugar, a Letter to The Members and Friends of The British And Foreign Anti-Slavery Society.]''</ref>.\n\nThe convention had been advertised as a \"whole world\" convention, but the delegates representing anti-slavery societies in the United States included several women, among them [[Lucretia Mott]] and [[Elizabeth Cady Stanton]], who later were instrumental in the movement for women's rights. Convention leaders refused to seat the women delegates from America, and prominent male abolitionists such as Thomas Knight were outraged. He went on to form his own society. \n\nIn the 1850s, under Louis Chamerovzow, the society helped [[John Brown (fugitive slave)|John Brown]] write and publish his autobiography a decade before the [[American Civil War]] ended slavery in the United States.\n\nThe second secretary of the Anti-Slavery Society, appointed under the honorary secretaries [[Joseph Cooper (abolitionist|Joseph Cooper]] and [[Edmund Sturge]], was the Rev. Aaron Buzacott (1829\u201381), the son of a South Seas missionary also named [[Aaron Buzacott]]. With American slavery abolished in 1865, Buzacott worked closely with Joseph Cooper in researching and publishing work designed to help abolish slavery in elsewhere, particularly in the Middle East, Turkey and Africa.\n\n==Twentieth century and now==\nIn 1909, the society merged with the [[Aborigines' Protection Society]] to form the Anti-Slavery and Aborigines' Protection Society, whose prominent member was [[Kathleen Simon, Viscountess Simon]]. In 1990 the name was changed to [[Anti-Slavery International]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[American Anti-Slavery Group]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.antislavery.org Anti-Slavery International]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930194208/http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/portrait.asp?search=sp&sText=Anti-Slavery+Society&rNo=0 Anti-Slavery Society Convention 1840]\n*[http://www.anti-slaverysociety.org Anti-Slavery Society]\n\n[[Category:Abolitionism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Abolitionist organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1839]]\n[[Category:1823 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1839 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Slavery_Society"}
{"title_page": "Anti-Brahminism", "text_new": "{{Hinduism small}}\n'''Anti-Brahminism''' or '''Anti-Manuvaad''' is the ideology of being opposed to [[Brahminism]].\n\n==History==\n{{Main|\u015arama\u1e47a|\u0100stika and n\u0101stika}}\nEarly criticism against Brahmanism flourished within [[\u015arama\u1e47a|Sramana movement]].<ref>Svarghese, Alexander P. 2008. ''India : History, Religion, Vision And Contribution To The World.'' p. 259-60.</ref> Particularly in [[\u0100stika and n\u0101stika|N\u0101stika]] schools of [[Indian philosophy]] like [[Buddhism]], [[Jainism]], and others such as [[\u0100j\u012bvika]],  [[Charvaka|C\u0101rv\u0101ka]] and [[Aj\u00f1ana]].<ref name=\"AL Basham 1951 pages 94-103\">AL Basham (1951), History and Doctrines of the Ajivikas - a Vanished Indian Religion, Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|978-8120812048}}, pages 94-103</ref>\n\n[[Aj\u00f1ana]] were the [[Skepticism|sceptical]] school of ancient [[Indian philosophy]]. A major rival of early [[Buddhism]], [[Jainism]] and [[Historical Vedic religion|Vedic Hinduism]].<ref name=\"AL Basham 1951 pages 94-103\"/>\n\n{{quote|Herein a certain recluse or brahmin does not understand, as it really is, that this is good or this is evil. And it occurs to him: I do not understand what is good or evil as it really is. Not understanding what is good or evil, as it really is, if I were to assert that this is good and this is evil, that will be due to my likes, desires, aversions, or resentments. If it were due to my likes, desires, aversions or resentments, it would be wrong. And if I were wrong, it would cause me worry (''vighato'') and worry would be a moral danger to me (''antarayo''). Thus, through fear of being wrong (''musavadabhaya'') and the abhorrence of being wrong, he does not assert anything to be good or evil and on questions being put to him on this or that matter he resorts to verbal jugglery and eel-wriggling, saying: I do not say so, I do not say thus, I do not  say otherwise, I do not say no, I deny the denials. (literally, I do not say \"no, no\")|from the [[Pali]] text [[Brahmajala Sutta]], first school of [[Aj\u00f1ana]]''.{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=122-123}} }}\n\nThe fourth school of [[Aj\u00f1ana]] scepticism is associated with Sanjaya Belatthiputta.{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=130-131}} Sanjaya is described as a contemporary of Buddha, as a well-known and celebrated teacher, and as a leader of a sect who was held in high esteem by the common folk. He is said to have taught [[Sariputta]] and [[Maudgalyayana|Moggall\u0101na]], before their conversion to [[Buddhism]].{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=130-131}}\n\n{{quote|Herein a certain recluse or brahmin is dull, stupid. And by reason of his dullness and stupidity, when questioned on this or that matter, he resorts to verbal jugglery or eel-wriggling: \"If you ask me whether there is a next world, then if it were to occur to me (''iti ce me assa'') that there is a next world, I would pronounce that there is a next world. Yet, I do not say so, I do not say thus, I do not say otherwise, I do not say no, I deny the denials. Similarly with regard to the propositions, \"there is no next world\", \"there is and is not a next world\", \"there neither is nor is not a next world\", \"there are beings who survive (death)\", \"there are no beings who survive\", \"there are and are no beings who survive\", \"there neither are nor are there no beings who survive\", \"there is a result and a consequence of good and evil actions\", \"there is no result or consequence of good or evil actions\", \"the Perfect One (Tathagato) exists after death\", \"the Perfect One does not exist after death\", \"the Perfect One both exists and does not exist after death\", \"the Perfect One neither exists nor does not exist after death\"\" |from the ''Brahmajala Sutta'', attributed to ''Sanjaya Belatthiputta''.{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=131}} }}\n\n[[C\u0101rv\u0101ka]]s were the atheistic and materialism school of ancient [[Indian philosophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/Not-scared-of-God-but-man/articleshow/46570208.cms|title=Not scared of God, but man}}</ref> They were critical of Brahmanism, as well of [[Buddhism]] and [[Jainism]].<ref name=moor>{{cite book|author1= Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan|author2= Charles A. Moore|title= A Sourcebook in Indian Philosophy|publisher= Princeton University Press|year= 1957|edition= Twelfth Princeton Paperback printing 1989|pages= [https://archive.org/details/sourcebookinindi00radh/page/227 227\u2013249]|isbn= 0-691-01958-4|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/sourcebookinindi00radh/page/227}}</ref>\n{{quote|There is no heaven, no final liberation, nor any soul in another world, Nor do the actions of the four castes, orders, etc., produce any real effect.|from the '' Sarvadar\u015banasa\u1e45\u0307graha'', attributed to ''[[C\u0101rv\u0101ka|Brhaspati]]''<ref>{{cite book|author=Ramkrishna Bhattacharya|title=Studies on the Carvaka/Lokayata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=59eygxzQTWQC&pg=PA91|accessdate=8 September 2013|year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-0-85728-433-4|pages=91}}</ref><ref name=\"Madhava\">{{cite book|author=M\u0101dhava|title=The Sarva-dar\u015bana-sa\u1e43graha|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/34125/34125-h/34125-h.htm|accessdate=8 September 2013|year=1908|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Buddhism]] was critical of Brahmanism, [[Jainism]], [[Carvaka]] and [[\u0100j\u012bvika]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">J. Abraham Velez de Cea 2013 \"The Buddha and Religious Diversity\", p.90</ref>\n\n{{quote|One is not a brahmin by birth, nor by birth a non-brahmin. By action is one a brahmin, by action is one a non-brahmin.| From the ''Vasettha Sutta'', attributed to ''[[Buddha]]''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>}}\n\n===Medieval period===\n{{See also|Bhakti movement|Lingayatism|Sikhism}}\nCriticism against Brahmanism continued up to late medieval period, particularly by some [[Shaivism]] and [[Vaishnavism]] sects of [[Hinduism]] notably with rise of [[Bhakti movement]] and [[Lingayatism]].<ref>\"[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/342355/Lingayat Lingayat].\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. 2010. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. 09 Jul. 2010.</ref> The [[Bhakti movement]] in particular encouraged followers to attain spiritual union with God not through sacrifices, rituals, pilgrimages, or prayers, but through the \u201cforce of pure love and fervent yearning for God.\u201d{{sfnp|Schomer|McLeod|1987|p=1}} The [[merchant]] class and [[agricultural]] class largely funded the growth of [[\u0100stika and n\u0101stika|N\u0101stika]] sects and religions during ancient and medieval period, who saw them as alternative to expensive Brahmanical [[ritualism]] and [[superstitions]].<ref name=\"AL Basham 1951 pages 94-103\"/>\n\n==20th century==\n\nIn the early 20th century, criticism against Brahminism came within various sections of Brahmin and other Hindu communities who were part of nationalist and rationalist movement. [[Vinayak Damodar Savarkar]] was an eminent [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] leader of the [[Indian independence movement]]. He was also an [[irreligion in India|atheist]] and a staunch [[rationalist]]<ref name=\"Kumar\">{{Cite book|title = Towards Understanding Communalism|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8_RtAAAAMAAJ|publisher = Centre for Research in Rural and Industrial Development|date = 1992-01-01|isbn = 9788185835174|first = Pramod|last = Kumar}}</ref> who disapproved of orthodox [[Hindu]] beliefs of [[caste system]] and dismissed [[Cattle in religion|cow worship]] as superstitious.<ref>{{Cite news|title = The man who thought Gandhi a sissy|url = https://www.economist.com/news/christmas-specials/21636599-controversial-mentor-hindu-right-man-who-thought-gandhi-sissy|newspaper = The Economist|access-date = 2016-01-23|issn = 0013-0613}}</ref> Being Hindu, for him, was a cultural and political identity.<ref name=\"Kumar\"/>\n\nAnti-Brahminism became organized in the formation of the ''Justice Party'' in late 1916 in Tamil Nadu. This party, composed of upper-class non-Brahmins who were typically [[feudal]] castes, land-owning agricultural castes and merchant castes and was committed to enhancing the opportunities for non-Brahmins.<ref name=\"Ritual\">''Ritualizing on the Boundaries''; by Fred W. Clothey;</ref> The [[Reddy|Reddys]], [[Mudaliar|Mudaliars]], and [[Nair|Nairs]] are specific examples of South Indian non-Brahmin castes that were involved in the anti-Brahminism movement for about 50 years.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c5yOAAAAMAAJ&dq|title=Lokayan Bulletin|last=|first=|date=1996|publisher=Lokayan|year=|isbn=|volume=13|location=|pages=6|language=en|issue=1-6}}</ref> With the dawn of the 20th century, and the rapid penetration of western education and western ideas, there was a rise in consciousness amongst the lower castes who felt that rights which were legitimately theirs were being denied to them. One of the most prominent proponents of Anti-Brahminism was Dravidian leader [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]], who called on Brahmins and non-Brahmins to reject Brahminism. Ramasamy was known for excluding Brahmins from his movement.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dalit Visions: The Anti-caste Movement and the Construction on an Indian Identity|author=Omvedt, Gail|year=2006|publisher=Orient Longman|page=95|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kCwpXZlKqL0C|isbn=978-81-250-2895-6|postscript=<!--None-->|accessdate=17 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-Brahmin violence in Maharashtra==\n====20th Century acts of violence====\nAfter [[Gandhi]]'s murder by [[Nathuram Godse]], a [[Chitpawan]], Brahmins in Maharashtra, became targets of violence, mostly by some elements from the [[Maratha]] caste.<ref name=\"malon\"/><ref name=\"ullekh\"/><ref name=\"elst\"/>The exact number deaths are unknown. Thousands of offices and homes were also set on fire. [[Sexual abuse|Molestation]] incidents were also reported during these attacks. On the first day alone, the number of deaths in Bombay were 15 and 50 in Pune.<ref name=\"elst\"/>\n\nAs per V.M.  Sirsikar, \"It will be too much to believe that the riots took place because of the intense love of Gandhiji on the part of the [[Maratha]]s. Godse became a very convenient hate symbol to damn the Brahmins and burn their properties.\"\nDonald Rosenthal opines in 1948 that the motivation for the violence was the historical opposition [[Maratha]] community faced for their caste status. He writes,\"Even today[1948], local Brahmins claim that the Marathas organized the riots to take political advantage of the situation\".<ref name=\"ullekh\">{{cite book|title=The Untold Vajpayee: Politician and Paradox|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4LZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT39|page=39|author= Ullekh N P|publisher=Random House India|year=2018}}</ref><ref name=\"malon\">{{cite book|title=State Intervention and Popular Response: Western India in the Nineteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t7f0JEWk6HMC&pg=PA11#v=onepage&q&f=false|editor1=Mariam Dossal|editor2=Ruby Malon|page=11}}</ref>\n\nIn Satara alone, the official reports show that about 1000 houses were burnt down in about 300 villages. There were \"cruel, cold-blooded killings\" as well - for example, one family whose last name happened to be 'Godse' had three of its male members killed.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=University of Toronto, Centre for South Asian Studies|title=City, countryside and society in Maharashtra|page=40|quote=There is no doubt now since about 1000 houses were officially reported to have burnt in some 300 villages spread across all thirteen talukas of the District and Aundh State. There are reports of \"cruel, cold-blooded killing\" \u2014 one family named Godse was said to have lost three male members \u2014 and there were other serious physical attacks on Brahmans. In general, the victims of arson and looting were predominantly Brahman...|year=1988}}</ref>\n\nMaureen Patterson concludes that the greatest violence took place not in the cities of Mumbai, Pune and Nagpur - but in [[Satara (city)|Satara]], [[Kolhapur]] and [[Belgaum]]. Destruction was very large in [[Kolhapur]] where Shahu had actively collaborated with the British against the Indian freedom struggle - a face that was identified by [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]]. Shahu was also actively involved in the anti-Brahmin movement. In [[Sangli]], the [[Jains]] and the [[Lingayats]] joined the Marathas in the attacks against the Brahmins. Here, specifically, the factories owned by the [[Chitpawan|Chitpawan Brahmin]]s were destroyed. This event led to the hasty integration of the Patwardhan states into the Bombay Province by March 1948.<ref name=\"elst\">{{cite book| title= Gandhi and Godse:A review and Critique|author=Koenraad Elst|year= 2001|pages=12, 13, 14|quote=(pg 13,14)Destruction was even larger in kolhapur...(pg14)Shahu Maharaj had actively collaborated with the British against the freedom movement, which was locally identified with Chitpawan Brahmins like B.G.Tilak...(pg14) The biggest violence took place in the seven Patwardhan (Chitpawan) princely states such as Sangli, where the remarkably advanced factories owned by Chitpawans were largely destroyed/ Here, Jains and Lingayats joined the Marathas in the attacks. The events hastened the integration of Patwardhan states (by march 1948) into the Bombay province, an integration opposed by the Brahmins - fearing Maratha predominance in the integrated province.}}</ref>\n\n====21st century threats of violence====\nPurshottam Khedekar, the chief of \"Maratha Maha Sangh\" (a [[Maratha]] caste based organization) and [[Sambhaji Brigade]], published writings in 2011 that had defamatory statements about the sexual habits, orientation and character of Brahmin men and women. He made a call for \"instigating communal riots purposefully started to kill Brahmin men.\" However, Ramteke, an [[Dalit Buddhist movement|Ambedkarite]], has written against Khedekar's writing. He said: \u201cWe should keep a distance from Khedekar and his movement against Brahmins. [[B. R. Ambedkar|Dr Babasaheb [Ambedkar]]] never stooped to this level. If we continue to associate with him, it will malign our image. The government should ban the book and the organisation\u201d. In 2011, a news report said that the \"[[Maratha]] politicians have mostly been silent on the issue\". A case has since been registered against Khedekar.<ref>http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-laine-baiter-maratha-author-pens-book-to-bash-brahmins-1546409</ref><ref>https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/cover-story/brahmin-insult-charge-on-maratha-seva-sangh-chief/articleshow/55988221.cms</ref>\n\n== Anti-Brahmin violence in TN ==\nIn the late 1950s, members of Dravidar Kazhagam have been accused of having assaulted the owner of  \"Hotel Murali Cafe\", in Triplicane, Chennai for having the name \"Hotel Murali Iyer's Cafe\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Memories-of-a-violent-movement-led-by-Periyar/articleshow/47823566.cms|title=Memories of a Violent Movement led by Periyar|last=|first=|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=}}</ref> The party members have been accused of laying siege to the Brahmin owner, by dragging him through litigation and harassment. The ordeal is said to have ended when a seer of [[Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham|Kanchi Mutt]], [[Chandrashekarendra Saraswati|Chandrasekara Saraswathy]] intervened.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 2015, an 80 year old man and a 12 year old boy were attacked, and their religious symbols were destroyed in public.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/attacks-fuel-brahmin-fears/cid/1511212|title=Attacks fuel Brahmin fears|last=|first=|date=|work=Telegraph India|access-date=}}</ref> The assailants were later identified as party members of [[Dravidar Viduthalai Kazhagam]], a Periyar inspired party, who yelled \"Periyar Vaazhga\" (Long live Periyar) during the assault.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[BAMCEF]]\n* [[Reservations in India]]\n* [[Caste-related violence in India]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*''[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/punes-endless-identity-wars/734020/ Pune\u2019s endless identity wars]'' by Rakshit Sonawane, ''[[The Indian Express]]'', January 6, 2011.\n* Politics and Social Conflict in South India, the Non-Brahman Movement and Tamil Separatism, 1916-1929. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1969. By Prof. Eugene Irschik\n* [http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/may/23franc.htm Editorial by Francois Gautier on anti-Brahmanism]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anti-Brahminism}}\n[[Category:Politics of India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Brahminism| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hinduism small}}\n'''Anti-Brahminism''' or '''Anti-Manuvaad''' is the ideology of being opposed to [[Brahminism]].\n\n==History==\n{{Main|\u015arama\u1e47a|\u0100stika and n\u0101stika}}\nEarly criticism against Brahmanism flourished within [[\u015arama\u1e47a|Sramana movement]].<ref>Svarghese, Alexander P. 2008. ''India : History, Religion, Vision And Contribution To The World.'' p. 259-60.</ref> Particularly in [[\u0100stika and n\u0101stika|N\u0101stika]] schools of [[Indian philosophy]] like [[Buddhism]], [[Jainism]], and others such as [[\u0100j\u012bvika]],  [[Charvaka|C\u0101rv\u0101ka]] and [[Aj\u00f1ana]].<ref name=\"AL Basham 1951 pages 94-103\">AL Basham (1951), History and Doctrines of the Ajivikas - a Vanished Indian Religion, Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|978-8120812048}}, pages 94-103</ref>\n\n[[Aj\u00f1ana]] were the [[Skepticism|sceptical]] school of ancient [[Indian philosophy]]. A major rival of early [[Buddhism]], [[Jainism]] and [[Historical Vedic religion|Vedic Hinduism]].<ref name=\"AL Basham 1951 pages 94-103\"/>\n\n{{quote|Herein a certain recluse or brahmin does not understand, as it really is, that this is good or this is evil. And it occurs to him: I do not understand what is good or evil as it really is. Not understanding what is good or evil, as it really is, if I were to assert that this is good and this is evil, that will be due to my likes, desires, aversions, or resentments. If it were due to my likes, desires, aversions or resentments, it would be wrong. And if I were wrong, it would cause me worry (''vighato'') and worry would be a moral danger to me (''antarayo''). Thus, through fear of being wrong (''musavadabhaya'') and the abhorrence of being wrong, he does not assert anything to be good or evil and on questions being put to him on this or that matter he resorts to verbal jugglery and eel-wriggling, saying: I do not say so, I do not say thus, I do not  say otherwise, I do not say no, I deny the denials. (literally, I do not say \"no, no\")|from the [[Pali]] text [[Brahmajala Sutta]], first school of [[Aj\u00f1ana]]''.{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=122-123}} }}\n\nThe fourth school of [[Aj\u00f1ana]] scepticism is associated with Sanjaya Belatthiputta.{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=130-131}} Sanjaya is described as a contemporary of Buddha, as a well-known and celebrated teacher, and as a leader of a sect who was held in high esteem by the common folk. He is said to have taught [[Sariputta]] and [[Maudgalyayana|Moggall\u0101na]], before their conversion to [[Buddhism]].{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=130-131}}\n\n{{quote|Herein a certain recluse or brahmin is dull, stupid. And by reason of his dullness and stupidity, when questioned on this or that matter, he resorts to verbal jugglery or eel-wriggling: \"If you ask me whether there is a next world, then if it were to occur to me (''iti ce me assa'') that there is a next world, I would pronounce that there is a next world. Yet, I do not say so, I do not say thus, I do not say otherwise, I do not say no, I deny the denials. Similarly with regard to the propositions, \"there is no next world\", \"there is and is not a next world\", \"there neither is nor is not a next world\", \"there are beings who survive (death)\", \"there are no beings who survive\", \"there are and are no beings who survive\", \"there neither are nor are there no beings who survive\", \"there is a result and a consequence of good and evil actions\", \"there is no result or consequence of good or evil actions\", \"the Perfect One (Tathagato) exists after death\", \"the Perfect One does not exist after death\", \"the Perfect One both exists and does not exist after death\", \"the Perfect One neither exists nor does not exist after death\"\" |from the ''Brahmajala Sutta'', attributed to ''Sanjaya Belatthiputta''.{{sfn|Jayatilleke|p=131}} }}\n\n[[C\u0101rv\u0101ka]]s were the atheistic and materialism school of ancient [[Indian philosophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/Not-scared-of-God-but-man/articleshow/46570208.cms|title=Not scared of God, but man}}</ref> They were critical of Brahmanism, as well of [[Buddhism]] and [[Jainism]].<ref name=moor>{{cite book|author1= Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan|author2= Charles A. Moore|title= A Sourcebook in Indian Philosophy|publisher= Princeton University Press|year= 1957|edition= Twelfth Princeton Paperback printing 1989|pages= [https://archive.org/details/sourcebookinindi00radh/page/227 227\u2013249]|isbn= 0-691-01958-4|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/sourcebookinindi00radh/page/227}}</ref>\n{{quote|There is no heaven, no final liberation, nor any soul in another world, Nor do the actions of the four castes, orders, etc., produce any real effect.|from the '' Sarvadar\u015banasa\u1e45\u0307graha'', attributed to ''[[C\u0101rv\u0101ka|Brhaspati]]''<ref>{{cite book|author=Ramkrishna Bhattacharya|title=Studies on the Carvaka/Lokayata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=59eygxzQTWQC&pg=PA91|accessdate=8 September 2013|year=2011|publisher=Anthem Press|isbn=978-0-85728-433-4|pages=91}}</ref><ref name=\"Madhava\">{{cite book|author=M\u0101dhava|title=The Sarva-dar\u015bana-sa\u1e43graha|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/34125/34125-h/34125-h.htm|accessdate=8 September 2013|year=1908|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Buddhism]] was critical of Brahmanism, [[Jainism]], [[Carvaka]] and [[\u0100j\u012bvika]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">J. Abraham Velez de Cea 2013 \"The Buddha and Religious Diversity\", p.90</ref>\n\n{{quote|One is not a brahmin by birth, nor by birth a non-brahmin. By action is one a brahmin, by action is one a non-brahmin.| From the ''Vasettha Sutta'', attributed to ''[[Buddha]]''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>}}\n\n===Medieval period===\n{{See also|Bhakti movement|Lingayatism|Sikhism}}\nCriticism against Brahmanism continued up to late medieval period, particularly by some [[Shaivism]] and [[Vaishnavism]] sects of [[Hinduism]] notably with rise of [[Bhakti movement]] and [[Lingayatism]].<ref>\"[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/342355/Lingayat Lingayat].\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. 2010. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. 09 Jul. 2010.</ref> The [[Bhakti movement]] in particular encouraged followers to attain spiritual union with God not through sacrifices, rituals, pilgrimages, or prayers, but through the \u201cforce of pure love and fervent yearning for God.\u201d{{sfnp|Schomer|McLeod|1987|p=1}} The [[merchant]] class and [[agricultural]] class largely funded the growth of [[\u0100stika and n\u0101stika|N\u0101stika]] sects and religions during ancient and medieval period, who saw them as alternative to expensive Brahmanical [[ritualism]] and [[superstitions]].<ref name=\"AL Basham 1951 pages 94-103\"/>\n\n==20th century==\n\nIn the early 20th century, criticism against Brahminism came within various sections of Brahmin and other Hindu communities who were part of nationalist and rationalist movement. [[Vinayak Damodar Savarkar]] was an eminent [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]] leader of the [[Indian independence movement]]. He was also an [[irreligion in India|atheist]] and a staunch [[rationalist]]<ref name=\"Kumar\">{{Cite book|title = Towards Understanding Communalism|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8_RtAAAAMAAJ|publisher = Centre for Research in Rural and Industrial Development|date = 1992-01-01|isbn = 9788185835174|first = Pramod|last = Kumar}}</ref> who disapproved of orthodox [[Hindu]] beliefs of [[caste system]] and dismissed [[Cattle in religion|cow worship]] as superstitious.<ref>{{Cite news|title = The man who thought Gandhi a sissy|url = https://www.economist.com/news/christmas-specials/21636599-controversial-mentor-hindu-right-man-who-thought-gandhi-sissy|newspaper = The Economist|access-date = 2016-01-23|issn = 0013-0613}}</ref> Being Hindu, for him, was a cultural and political identity.<ref name=\"Kumar\"/>\n\nAnti-Brahminism became organized in the formation of the ''Justice Party'' in late 1916 in Tamil Nadu. This party, composed of upper-class non-Brahmins who were typically [[feudal]] castes, land-owning agricultural castes and merchant castes and was committed to enhancing the opportunities for non-Brahmins.<ref name=\"Ritual\">''Ritualizing on the Boundaries''; by Fred W. Clothey;</ref> The [[Reddy|Reddys]], [[Mudaliar|Mudaliars]], and [[Nair|Nairs]] are specific examples of South Indian non-Brahmin castes that were involved in the anti-Brahminism movement for about 50 years.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=c5yOAAAAMAAJ&dq|title=Lokayan Bulletin|last=|first=|date=1996|publisher=Lokayan|year=|isbn=|volume=13|location=|pages=6|language=en|issue=1-6}}</ref> With the dawn of the 20th century, and the rapid penetration of western education and western ideas, there was a rise in consciousness amongst the lower castes who felt that rights which were legitimately theirs were being denied to them. One of the most prominent proponents of Anti-Brahminism was Dravidian leader [[Periyar E. V. Ramasamy]], who called on Brahmins and non-Brahmins to reject Brahminism. Ramasamy was known for excluding Brahmins from his movement.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dalit Visions: The Anti-caste Movement and the Construction on an Indian Identity|author=Omvedt, Gail|year=2006|publisher=Orient Longman|page=95|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kCwpXZlKqL0C|isbn=978-81-250-2895-6|postscript=<!--None-->|accessdate=17 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-Brahmin violence in Maharashtra==\n====20th Century acts of violence====\nAfter [[Gandhi]]'s murder by [[Nathuram Godse]], a [[Chitpawan]], Brahmins in Maharashtra, became targets of violence, mostly by some elements from the [[Maratha]] caste.<ref name=\"malon\"/><ref name=\"ullekh\"/><ref name=\"elst\"/>The exact number deaths are unknown. Thousands of offices and homes were also set on fire. [[Sexual abuse|Molestation]] incidents were also reported during these attacks. On the first day alone, the number of deaths in Bombay were 15 and 50 in Pune.<ref name=\"elst\"/>\n\nAs per V.M.  Sirsikar, \"It will be too much to believe that the riots took place because of the intense love of Gandhiji on the part of the [[Maratha]]s. Godse became a very convenient hate symbol to damn the Brahmins and burn their properties.\"\nDonald Rosenthal opines in 1948 that the motivation for the violence was the historical opposition [[Maratha]] community faced for their caste status. He writes,\"Even today[1948], local Brahmins claim that the Marathas organized the riots to take political advantage of the situation\".<ref name=\"ullekh\">{{cite book|title=The Untold Vajpayee: Politician and Paradox|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4LZDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT39|page=39|author= Ullekh N P|publisher=Random House India|year=2018}}</ref><ref name=\"malon\">{{cite book|title=State Intervention and Popular Response: Western India in the Nineteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t7f0JEWk6HMC&pg=PA11#v=onepage&q&f=false|editor1=Mariam Dossal|editor2=Ruby Malon|page=11}}</ref>\n\nIn Satara alone, the official reports show that about 1000 houses were burnt down in about 300 villages. There were \"cruel, cold-blooded killings\" as well - for example, one family whose last name happened to be 'Godse' had three of its male members killed.<ref>{{cite book|publisher=University of Toronto, Centre for South Asian Studies|title=City, countryside and society in Maharashtra|page=40|quote=There is no doubt now since about 1000 houses were officially reported to have burnt in some 300 villages spread across all thirteen talukas of the District and Aundh State. There are reports of \"cruel, cold-blooded killing\" \u2014 one family named Godse was said to have lost three male members \u2014 and there were other serious physical attacks on Brahmans. In general, the victims of arson and looting were predominantly Brahman...|year=1988}}</ref>\n\nMaureen Patterson concludes that the greatest violence took place not in the cities of Mumbai, Pune and Nagpur - but in [[Satara (city)|Satara]], [[Kolhapur]] and [[Belgaum]]. Destruction was very large in [[Kolhapur]] where Shahu had actively collaborated with the British against the Indian freedom struggle - a face that was identified by [[Bal Gangadhar Tilak]]. Shahu was also actively involved in the anti-Brahmin movement. In [[Sangli]], the [[Jains]] and the [[Lingayats]] joined the Marathas in the attacks against the Brahmins. Here, specifically, the factories owned by the [[Chitpawan|Chitpawan Brahmin]]s were destroyed. This event led to the hasty integration of the Patwardhan states into the Bombay Province by March 1948.<ref name=\"elst\">{{cite book| title= Gandhi and Godse:A review and Critique|author=Koenraad Elst|year= 2001|pages=12, 13, 14|quote=(pg 13,14)Destruction was even larger in kolhapur...(pg14)Shahu Maharaj had actively collaborated with the British against the freedom movement, which was locally identified with Chitpawan Brahmins like B.G.Tilak...(pg14) The biggest violence took place in the seven Patwardhan (Chitpawan) princely states such as Sangli, where the remarkably advanced factories owned by Chitpawans were largely destroyed/ Here, Jains and Lingayats joined the Marathas in the attacks. The events hastened the integration of Patwardhan states (by march 1948) into the Bombay province, an integration opposed by the Brahmins - fearing Maratha predominance in the integrated province.}}</ref>\n\n====21st century threats of violence====\nPurshottam Khedekar, the chief of \"Maratha Maha Sangh\" (a [[Maratha]] caste based organization) and [[Sambhaji Brigade]], published writings in 2011 that had defamatory statements about the sexual habits, orientation and character of Brahmin men and women. He made a call for \"instigating communal riots purposefully started to kill Brahmin men.\" However, Ramteke, an [[Dalit Buddhist movement|Ambedkarite]], has written against Khedekar's writing. He said: \u201cWe should keep a distance from Khedekar and his movement against Brahmins. [[B. R. Ambedkar|Dr Babasaheb [Ambedkar]]] never stooped to this level. If we continue to associate with him, it will malign our image. The government should ban the book and the organisation\u201d. In 2011, a news report said that the \"[[Maratha]] politicians have mostly been silent on the issue\". A case has since been registered against Khedekar.<ref>http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-laine-baiter-maratha-author-pens-book-to-bash-brahmins-1546409</ref><ref>https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/cover-story/brahmin-insult-charge-on-maratha-seva-sangh-chief/articleshow/55988221.cms</ref>\n\n== Anti-Brahmin violence in TN ==\nIn the late 1950s, members of Dravidar Kazhagam have been accused of having assaulted the owner of  \"Hotel Murali Cafe\", in Triplicane, Chennai for having the name \"Hotel Murali Iyer's Cafe\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Memories-of-a-violent-movement-led-by-Periyar/articleshow/47823566.cms|title=Memories of a Violent Movement led by Periyar|last=|first=|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>. The party members have been accused of laying siege to the Brahmin owner, by dragging him through litigation and harassment. The ordeal is said to have ended when a seer of [[Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham|Kanchi Mutt]], [[Chandrashekarendra Saraswati|Chandrasekara Saraswathy]] intervened.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 2015, an 80 year old man and a 12 year old boy were attacked, and their religious symbols were destroyed in public.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/attacks-fuel-brahmin-fears/cid/1511212|title=Attacks fuel Brahmin fears|last=|first=|date=|work=Telegraph India|access-date=}}</ref> The assailants were later identified as party members of [[Dravidar Viduthalai Kazhagam]], a Periyar inspired party, who yelled \"Periyar Vaazhga\" (Long live Periyar) during the assault.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[BAMCEF]]\n* [[Reservations in India]]\n* [[Caste-related violence in India]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*''[http://www.indianexpress.com/news/punes-endless-identity-wars/734020/ Pune\u2019s endless identity wars]'' by Rakshit Sonawane, ''[[The Indian Express]]'', January 6, 2011.\n* Politics and Social Conflict in South India, the Non-Brahman Movement and Tamil Separatism, 1916-1929. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1969. By Prof. Eugene Irschik\n* [http://in.rediff.com/news/2006/may/23franc.htm Editorial by Francois Gautier on anti-Brahmanism]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anti-Brahminism}}\n[[Category:Politics of India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Brahminism| ]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Brahminism"}
{"title_page": "Peter Walton (referee)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n<!--VANDALISM to this page will be promptly removed. Additions must be properly cited and comply with Wikipedia's rules on recentisms, notability and neutrality.-->\n{{Infobox football official\n| image = Peter Walton 1.jpg\n| name = Peter Walton\n| fullname = Peter Walton\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Long Buckby]], [[Northamptonshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| otheroccupation = \n| years1              = 1993-1994\n| league1             = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n| role1               = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referee]]\n| years2              = 1994-1998\n| league2             = [[Premier League]]\n| role2               = Assistant referee\n| years3              = 1998-2003\n| league3             = Football League\n| role3               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years4              = 2003-2012\n| league4             = Premier League\n| role4               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 1996-1998\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = Assistant referee\n}}\n'''Peter Walton''' (born 10 October 1959)<ref>[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0,,10794~628215,00.html Birthdate and biographical details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115195943/http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10794~628215%2C00.html |date=15 January 2008 }}: [[Football League|The Football League]] Official website.</ref> is an [[England|English]] former professional [[Association football|football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]] who officiated in the [[Premier League]] from 2003 to 2012. Beginning 2013, he was general manager of the [[Professional Referee Organization]] (PRO) in North America until being replaced by [[Howard Webb]] in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=PROreferees.com |publisher=PROreferees.com |url=http://www.proreferees.com/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PRO promotes Howard Webb to General Manager|publisher=PROreferees.com|url=http://proreferees.com/2018/01/18/pro-promotes-howard-webb-to-general-manager/}}</ref>\n\nWalton is also a former player in the [[United Counties Football League|United Counties League]]. He is based in [[Long Buckby]],<ref>[http://www.pink-un.com/Content/ncfc/statattack/2000-01/matches/asp/001216Grimsby.asp Home town]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} reference example: ''The Pink-Un'' online.</ref> [[Northamptonshire]], the village which he played his football for.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060621162104/http://stneotsfc.net/news/UCL_03August.pdf Playing career] reference: ''UCL  Newsletter 168 August 2003''.</ref> He lists his interests as current affairs and golf.<ref>[http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enRefereesProfile&id=374253&type=com.fapl.website.stories.SimpleStories&categoryCode=Referees Hobbies and interests] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114105937/http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enRefereesProfile&id=374253&type=com.fapl.website.stories.SimpleStories&categoryCode=Referees |date=14 November 2006 }}, plus further biography: [[Premier League]] Official website.</ref>\n\nDuring his professional career which spanned nearly 20 years, Walton refereed a number of notable matches, including the 2003 final of the [[Football League Trophy]] and the [[FA Community Shield]] in 2008.\n\n==Career==\nWalton began refereeing in 1986 in local leagues. He was appointed to the assistant referees' lists of [[the Football League]] in 1993, and the [[Premier League]] in 1994.\n\nIn 1996, he was an assistant referee for the [[1996 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], when [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] defeated [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] with a late [[Eric Cantona]] goal.\n\nIn the same year he became a [[FIFA]] assistant referee, officiating in that capacity during [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro '96]] in England, notably in a group-stage match between [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] at [[Old Trafford]], which Germany won 2\u20130.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/history/season=1996/round=227/match=52506/index.html Details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070716115242/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/euro/history/season%3D1996/round%3D227/match%3D52506/index.html |date=16 July 2007 }} of Germany v. Czech Republic: [[UEFA|UEFA.com]] website.</ref>\n\nWalton was promoted to the Football League list of referees in 1998.<ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19981027/ai_n14184553 Reported] comment by [[Joe Kinnear]]: [[The Independent|Independent.co.uk]] through ''FindArticles.com'' website.</ref> At this point, he also stepped down from the FIFA assistant referees' list.\n\nIn 2003, he was added to the [[Select Group Referees|Select Group]] of referees and took charge of the [[Football League Trophy]] final between [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] and [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] on 6 April, with the Robins triumphing 2\u20130.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=387629 Match details] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001131110/http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=387629 |date=1 October 2007 }}: [[Football League Trophy]] at [[soccerbase]].com website.</ref> He also refereed a [[Football League First Division|Division 1]] play-off semi-final [[Two-legged tie|second leg]]<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=390219 Sheff. Utd. v. Nottm. Forest], 2003 [[Football League First Division|(old) First Division]] [[play-off]] [[semi-final]] [[leg (sport)|second leg]].</ref> and a [[Football League Division Three|Division 3]] play-off semi-final first leg<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=390075 Lincoln v. Scunthorpe], 2003 [[Football League Division Three|(old) Division Three]] [[play-off]] [[semi-final]] [[leg (sport)|first leg]].</ref> at the end of the [[2002-03 in English football|2002-03 season]].\n\nHis first Premier League appointment was a 4\u20133 home win by [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] at [[Molineux Stadium]] on 25 October 2003.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=404869 First ever] [[Premier League]] match: soccerbase.com website.</ref>\n\nAt the end of January 2007, Walton accompanied Regional Referees' Manager [[Ray Olivier]] (a Football League referee himself) to [[Guayaquil]], Ecuador, to undertake an Advanced Course for Referees' Instructors on behalf of [[the Football Association]] and [[CONMEBOL]].<ref>[http://www.conmebol.com/comunicados_ver.jsp?id=60211&slangab=E Ecuador] trip with Ray Olivier: [[Confederaci\u00f3n Sudamericana de F\u00fatbol]] website.</ref> Olivier is quoted as saying: \"It is also a great fillip to have someone of Peter's calibre as part of the team and his experience of refereeing in the Premiership is invaluable to those referees taking part in this workshop.\"<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/InternationalRelations/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2007/01/OlivierWalton.htm Ecuador] trip with Ray Olivier: [[The Football Association|TheFA.com]] website.</ref>\n\nWalton refereed the [[2008 FA Community Shield]] match between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], issuing three cautions during the game between the Premier League champions and FA Cup winners of the previous season, which United won 3\u20131 on penalties after extra-time.\n\nWalton's last appointment as a Premier League referee was [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]'s 2\u20130 home win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 31 March 2012. He then took up a new role as the general manager of the [[Professional Referee Organization]] (PRO) for the Football Leagues in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]], from 2 April 2012.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120911021345/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/walton-to-head-us-referees-body.html]</ref>\n\nUpon his appointment, Walton said to proreferees.com: \"I think the referees we've got in North America are very good.\n\n\u201cI think the competitive nature of our leagues are very good as well and what I'm intending to do is match-up the referee abilities to that of the playing side.\n\n\"We can see great strides being taken with the league and with the infrastructure, with the players and I must make sure our referees are running parallel to that so we advance at the same pace and there isn't a gap developing or developed.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Walton: \"a long-term building process\" |publisher=PROreferees.com |url=http://www.proreferees.com/news-walton-a-long-term-building-process.php |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919000416/http://www.proreferees.com/news-walton-a-long-term-building-process.php |archivedate=19 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWalton currently works as a referee analyst for BT Sport's coverage of the UEFA Champions League, discussing key decisions and explaining the usage of VAR, both in-game and post-match. During the 2019 Champions League semi-final second leg between Tottenham and Ajax, a celebrating Walton, in his BT studio, was inadvertently broadcast in the midst of the dramatic scenes following Tottenham's late winning goal. Walton also regularly appears on [[ESPN FC]].\n\n==Card statistics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Season!!Games!!Total {{yel}}!!{{yel}} per game!!Total {{sent off}}!!{{sent off}} per game\n|-\n|'''[[1998-99 in English football|1998/99]]'''||32||99||''3.09''||8||''0.25''\n|-\n|'''[[1999-00 in English football|1999/00]]'''||31||86||''2.77''||4||''0.13''\n|-\n|'''[[2000-01 in English football|2000/01]]'''||37||102||''2.76''||7||''0.19''\n|-\n|'''[[2001-02 in English football|2001/02]]'''||35||113||''3.23''||13||''0.37''\n|-\n|'''[[2002-03 in English football|2002/03]]'''||45||129||''2.87''||8||''0.18''\n|-\n|'''[[2003-04 in English football|2003/04]]'''||31||64||''2.06''||4||''0.13''\n|-\n|'''[[2004-05 in English football|2004/05]]'''||31||87||''2.81''||2||''0.06''\n|-\n|'''[[2005-06 in English football|2005/06]]'''||42||126||''3.00''||6||''0.14''\n|-\n|'''[[2006-07 in English football|2006/07]]'''||40||128||''3.20''||4||''0.10''\n|-\n|'''[[2007-08 in English football|2007/08]]'''||41||123||''3.00''||5||''0.12''\n|-\n|'''[[2008-09 in English football|2008/09]]'''||43||97||''2.25''||4||''0.09''\n|-\n|'''[[2009\u201310 in English football|2009/10]]'''||36||91||''2.53''||6||''0.16''\n|-\n|'''[[2010\u201311 in English football|2010/11]]'''||33||110||''3.33''||9||''0.27''\n|-\n|'''[[2011\u201312 in English football|2011/12]]'''||22||68||''3.09''||2||''0.09''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of football referees]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Peter Walton}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212183420/http://www.refworld.com/referee/23/0/peter-walton |title=Peter Walton at Refworld.com}}\n* {{Soccerbase referee|243}} ([https://web.archive.org/web/20080330073003/http://www.soccerbase.com:80/refs2.sd?refid=243 archive])\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walton, Peter}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:Premier League referees]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Long Buckby]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n<!--VANDALISM to this page will be promptly removed. Additions must be properly cited and comply with Wikipedia's rules on recentisms, notability and neutrality.-->\n{{Infobox football official\n| image = Peter Walton 1.jpg\n| name = Peter Walton\n| fullname = Peter Walton\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1959|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Long Buckby]], [[Northamptonshire]], [[England]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| otheroccupation = \n| years1              = 1993-1994\n| league1             = [[The Football League|Football League]]\n| role1               = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referee]]\n| years2              = 1994-1998\n| league2             = [[Premier League]]\n| role2               = Assistant referee\n| years3              = 1998-2003\n| league3             = Football League\n| role3               = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years4              = 2003-2012\n| league4             = Premier League\n| role4               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 1996-1998\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA listed]]\n| internationalrole1  = Assistant referee\n}}\n'''Peter Walton''' (born 10 October 1959)<ref>[http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0,,10794~628215,00.html Birthdate and biographical details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115195943/http://www.football-league.premiumtv.co.uk/page/RefereeProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10794~628215%2C00.html |date=15 January 2008 }}: [[Football League|The Football League]] Official website.</ref> is an [[England|English]] former professional [[Association football|football]] [[referee (association football)|referee]] who officiated in the [[Premier League]] from 2003 to 2012. Beginning 2013, he was general manager of the [[Professional Referee Organization]] (PRO) in North America until being replaced by [[Howard Webb]] in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=PROreferees.com |publisher=PROreferees.com |url=http://www.proreferees.com/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=PRO promotes Howard Webb to General Manager|publisher=PROreferees.com|url=http://proreferees.com/2018/01/18/pro-promotes-howard-webb-to-general-manager/}}</ref>\n\nWalton is also a former player in the [[United Counties Football League|United Counties League]]. He is based in [[Long Buckby]],<ref>[http://www.pink-un.com/Content/ncfc/statattack/2000-01/matches/asp/001216Grimsby.asp Home town]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} reference example: ''The Pink-Un'' online.</ref> [[Northamptonshire]], the village which he played his football for.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060621162104/http://stneotsfc.net/news/UCL_03August.pdf Playing career] reference: ''UCL  Newsletter 168 August 2003''.</ref> He lists his interests as current affairs and golf.<ref>[http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enRefereesProfile&id=374253&type=com.fapl.website.stories.SimpleStories&categoryCode=Referees Hobbies and interests] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114105937/http://www.premierleague.com/fapl.rac?command=setSelectedId&nextPage=enRefereesProfile&id=374253&type=com.fapl.website.stories.SimpleStories&categoryCode=Referees |date=14 November 2006 }}, plus further biography: [[Premier League]] Official website.</ref>\n\nDuring his professional career which spanned nearly 20 years, Walton refereed a number of notable matches, including the 2003 final of the [[Football League Trophy]] and the [[FA Community Shield]] in 2008.\n\n==Career==\nWalton began refereeing in 1986 in local leagues. He was appointed to the assistant referees' lists of [[the Football League]] in 1993, and the [[Premier League]] in 1994.\n\nIn 1996, he was an assistant referee for the [[1996 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], when [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] defeated [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] with a late [[Eric Cantona]] goal.\n\nIn the same year he became a [[FIFA]] assistant referee, officiating in that capacity