ivision Three|(old) Division Three]] [[play-off]] [[semi-final]] [[leg (sport)|first leg]].</ref> at the end of the [[2002-03 in English football|2002-03 season]].\n\nHis first Premier League appointment was a 4\u20133 home win by [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] at [[Molineux Stadium]] on 25 October 2003.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=404869 First ever] [[Premier League]] match: soccerbase.com website.</ref>\n\nAt the end of January 2007, Walton accompanied Regional Referees' Manager [[Ray Olivier]] (a Football League referee himself) to [[Guayaquil]], Ecuador, to undertake an Advanced Course for Referees' Instructors on behalf of [[the Football Association]] and [[CONMEBOL]].<ref>[http://www.conmebol.com/comunicados_ver.jsp?id=60211&slangab=E Ecuador] trip with Ray Olivier: [[Confederaci\u00f3n Sudamericana de F\u00fatbol]] website.</ref> Olivier is quoted as saying: \"It is also a great fillip to have someone of Peter's calibre as part of the team and his experience of refereeing in the Premiership is invaluable to those referees taking part in this workshop.\"<ref>[http://www.thefa.com/TheFA/InternationalRelations/NewsAndFeatures/Postings/2007/01/OlivierWalton.htm Ecuador] trip with Ray Olivier: [[The Football Association|TheFA.com]] website.</ref>\n\nWalton refereed the [[2008 FA Community Shield]] match between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], issuing three cautions during the game between the Premier League champions and FA Cup winners of the previous season, which United won 3\u20131 on penalties after extra-time.\n\nWalton's last appointment as a Premier League referee was [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]'s 2\u20130 home win over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on 31 March 2012. He then took up a new role as the general manager of the [[Professional Referee Organization]] (PRO) for the Football Leagues in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]], from 2 April 2012.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120911021345/http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/walton-to-head-us-referees-body.html]</ref>\n\nUpon his appointment, Walton said to proreferees.com: \"I think the referees we've got in North America are very good.\n\n\u201cI think the competitive nature of our leagues are very good as well and what I'm intending to do is match-up the referee abilities to that of the playing side.\n\n\"We can see great strides being taken with the league and with the infrastructure, with the players and I must make sure our referees are running parallel to that so we advance at the same pace and there isn't a gap developing or developed.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Walton: \"a long-term building process\" |publisher=PROreferees.com |url=http://www.proreferees.com/news-walton-a-long-term-building-process.php |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919000416/http://www.proreferees.com/news-walton-a-long-term-building-process.php |archivedate=19 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nWalton currently works as a referee analyst for BT Sport's coverage of the UEFA Champions League, discussing key decisions and explaining the usage of VAR, both in-game and post-match. During the 2019 Champions League semi-final second leg between Tottenham and Ajax, a celebrating Walton, in his BT studio, was inadvertently broadcast in the midst of the dramatic scenes following Tottenham's late winning goal. Walton also regularly appears on [[ESPN FC]].\n\n==Card statistics==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Season!!Games!!Total {{yel}}!!{{yel}} per game!!Total {{sent off}}!!{{sent off}} per game\n|-\n|'''[[1998-99 in English football|1998/99]]'''||32||99||''3.09''||8||''0.25''\n|-\n|'''[[1999-00 in English football|1999/00]]'''||31||86||''2.77''||4||''0.13''\n|-\n|'''[[2000-01 in English football|2000/01]]'''||37||102||''2.76''||7||''0.19''\n|-\n|'''[[2001-02 in English football|2001/02]]'''||35||113||''3.23''||13||''0.37''\n|-\n|'''[[2002-03 in English football|2002/03]]'''||45||129||''2.87''||8||''0.18''\n|-\n|'''[[2003-04 in English football|2003/04]]'''||31||64||''2.06''||4||''0.13''\n|-\n|'''[[2004-05 in English football|2004/05]]'''||31||87||''2.81''||2||''0.06''\n|-\n|'''[[2005-06 in English football|2005/06]]'''||42||126||''3.00''||6||''0.14''\n|-\n|'''[[2006-07 in English football|2006/07]]'''||40||128||''3.20''||4||''0.10''\n|-\n|'''[[2007-08 in English football|2007/08]]'''||41||123||''3.00''||5||''0.12''\n|-\n|'''[[2008-09 in English football|2008/09]]'''||43||97||''2.25''||4||''0.09''\n|-\n|'''[[2009\u201310 in English football|2009/10]]'''||36||91||''2.53''||6||''0.16''\n|-\n|'''[[2010\u201311 in English football|2010/11]]'''||33||110||''3.33''||9||''0.27''\n|-\n|'''[[2011\u201312 in English football|2011/12]]'''||22||68||''3.09''||2||''0.09''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of football referees]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091212183420/http://www.refworld.com/referee/23/0/peter-walton Peter Walton Profile] at Refworld.com\n{{commons category|Peter Walton}}\n*[http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=243 Peter Walton Referee Statistics] at [[soccerbase]].com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walton, Peter}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:Premier League referees]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Long Buckby]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Walton_(referee)"}
{"title_page": "Anthoine Hubert", "text_new": "{{short description|French racing driver}}\n{{about|the racing driver|the musician|Antoine Huberty}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Anthoine Hubert\n| image             = Anthoine Hubert 2013 (cropped).JPG\n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = Anthoine Hubert (2013)\n| nationality       = French\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1996|09|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Lyon]], France\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|2019|08|31|1996|09|22|df=y}}\n| death_place       = [[Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps]], Belgium\n| last series    = [[FIA Formula 2 Championship]]\n| first year        = [[2019 FIA Formula 2 Championship|2019]]\n| teams      = [[Arden International|BWT Arden]]\n| car number        = 19 (retired in honour)<ref name=\"#19\"/>\n| former teams      = \n| championships     = \n| starts            = 16\n| wins              = 2\n| poles             = 0\n| fastest laps      = 0\n| best finish       = \n| year              = [[2019 FIA Formula 2 Championship|2019]]\n| prev series       = {{nobr|[[GP3 Series]]<br>[[FIA Formula 3 European Championship]]}}<br>[[Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0]]<br>[[Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]]<br>[[French F4 Championship]]\n| prev series years = [[2017 GP3 Series|2017]]\u2013[[2018 GP3 Series|18]]<br>[[2016 FIA Formula 3 European Championship|2016]]<br>[[2014 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0|2014]]\u2013[[2015 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0|15]]<br>[[2014 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps season|2014]]\u2013[[2015 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps season|15]]<br>[[2013 French F4 Championship|2013]]\n| titles            = [[GP3 Series]]<br>[[French F4 Championship]]\n| title years       = [[2018 GP3 Series|2018]]<br>[[2013 French F4 Championship|2013]]\n}}\n\n'''Anthoine Hubert''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0251\u0303twan yb\u025b\u0281}}; 22 September 1996 \u2013 31 August 2019) was a [[France|French]] professional racing driver. He was the [[2018 GP3 Series]] champion. He died, aged 22, following an accident during the feature race of the [[2019 Spa-Francorchamps FIA Formula 2 round]] at the [[Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Karting===\nBorn in [[Lyon]], Hubert began his [[kart racing|karting]] career in 2004 at age twelve.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/49537765|title=Anthoine Hubert Formula 2 death: Why the motorsport 'family' races on|last=Benson|first=Andrew|date=31 August 2019|access-date=19 December 2019|website=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> In 2010 he finished as runner-up in the CIK-FIA Karting Academy Trophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/cik-fia-karting-academy-trophy/2010/|title=CIK-FIA Karting Academy Trophy 2010 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208031406/https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/cik-fia-karting-academy-trophy/2010/|archive-date=8 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In the 2011 and 2012 CIK-FIA \"U18\" World Karting Championships, he finished third.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/u18-world-karting-championship/2011/|title=CIK-FIA \"U18\" World Karting Championship 2011 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427013215/http://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/u18-world-karting-championship/2011/|archive-date=27 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/u18-world-karting-championship/2012/|title=CIK-FIA \"U18\" World Karting Championship 2012 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012034812/https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/u18-world-karting-championship/2012/|archive-date=12 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Formula Renault===\nIn [[2013 French F4 Championship|2013]], Hubert moved up to [[open-wheel car|single-seater]] racing, joining the [[French F4 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autosportacademy.com/gb/competition/2013-season/news/p/20/r/26405/15022013-the-2013-french-f4-championship-field-is-taking-shape.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130407175310/http://www.autosportacademy.com/gb/competition/2013-season/news/p/20/r/26405/15022013-the-2013-french-f4-championship-field-is-taking-shape.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 April 2013 |title=The 2013 French F4 Championship field is taking shape |date=15 February 2013 |work=Auto Sport Academy |publisher=[[French F4 Championship]] |accessdate=14 August 2016 }}</ref> He went on to win the series on his first attempt, finishing the season with eleven wins and two further podium finishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/french-f4-championship/2013/|title=French F4 Championship 2013 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207092044/https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/french-f4-championship/2013/|archive-date=7 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2014 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0 season|2014]], he graduated to competing in the [[Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0]] with [[Tech 1 Racing]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/hubert-romanov-join-orudzhev-in-tech-1s-eurocup-lineup/|title=Hubert, Romanov join Orudzhev in Tech 1's Eurocup lineup|work=PaddockScout.com|publisher=Paddock Scout|last=Khorounzhiy|first=Valentin|date=8 January 2014|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011045321/http://www.paddockscout.com/hubert-romanov-join-orudzhev-in-tech-1s-eurocup-lineup/|archive-date=11 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He finished fifteenth overall, with six point-scoring finishes throughout the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.driverdb.com/standings/129-2014/|title=Formula Renault 2.0 Eurocup 2014|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref> He also participated in [[2014 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps season|Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]] as guest driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/formula-renault-20-alps/2014/|title=Formula Renault 2.0 Alps 2014 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200753/https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/formula-renault-20-alps/2014/|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[2015 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0 season|2015 season]] Hubert remained in the Eurocup and with Tech 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/tech-1-racing-retain-hubert-for-2015-eurocup-campaign/|title=Tech 1 Racing retain Hubert for 2015 Eurocup campaign|last=Khorounzhiy|first=Valentin|date=5 March 2015|publisher=Paddock Scout|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306102916/http://www.paddockscout.com/tech-1-racing-retain-hubert-for-2015-eurocup-campaign|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He finished fifth in the championship with wins at Silverstone and Le Mans and another five podiums to his name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formulascout.com/2015-eurocup-formula-renault-2-0-season-review/31615|title=2015 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0 season review|last=David|first=Gruz|date=7 November 2015|publisher=Formula Scout|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607164755/http://www.formulascout.com/2015-eurocup-formula-renault-2-0-season-review/31615|archive-date=7 June 2017|url-status=live|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> He also contested selected events in the [[2015 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps season|Alps series]], where he won four of the six races that he started, and finished second in other two races.<ref name=2016F3Confirmed/>\n\n===Formula 3===\nIn February 2016, it was confirmed that Hubert would make his debut in the [[European Formula 3 Championship]], racing with [[Van Amersfoort Racing]].<ref name=2016F3Confirmed>{{cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-european-masters/news/hubert-completes-van-amersfoort-line-up-676314/676314/|title=Hubert completes Van Amersfoort line-up|last= Khorounzhiy|first=Valentin|publisher=motorsport.com|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref> He took his first Formula 3 win in the second race at [[Norisring]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/anthoine-hubert-takes-his-debut-win-in-the-second-european-f3-race-at-the-norisring/34901|title=Hubert takes debut F3 win in second Norisring race|last=Bosley|first=Jacob|date=25 June 2016|publisher=Paddock Scout|accessdate=14 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812081425/http://www.paddockscout.com/anthoine-hubert-takes-his-debut-win-in-the-second-european-f3-race-at-the-norisring/34901|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===GP3 Series===\nIn November 2016, Hubert participated in F3 post-season testing with [[ART Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gp3series.com/News/2016/12_December/Driver-entry-list-for-day-3-of-post-season-test/|title=Driver entry list for day 3 of post-season test|publisher=GP3 Series|date=1 December 2016|accessdate=1 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202120122/http://www.gp3series.com/News/2016/12_December/Driver-entry-list-for-day-3-of-post-season-test/|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2017, he was recruited by ART to compete in the [[2017 GP3 Series|2017]] championship. He remained with them for the 2018 season, winning the title and gaining reputation with Formula 1 teams such as Renault.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gp3series.com/News/2017/02_February/ART-sign-Hubert-/|title=ART signs Hubert|publisher=GP3 Series|date=February 23, 2017|accessdate=February 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223180820/http://www.gp3series.com/News/2017/02_February/ART-sign-Hubert-/|archive-date=23 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===FIA Formula 2 Championship===\nIn November 2018, Hubert participated in the F2 post-season test at Abu Dhabi with [[MP Motorsport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f2/news/911405/1/gp3-champion-hubert-included-f2-abu-dhabi-test-lineup|title=GP3 champion Hubert included in F2 Abu Dhabi test line-up|last=Larkam|first=Lewis|work=Crash.net|date=November 28, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123223033/https://www.crash.net/f2/news/911405/1/gp3-champion-hubert-included-f2-abu-dhabi-test-lineup|archive-date=23 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, Hubert joined F2 full-time racing with [[Arden International|BWT Arden]]. He took two wins in the first half of his debut season, at Monaco and at his home race in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2019/01_january/Anthoine-Hubert-joins-BWT-Arden-for-2019-season/|title=Anthoine Hubert Joins BWT Arden for 2019 Season|publisher=FIA Formula 2|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321080630/http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2019/01_january/Anthoine-Hubert-joins-BWT-Arden-for-2019-season/|archive-date=21 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Formula One===\nIn May 2018, Hubert became an affiliated driver with the [[Renault Sport Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.renaultsport.com/anthoine-hubert-becomes-first-renault-sport-affiliated-driver.html|title=Anthoine Hubert becomes first Renault Sport Affiliated Driver|publisher=Renault Sport|date=11 May 2018|accessdate=23 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123223209/https://www.renaultsport.com/anthoine-hubert-becomes-first-renault-sport-affiliated-driver.html|archive-date=23 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Hubert received full backing from the Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsportweek.com/news/id/21294|title=GP3 champion Anthoine Hubert joins Renault F1 scheme, makes F2 move|last=Horton|first=Phillip|work=Motorsport Week|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123223657/https://www.motorsportweek.com/news/id/21294|archive-date=23 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n{{See also|2019 Spa-Francorchamps FIA Formula 2 round}}\nOn 31 August 2019, Hubert was involved in a serious crash on the second lap of the feature race of the [[2019 Spa-Francorchamps FIA Formula 2 round]]. As the second lap began, [[Trident Racing|Trident]] driver [[Giuliano Alesi]] lost control of his car as he climbed the Raidillon curve due to a puncture he had received earlier, causing his car to spin and hit the left wall of the circuit, tearing off his rear wing and spreading debris onto the track. As another Trident driver, [[Ralph Boschung]] reached the crest of Raidillon, he slowed down and moved towards the run-off area to avoid Alesi's damaged car and the field of debris. Hubert, who was following Boschung closely and had no view of what had happened to Alesi, moved right to avoid Boschung's slowing car, clipping Boschung's right rear wheel with his front wing. Hubert's car crashed into the tyre barrier on the right side of the track at an acute angle and was deflected sideways into the path of [[Charouz Racing System|Charouz]] driver [[Juan Manuel Correa]], who struck the left side of Hubert's car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejudge13.com/2019/09/02/serious-questions-need-answers-new-analysis-on-how-it-happened/|title=Fatal F2 crash: detailed new analysis on how it happened, is action needed?|website=thejudge13}}</ref> Correa's speed was estimated to be between 250 and 270&nbsp;km/h (155-167&nbsp;mph) in the moments before the impact.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.auto-motor-und-sport.de/formel-1/hubert-unfallanalyse-laeuft-an-correa-geht-es-besser/|title=Hubert-Unfallanalyse l\u00e4uft an: Correa geht es besser|last=Schmidt|first=Michael|date=2019-09-01|website=auto motor und sport|language=de|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref> The impact producing 70G deceleration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://f1i.com/news/362605-correa-says-very-bad-luck-caused-tragic-spa-accident.html|title=Correa says 'very bad luck' caused tragic Spa accident|date=23 November 2019}}</ref> Both cars were torn apart by the force of the accident. Hubert and Correa were transported to the circuit's medical centre following the accident where Hubert died from his injuries.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.fia.com/news/statement-incident-during-fia-formula-2-sprint-race-spa-francorchamps|title=Statement: Incident during FIA Formula 2 Sprint Race, Spa-Francorchamps|date=2019-08-31|work=Federation Internationale de l'Automobile|access-date=2019-08-31|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC49537761\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/motorsport/49537761 |title=Formula 2: Anthoine Hubert killed in Belgium crash |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=31 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831164344/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/motorsport/49537761 |archive-date=31 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCorrea was airlifted to [[Li\u00e8ge]] where he underwent surgery for fractures in both his legs and a minor spinal injury and was reported to be in a stable condition, having never lost consciousness after the impact, but one week later was placed in an induced coma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/fia-f2/news/correa-stable-surgery-crash-injuries/4526406/|title=Correa listed as stable after surgery for crash injuries|publisher=Motorsport.com|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> Alesi, the third driver in the accident, was unhurt. As a result of the accident the feature race was [[Racing flags#red flag|not completed]] and the sprint race was cancelled out of respect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.statement-anthoine-hubert.3YZvWvyy8XuGZOvmVrCO27.html|title=Statement: Anthoine Hubert|date=31 August 2019|website=formula1|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, many drivers and teams in the motorsport world paid tribute to Hubert.<ref name=\"speedcafe 1sept\">{{cite web|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2019/09/01/f1-paddock-pays-tribute-to-late-hubert/|title=F1 paddock pays tribute to late Hubert|first=Daniel|last=Herrero|work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]]|publisher=[[Speedcafe]]|date=1 September 2019|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> On 1 September, a minute's silence was observed before the Formula 3 and Formula 1 races at Spa.<ref name=BBC49542632>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/formula1/49542632 |title=Anthoine Hubert: Formula 1 pays tribute with minute's silence before Belgian GP |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> Former F3 competitor and [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] Formula One driver [[Charles Leclerc]], who won his first career race that afternoon, dedicated his win to Hubert.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/leclerc-first-win-hubert-tribute/4527008/|title=Leclerc: First career win \"difficult\" to enjoy after Hubert tragedy|publisher=Motorsport.com|date=1 September 2019|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> A standing ovation took place on the 19th lap of the race, corresponding to the number 19 of his Formula 2 car. Before the start of the race, all racing safety vehicles, safety car, medical car, track inspection car, ambulance, car recovery vehicles, etc. made a lap of Circuit de Spa Francorchamps as a tribute to Hubert. All F1 cars had Hubert's car number inside a star and the words \"Racing for Anthoine\".\n\nThe [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] launched an investigation into the accident.<ref name=FIA>{{cite web |url=https://www.fia.com/news/statement-incident-during-fia-formula-2-feature-race-spa-francorchamps |title=Statement: Incident during FIA Formula 2 Feature Race, Spa-Francorchamps  |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile |date=31 August 2019 |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> Findings of the Accident Investigation were presented to the World Motor Sport Council, together with recommended actions in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fia.com/news/fia-announces-world-motor-sport-council-decisions-16|title=FIA ANNOUNCES WORLD MOTOR SPORT COUNCIL DECISIONS|date=5 December 2019|website=Federation Internationale de l'Automobile}}</ref> F2 cars are built to the same safety standard as F1 cars,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maxf1.net/en/technical-specification-new-f2-2018-car-never-so-close-to-f1/|title=Technical specification: New F2 2018 car never so close to F1|first=Darjan|last=Petric|date=23 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/championship/inside-f1/safety/cockpit-crash-tests/Cockpit_safety.html|title=Cockpit safety|website=Formula 1\u00ae - The Official F1\u00ae Website}}</ref> however, following the accident Racing Point tech boss Andy Green commented: \"The energy involved was absolutely huge, and the current chassis design, whether F2 or F1, there's no way a current chassis can survive that sort of impact.\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://f1i.com/news/355143-f1-considers-safety-changes-for-2020-following-hubert-crash-investigation.html|title=F1 considers safety changes for 2020 following Hubert crash investigation|first=Phillip van|last=Osten|date=21 September 2019}}</ref> The FIA finished this investigation in February 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.letstalkmotorsport.com/2020/fia-concludes-investigation-into-formula-2-accident-at-spa-francorchamps/|title=Fia Concludes investigation into Formula 2  accident  at Spa Francorchamps|date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n \nHubert's funeral was on 10 September at [[Chartres Cathedral]], [[Eure-et-Loire]]. It was attended by his family, friends and many people from the motorsport world, including [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] president [[Jean Todt]], Renault F1 advisor and four-time champion [[Alain Prost]], [[Charles Leclerc]], [[Pierre Gasly]], [[Esteban Ocon]], and [[George Russell (racing driver)|George Russell]].<ref name=Funeral>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11806486/anthoine-hubert-respects-paid-at-f2-drivers-funeral-in-france |title=Anthoine Hubert: Respects paid at F2 driver's funeral in France |publisher=Sky News |date=10 September 2019 |accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref> Hubert's car number, 19, was later announced to have been retired from use in [[Formula 2]] for the remainder of the season with his replacement [[Artem Markelov]] running the #22 in place of the #19.<ref name=\"#19\">{{Cite web|url=https://formulaspy.com/f1/markelov-joins-arden-as-huberts-19-is-retired-64730|title=F2 - Markelov joins Arden as Hubert's #19 is retired|date=2019-09-24|website=FormulaSpy|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nAt the FIA Formula 2 Championship prize-giving ceremony in Monaco in 2019 the [[FIA Formula 2 Championship#Anthoine Hubert Award|''Anthoine Hubert Award'']] was introduced. It is named after Hubert who was the only rookie in the season to score two wins.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2019/12_December/Formula-2-introduces-the-Anthoine-Hubert-Award/|title=Formula 2 introduces the Anthoine Hubert Award - Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com}}</ref> The award is given to the highest-placed driver without previous Formula 2 experience.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Allen |first1=Peter |title=F2 introduces Anthoine Hubert Award, presented to Guanyu Zhou |url=http://www.formulascout.com/f2-introduces-anthoine-hubert-award-presented-to-guanyu-zhou/57534 |accessdate=12 December 2019 |work=formulascout.com |publisher=Formula Scout |date=12 December 2019}}</ref> The inaugural recipient of the Anthoine Hubert Award is [[Guanyu Zhou]].\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career summary===\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%; text-align:center\"\n! Season\n! Series\n! Team\n! Races\n! Wins\n! Poles\n! F/Laps\n! Podiums\n! Points\n! Position\n|-\n! 2013\n|align=left| [[2013 French F4 Championship|French F4 Championship]]\n|align=left| [[French F4 Championship|Autosport Academy]]\n| 21\n| 11\n| 10\n| 8\n| 13\n| 365\n|style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| '''1st'''\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 2014\n|align=left| [[2014 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0|Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0]]\n|align=left rowspan=2| [[Tech 1 Racing]]\n| 14\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 30\n| 15th\n|-\n|align=left| [[2014 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps season|Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]]\n| 6\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| N/A\n| NC\u2020\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 2015\n|align=left| [[2015 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0|Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0]]\n|align=left rowspan=2| [[Tech 1 Racing]]\n| 17\n| 2\n| 2\n| 2\n| 7\n| 172\n| 5th\n|-\n|align=left| [[2015 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps season|Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]]\n| 6\n| 4\n| 4\n| 3\n| 6\n| N/A\n| NC\u2020\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 2016\n|align=left| [[2016 FIA Formula 3 European Championship|FIA Formula 3 European Championship]]\n|align=left rowspan=3| [[Van Amersfoort Racing]]\n| 30\n| 1\n| 1\n| 1\n| 3\n| 160\n| 8th\n|-\n|align=left| [[2016 Masters of Formula 3|Masters of Formula 3]]\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| N/A\n| 7th\n|-\n|align=left| [[2016 Macau Grand Prix|Macau Grand Prix]]\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| N/A\n| 13th\n|-\n! 2017\n|align=left| [[2017 GP3 Series|GP3 Series]]\n|align=left| [[ART Grand Prix]]\n| 15\n| 0\n| 0\n| 4\n| 4\n| 123\n| 4th\n|-\n! 2018\n|align=left| [[2018 GP3 Series|GP3 Series]]\n|align=left| [[ART Grand Prix]]\n| 18\n| 2\n| 2\n| 4\n| 11\n| 214\n|style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| '''1st'''\n|-\n! 2019\n|align=left| [[2019 FIA Formula 2 Championship|FIA Formula 2 Championship]]\