{"title_page": "Antenor (mythology)", "text_new": "{{about|the mythological figure|the historical sculptor|Antenor|other uses|Antenor (disambiguation)}}\nIn [[Greek mythology]], '''Antenor''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: \u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03c1 ''Ant\u1e17n\u014dr'') was a [[Counselor (diplomat)|counselor]] to [[Priam|King Priam]]  of [[Troy (mythology)|Troy]] during the events of the [[Trojan War]].\n\n\n\n{{anchor|History|Legend|Biography}}\n\n==Family==\nAntenor was variously named as the son of the [[Dardanoi|Dardanian]] noble [[Aesyetes]] by [[Cleomestra]]<ref>[[Dictys Cretensis]], ''Trojan War Chronicle'' 4.22</ref> or of [[Hicetaon]].<ref>[[Eustathius of Thessalonica|Eustathius]] on Homer, p. 349; [[scholia]] on ''Iliad'', 3. 201</ref> He was the husband of [[Theano]], daughter of [[Cisseus]] of [[Thrace]], who bore him at least one daughter, [[Crino]], and numerous sons, including [[Archelochus]], [[Acamas (son of Antenor)|Acamas]], [[Glaucus (mythology)|Glaucus]], [[Helicaon]], [[Laodocus]], [[Co\u00f6n]], [[Polybus (Trojan War)|Polybus]], [[Agenor, son of Antenor|Agenor]], [[Iphidamas]], [[Laodamas]], [[Demoleon]], [[Eurymachus]], [[Hippolochus (mythology)|Hippolochus]], [[Medon]], [[Thersilochus]], and [[Antheus]] (most of whom perished during the [[Trojan War]]).{{sfn|Parada|F\u00f6rlag|1997}} He was also the father of a son, [[Pedaeus]], by an unknown woman. According to numerous scholars, Antenor was actually related to Priam.{{sfn|Lempri\u00e8re|1822|p=85}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Comparative table of Antenor's family\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Relation\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Names\n! colspan=\"8\" |Sources\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |''Homer''\n|''Virgil''\n|''Apollodorus''\n|''Pausanias''\n|''Dictys''\n|''Tzetzes''\n|''Eustathius''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Parentage''\n|Aesyetes and Cleomestra\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|-\n|Hicetaon\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Spouse''\n|Theano\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\" |''Children''\n|Crino\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Archelochus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Acamas\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Glaucus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\u2713\n|\u2713\n|\u2713\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|-\n|Helicaon\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Laodocus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Pedaeus\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Co\u00f6n\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Polybus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Agenor\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Iphidamas\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Laodamas\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Demoleon\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Eurymachus\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Hippolochus\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Medon\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Thersilochus\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Antheus\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|}\n\n== Mythology ==\nAntenor was one of the wisest of the Trojan elders and counsellors.{{sfn|''EB''|1911}} In the [[Homer]]ic account of the [[Trojan War]], Antenor advised the Trojans to return [[Helen of Troy|Helen]] to [[Menelaus|her husband]] and otherwise proved sympathetic to a negotiated peace with the [[Achaeans (Homer)|Greeks]].{{sfn|''EB''|1878}} In later developments of the myths, particularly per [[Dares]] and [[Dictys Cretensis|Dictys]],{{sfn|''EB''|1911}} Antenor was made an open [[treason|traitor]], unsealing the city gates to the enemy. As payment, his house\u2014marked by a [[panthera|panther]] skin over the door\u2014was spared during the sack of the city.{{sfn|''EB''|1878}}\n\nHis subsequent fate varied across the authors. He was said to have rebuilt a city on the site of [[Troy]]; to have settled at [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]];{{sfn|''EB''|1878}} or to have founded [[Patavium]] (modern [[Padua]]),<ref>[[Virgil]], ''[[Aeneid]]'', Book I, l. 242.</ref><ref>[[Livy]]. ''[[Ab Urbe Condita Libri (Livy)|History of Rome]]'', Vol.&nbsp;I, Ch.&nbsp;I.</ref> [[Kor\u010dula]],{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} or other cities in eastern Italy.{{sfn|''EB''|1878}}\n\n==In literature==\n\n* Antenor appears briefly in [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]''. In Book 3 he is present when Helen identifies for Priam each of the Greek warriors from the wall of Troy; when she describes Odysseus, Antenor criticizes her, saying how he entertained Odysseus and Menelaus and got to know both. In Book 7, as mentioned above, he advises the Trojans to give Helen back, but [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] refuses to yield.\n* Antenor is mentioned in [[Vergil]]'s [[Aeneid]] in book 1, line 243, when Venus tells Jupiter that Antenor had escaped from the fall of [[Troy]] and founded Patavium, modern Padua.\n* In [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[Troilus and Criseyde]]'', Antenor appears as a minor, non-speaking, character who has been taken prisoner by the Greeks but is returned by them in exchange for [[Criseyde]].\n* The circle ''Antenora'' is named after him in the poem ''[[Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]]'' in [[Dante Alighieri]]'s ''[[Divine Comedy]]''. It is located in [[Hell]]'s Circle of Treachery which is reserved for traitors of cities, countries, and political parties.\n\n==Eponym==\nThe [[minor planet]] [[2207 Antenor]], discovered in 1977 by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] astronomer [[Nikolai Stepanovich Chernykh]], is named after him.{{sfn|Schmadel|2003|p=293}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Antenor (1.) |volume=2  |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |page=102 }}\n* {{citation |last=Cheetham |first=Erica |year=1985 |page=[https://archive.org/details/furtherprophecie00chee/page/76 76] |title=The Prophecies of Nostradamus |publisher=Perigee Books (a division of Putnam Pub. Group) |isbn=0399511210 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/furtherprophecie00chee/page/76 }}\n* {{cite EB1911 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Antenor (mythology)|display=Antenor |volume=2 |ref={{harvid|EB|1911}} |pages=92\u201393 }}\n*{{citation |last=Lempri\u00e8re |first=John |authorlink=John Lempri\u00e8re |chapter=Ant\u0113nor |title=[[Bibliotheca Classica|A Classical Dictionary: Containing a Copious Account of All Proper Names Mentioned in Ancient Authors, with the Value of Coins, Weights, and Measures Used Among the Greeks and Romans, and a Chronological Table]] |year=1822|publisher=J. Crissy|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=udw7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PR86 86]}}\n* {{citation |last=Parada  |first=Carlos |last2=F\u00f6rlag|first2=Maicar  |year=1997 \n|publisher=Greek Mythology Link (Carlos Parada) |url=http://www.maicar.com/GML/Antenor1.html |title=Antenor |accessdate=8 January 2017}}.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2017}}\n*{{citation  |last=Proust |first=Marcel |title=The Guermantes Way  |volume=3 |series= Remembrance of Things Past   |edition=Pleiade |page=225}}.{{full citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n* {{citation |last=Schmadel |first=Lutz D. |year=2003 |title=Dictionary of Minor Planet Names |edition=5th |publisher=Springer Verlag |location=New York | isbn=3-540-00238-3 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2lzoCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA293#v=onepage&q&f=false 293]}}\n\n{{Characters in the Iliad}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:People of the Trojan War]]\n[[Category:Characters in the Iliad]]\n[[Category:Trojans]]\n[[Category:Characters in Greek mythology]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the mythological figure|the historical sculptor|Antenor|other uses|Antenor (disambiguation)}}\nIn [[Greek mythology]], '''Antenor''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: \u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03ae\u03bd\u03c9\u03c1 ''Ant\u1e17n\u014dr'') was a [[Counselor (diplomat)|counselor]] to [[Priam|King Priam]]  of [[Troy (mythology)|Troy]] during the events of the [[Trojan War]].\n\n\n\n{{anchor|History|Legend|Biography}}\n\n==Family==\nAntenor was variously named as the son of the [[Dardanoi|Dardanian]] noble [[Aesyetes]] by [[Cleomestra]]<ref>[[Dictys Cretensis]], ''Trojan War Chronicle'' 4.22</ref> or of [[Hicetaon]]<ref>[[Eustathius of Thessalonica|Eustathius]] on Homer, p. 349; [[scholia]] on ''Iliad'', 3. 201</ref>. He was the husband of [[Theano]], daughter of [[Cisseus]] of [[Thrace]], who bore him at least one daughter, [[Crino]], and numerous sons, including [[Archelochus]], [[Acamas (son of Antenor)|Acamas]], [[Glaucus (mythology)|Glaucus]], [[Helicaon]], [[Laodocus]], [[Co\u00f6n]], [[Polybus (Trojan War)|Polybus]], [[Agenor, son of Antenor|Agenor]], [[Iphidamas]], [[Laodamas]], [[Demoleon]], [[Eurymachus]], [[Hippolochus (mythology)|Hippolochus]], [[Medon]], [[Thersilochus]], and [[Antheus]] (most of whom perished during the [[Trojan War]]).{{sfn|Parada|F\u00f6rlag|1997}} He was also the father of a son, [[Pedaeus]], by an unknown woman. According to numerous scholars, Antenor was actually related to Priam.{{sfn|Lempri\u00e8re|1822|p=85}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Comparative table of Antenor's family\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Relation\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Names\n! colspan=\"8\" |Sources\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |''Homer''\n|''Virgil''\n|''Apollodorus''\n|''Pausanias''\n|''Dictys''\n|''Tzetzes''\n|''Eustathius''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Parentage''\n|Aesyetes and Cleomestra\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|-\n|Hicetaon\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Spouse''\n|Theano\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|''Unknown''\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"18\" |''Children''\n|Crino\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Archelochus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Acamas\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Glaucus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\u2713\n|\u2713\n|\u2713\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|-\n|Helicaon\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Laodocus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Pedaeus\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Co\u00f6n\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Polybus\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Agenor\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Iphidamas\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Laodamas\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Demoleon\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Eurymachus\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Hippolochus\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Medon\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Thersilochus\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|Antheus\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\u2713\n|\n|}\n\n== Mythology ==\nAntenor was one of the wisest of the Trojan elders and counsellors.{{sfn|''EB''|1911}} In the [[Homer]]ic account of the [[Trojan War]], Antenor advised the Trojans to return [[Helen of Troy|Helen]] to [[Menelaus|her husband]] and otherwise proved sympathetic to a negotiated peace with the [[Achaeans (Homer)|Greeks]].{{sfn|''EB''|1878}} In later developments of the myths, particularly per [[Dares]] and [[Dictys Cretensis|Dictys]],{{sfn|''EB''|1911}} Antenor was made an open [[treason|traitor]], unsealing the city gates to the enemy. As payment, his house\u2014marked by a [[panthera|panther]] skin over the door\u2014was spared during the sack of the city.{{sfn|''EB''|1878}}\n\nHis subsequent fate varied across the authors. He was said to have rebuilt a city on the site of [[Troy]]; to have settled at [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]];{{sfn|''EB''|1878}} or to have founded [[Patavium]] (modern [[Padua]]),<ref>[[Virgil]], ''[[Aeneid]]'', Book I, l. 242.</ref><ref>[[Livy]]. ''[[Ab Urbe Condita Libri (Livy)|History of Rome]]'', Vol.&nbsp;I, Ch.&nbsp;I.</ref> [[Kor\u010dula]],{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} or other cities in eastern Italy.{{sfn|''EB''|1878}}\n\n==In literature==\n\n* Antenor appears briefly in [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]''. In Book 3 he is present when Helen identifies for Priam each of the Greek warriors from the wall of Troy; when she describes Odysseus, Antenor criticizes her, saying how he entertained Odysseus and Menelaus and got to know both. In Book 7, as mentioned above, he advises the Trojans to give Helen back, but [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] refuses to yield.\n* Antenor is mentioned in [[Vergil]]'s [[Aeneid]] in book 1, line 243, when Venus tells Jupiter that Antenor had escaped from the fall of [[Troy]] and founded Patavium, modern Padua.\n* In [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[Troilus and Criseyde]]'', Antenor appears as a minor, non-speaking, character who has been taken prisoner by the Greeks but is returned by them in exchange for [[Criseyde]].\n* The circle ''Antenora'' is named after him in the poem ''[[Inferno (Dante)|Inferno]]'' in [[Dante Alighieri]]'s ''[[Divine Comedy]]''. It is located in [[Hell]]'s Circle of Treachery which is reserved for traitors of cities, countries, and political parties.\n\n==Eponym==\nThe [[minor planet]] [[2207 Antenor]], discovered in 1977 by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] astronomer [[Nikolai Stepanovich Chernykh]], is named after him.{{sfn|Schmadel|2003|p=293}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Antenor (1.) |volume=2  |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |page=102 }}\n* {{citation |last=Cheetham |first=Erica |year=1985 |page=[https://archive.org/details/furtherprophecie00chee/page/76 76] |title=The Prophecies of Nostradamus |publisher=Perigee Books (a division of Putnam Pub. Group) |isbn=0399511210 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/furtherprophecie00chee/page/76 }}\n* {{cite EB1911 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Antenor (mythology)|display=Antenor |volume=2 |ref={{harvid|EB|1911}} |pages=92\u201393 }}\n*{{citation |last=Lempri\u00e8re |first=John |authorlink=John Lempri\u00e8re |chapter=Ant\u0113nor |title=[[Bibliotheca Classica|A Classical Dictionary: Containing a Copious Account of All Proper Names Mentioned in Ancient Authors, with the Value of Coins, Weights, and Measures Used Among the Greeks and Romans, and a Chronological Table]] |year=1822|publisher=J. Crissy|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=udw7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PR86 86]}}\n* {{citation |last=Parada  |first=Carlos |last2=F\u00f6rlag|first2=Maicar  |year=1997 \n|publisher=Greek Mythology Link (Carlos Parada) |url=http://www.maicar.com/GML/Antenor1.html |title=Antenor |accessdate=8 January 2017}}.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2017}}\n*{{citation  |l