y_id&id=fVhlXw%3D%3D|title=\u00c0nt\u016bn|quote=\u00c1nte|website=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hjp.znanje.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=f1tgXRU%3D&keyword=%C4%8Caslav|title=\u010c\u00e0slav|quote=\u010c\u0201\u010di\u0107|website=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal|accessdate=2018-03-17|language=sh}}</ref> born 29 September 1953) is a Croatian professional [[association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]] who is the current manager of [[Pyramids FC]].\n\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 graduated on the Faculty of Physical Education at the [[University of Zagreb]]. He was one of the first ten football coaches in Croatia to get the [[UEFA Pro Licence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.24sata.hr/sport/tko-je-ante-cacic-trener-koji-vec-odudara-od-ostatka-hnl-a-247265|title=Tko je Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107? Trener koji ve\u0107 odudara od ostatka HNL-a|date=23 December 2011|language=hr|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nDuring his career, he successfully achieved promotion to the top division with [[NK Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107|Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107]] and [[NK Dubrava|Dubrava]]. He also coached [[NK Zadar|Zadar]], [[NK Osijek|Osijek]], [[NK Slaven Belupo|Slaven Belupo]], [[NK Kamen Ingrad|Kamen Ingrad]], [[NK Croatia Sesvete|Croatia Sesvete]] and [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]].<ref name=\"jutarnji\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/novi-strateg-modrih--covjek-koji-je-hajduku-donio-dva-prvenstva-/995519/ |title=Novi strateg Modrih: \u010covjek koji je Hajduku donio dva prvenstva! |last=Lipovac |first=Nikola |date=23 December 2011 |work=Jutarnji.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107 (2002\u20132003) ===\nIn the [[2002\u201303 Druga HNL|2002\u201303 season]], \u010ca\u010di\u0107 was at the helm of [[NK Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107|Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107]] in the South Division in the [[Druga HNL]]. In March 2003, he resigned after losing to the first-placed team [[NK Istra 1961|Uljanik]], leaving Inter at the second place in the table and five points behind the leaders. He was replaced with [[Ilija Lon\u010darevi\u0107]], who achieved promotion to Prva HNL.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/202641/nogomet/cacic-otisao-uskace-loncarevic |title=\u010c\u010d\u0107 oti\u0161ao, \"uska\u010de\" Lon\u010darevi\u0107 |last=Puri\u0107 |first=Bojan |date=11 March 2003 |work=Sportnet.hr  | language = Croatian | accessdate = 24 December 2011 }}</ref> \n\n=== Libya (2005\u20132006) ===\nWhen Lon\u010darevi\u0107 was appointed as the manager of [[Libya national football team]], he named \u010ca\u010di\u0107 as his assistant. During his time at Libya, he was chosen to lead their under-20 squad at the [[Football at the 2005 Mediterranean Games|2005 Mediterranean Games]] held in Spain. After losing to the hosts in the semi-finals, they won the bronze medal after defeating Morocco in the penalty shoot-out.<ref name=\"mediterraneangames\">{{cite news |title=Le bronze \u00e0 La Libye aux Jeux m\u00e9diterran\u00e9ens en football |url=http://www.panapress.com/Le-bronze-a-La-Libye-aux-Jeux-mediterraneens-en-football--13-619776-17-lang1-index.html |website=[[PanaPress]] |date=11 July 2005 |accessdate=12 June 2016 |language=French}}</ref>\n\n=== Kamen Ingrad (2006\u20132007) ===\nIn June 2006, \u010ca\u010di\u0107 returned to Croatia and was appointed as manager of [[NK Kamen Ingrad|Kamen Ingrad]], but after only three months he terminated his contract.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/310514/nogomet/cacic-preuzeo-kamen-ingrad |title=\u010c\u010d\u0107 preuzeo Kamen Ingrad |last=Zdelar |first=Zoran |date=26 June 2006 |work=Sportnet.hr | language = Croatian | accessdate = 24 December 2011 }}</ref>\n\n=== Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107 (2007) ===\nIn October 2006, he again took over the helm of [[NK Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107|Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107]] after they sacked [[Sre\u0107ko Bogdan]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/319968/nogomet-hnl/inter-opet-smijenio-srecka-bogdana |title=Inter opet smijenio Sre\u0107ka Bogdana |last=Tomi\u010di\u0107 |first=Goran |date=23 October 2006 |work=Sportnet.hr | language = Croatian |accessdate=24 December 2011 }}</ref> \u010ca\u010di\u0107 led Inter to the first place in the [[2006\u201307 Druga HNL]] and the team was promoted to Prva HNL. After a disappointing start in the following season, he was sacked in August 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/348575/nogomet-hnl/cacic-smijenjen-bracun-pred-vratima |title=\u010ca\u010di\u0107 smijenjen, Bra\u010dun pred vratima |last=Le\u0161kovi\u0107 | first=Mario | last2 = Hohnjec |first2=Kristian |date=18 August 2007 |work=Sportnet.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Lokomotiva (2011) ===\nIn October 2011, \u010ca\u010di\u0107 was appointed as manager of [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/427812/nogomet-1-hnl/potvrdjen-novi-trener-lokomotive |title=Potvr\u0111en novi trener Lokomotive |last=\u0160trbini\u0107 |first=Lovro |date=31 October 2011 | work = Sportnet.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref> They finished in the sixth place at the winter break, undefeated in four games led by \u010ca\u010di\u0107.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/430040/nogomet-1-hnl/cacic-veliki-poticaj-za-lokomotivu |title=\u010ca\u010di\u0107: Veliki poticaj za Lokomotivu |last=Rupnik |first=Borna |date=5 December 2011 |work=Sportnet.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Dinamo Zagreb (2011\u20132012) ===\nOn 23 December 2011, it was announced that \u010ca\u010di\u0107 had signed a one-and-a-half-year contract with [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/431170/nogomet-1-hnl/ante-cacic-preuzima-dinamo |title=Amte \u010c\u010d\u0107 preuzima Dinamo |date=23 December 2011 |work=Sportnet.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=24 December 2011}}</ref> He was sacked from Dinamo in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=\u0160nidari\u0107|first=Marko|title=Mami\u0107 smijenio \u010ca\u010di\u0107a! Kruno Jur\u010di\u0107 je opet na klupi Dinama|url=http://www.24sata.hr/nogomet/treci-put-kruno-jurcic-novi-je-trener-dinama-sluzbena-vijest-291102|publisher=24sata.hr|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> \n\n=== Radnik Sesvete (2013) ===\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 was without assignment until April 2013 when he took over as a manager of [[NK Radnik Sesvete|Radnik Sesvete]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Guberina|first=Kazimir|title=Amte \u010c\u010d\u0107 novi trener Radnika Sesvete|url=http://www.sportnews-hr.info/2-hnl/seniori/vijesti/1336-ante-cacic-novi-trener-radnika-sesvete.html|publisher=SportNews|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> \n\n=== Maribor (2013) ===\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 left Radnik Sesvete in early June 2013, when he accepted an offer from [[List of Slovenian football champions|Slovenian champions]] [[NK Maribor|Maribor]].<ref name=\"milanic_cacic\">{{cite news | url = http://www.siol.net/sportal/nogomet/slovenija/novice/2013/06/novi_trener_maribora.aspx | title = \u010ca\u010di\u0107: Ponosen sem, ker sem v Mariboru | trans-title = Cacic: I am proud to be in Maribor | date = 5 June 2013 | author = Dario Dotto | publisher = [[Siol]] official website | language = sl | accessdate = 28 June 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160204030858/http://www.siol.net/sportal/nogomet/slovenija/novice/2013/06/novi_trener_maribora.aspx | archive-date = 4 February 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Slaven Belupo (2014\u20132015) ===\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 became manager of [[NK Slaven Belupo|Slaven Belupo]] on 4 November 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.narodni-list.hr/posts/60495001|title=Prva HNL: Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 novi trener Slaven Belupa|work=Narodni List|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> and the club finished 6th in his only season at the club.\n\n=== Lokomotiva (2015) ===\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 became manager of [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]] on 3 June 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://prigorski.hr/ante-cacic-novi-trener-nk-lokomotive/|title=Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 novi trener NK Lokomotive - Prigorski.hr|website=prigorski.hr|language=hr|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> and was with the club for only 3 months before being selected as head coach of the [[Croatia national football team|Croatia national team]].\n\n=== Croatia (2015\u20132017) ===\n\n==== Euro 2016: Qualifying and finals ====\nFollowing the sacking of [[Niko Kova\u010d]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/sport/niko-kovac-dobio-otkaz-suker-otkrio-tko-ce-birati-izbornika-ovo-si-vise-ne-smijemo-dozvoliti/298798/|title=NIKO KOVA\u010c DOBIO OTKAZ, \u0160UKER OTKRIO TKO \u0106E BIRATI IZBORNIKA 'Ovo si vi\u0161e ne smijemo dozvoliti!'|work=jutarnji.hr|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en}}</ref> which was caused due to a poor run in the [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying|Euro 2016 qualifying]], Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 was appointed as the head coach of the [[Croatia national football team|Croatia national team]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gol.dnevnik.hr/clanak/nogomet/ceka-se-potvrda-ono-cega-smo-se-svi-bojali-cacic-postaje-izbornik-hrvatske---409401.html|title=Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 novi izbornik, a pomo\u0107nik mu je Joe \u0160imuni\u0107! - 'Do sada smo svaki put pogodili'|work=Gol.hr|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr-HR}}</ref> His appointment was very controversial and left fans of the national team in shock<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnevno.hr/sport/nogomet/ceka-se-objava-ante-cacic-novi-je-izbornik-hrvatske-reprezentacije-832570/|title=NAVIJA\u010cI U \u0160OKU: Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 novi je izbornik hrvatske reprezentacije! {{!}} Dnevno.hr|date=2015-09-21|work=Dnevno.hr|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr-HR}}</ref>. Croatia finished 2nd in their qualifying group, securing a place in the group stages of [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]. Croatia enjoyed a memorable [[UEFA Euro 2016#Group D|group stage]] run, topping their group after beating [[UEFA Euro 2012|European champions]] [[Spain national football team|Spain]] by a scoreline of 2\u20131 on 21 June 2016<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3653101/Croatia-2-1-Spain-Ivan-Perisic-sends-Croatia-Group-D-consigns-Spain-clash-Italy-Euro-2016-16.html|title=Croatia 2-1 Spain: Ivan Perisic sends Croatia to the top of Group D|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>, despite key-player [[Luka Modri\u0107]] not playing due to injury problems.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hr.n1info.com/a131331/Sport-Klub/Nogomet/Luka-Modric-gotovo-sigurno-nece-igrati-protiv-Spanjolske.html|title=Luka Modri\u0107 gotovo sigurno ne\u0107e igrati protiv \u0160panjolske!|work=N1 HR|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr}}</ref> However, Croatia fans had earlier sparked controversy during a match against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]], which finished 2\u20132, when [[Flare|flares]] were lit at the near end of the match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36496116|title=Czech Republic 2-2 Croatia|date=2016-06-17|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-GB}}</ref> After beating Spain, Croatia were tipped as one of the favorites to win the tournament<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jun/21/croatia-spain-euro-2016-match-report|title=Ivan Perisic stunner for Croatia leaves Spain to face Italy in last 16|last=Lowe|first=Sid|date=2016-06-21|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>, but they were knocked out by [[UEFA Euro 2016 Final|future winners]] [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2016 knockout phase|round of sixteen]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2016/matches/round=2000744/match=2017998/index.html|title=UEFA EURO 2016 - History - Croatia-Portugal \u2013 UEFA.com|last=uefa.com|date=2016-06-25|work=Uefa.com|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 was voted as the 7th Best National Team Coach by the [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://iffhs.de/the-worlds-best-national-coach-2016-fernando-santos/|title=THE WORLD'S BEST NATIONAL COACH 2016 : Fernando Santos {{!}} IFFHS|date=2016-12-27|work=IFFHS|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== FIFA World Cup 2018: Qualifying and sacking ====\n\u010ca\u010di\u0107 took Croatia to a strong start in [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group I|their qualifying campaign]], with Croatia leading their group and remaining undefeated. However, defeats to [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] and [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sportske.jutarnji.hr/nogomet/reprezentacija/video-maksimir-u-euforiji-hrvatska-slavi-veliku-pobjedu-kalinic-spektakularnim-golom-vodi-vatrene-na-sp-navijaci-opet-najbolji-na-svijetu/5807551/|title=VIDEO: MAKSIMIR U EUFORIJI, HRVATSKA SLAVI VELIKU POBJEDU Kalini\u0107 spektakularnim golom vodi Vatrene na SP, navija\u010di opet najbolji na svijetu!|work=sportske.jutarnji.hr|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/sport/hrvatska-bez-cetvorice-standardnih-po-pobjedu-protiv-islanda-1175934|title=Island \u0161okirao Hrvatsku golom u 90. minuti! Prvi poraz na\u0161ih u kvalifikacijama|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nacional.hr/sp-2018-kvalifikacije-turska-hrvatska-1-0/|title=SP 2018. KVALIFIKACIJE Turska \u2013 Hrvatska 1-0 {{!}} NACIONAL.HR|website=www.nacional.hr|language=hr|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> as well as a draw to [[Finland national football team|Finland]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.hrt.hr/408913/htv-1-2045-imperativ-pobjede-protiv-finske-uoci-puta-u-kijev|title=[VIDEO] \u0160ok na Rujevici: Finska uzela bod protiv Hrvatske|work=Hrvatska radiotelevizija|access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> threatened their progression and caused a public outcry against \u010ca\u010di\u0107, who was criticized for his poor team selection, decreasing player morale and losing support from players and fans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.index.hr/sport/clanak/modric-konacno-progovorio-o-rasulu-ne-znam-je-li-cacic-izbornik-za-hrvatsku-ali-sto-da-sad-radimo/999288.aspx|title=MODRI\u0106 KONA\u010cNO PROGOVORIO O RASULU \"Ne znam je li \u010ca\u010di\u0107 izbornik za Hrvatsku\"|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr}}</ref> \u010ca\u010di\u0107 was also criticized by former Croatia head coach [[Miroslav Bla\u017eevi\u0107]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sport.avaz.ba/nogomet/321335/rat-u-hrvatskoj-ciro-bez-ustezanja-kritizirao-cacica-bivsi-selektor-udario-po-njemu-i-subasicu|title=\"Rat\" u Hrvatskoj: \u0106iro bez ustezanja kritizirao \u010ca\u010di\u0107a, biv\u0161i selektor udario po njemu i Suba\u0161i\u0107u|work=Avaz.ba|access-date=2018-06-02|language=bs-BA}}</ref> \n\nHe was sacked on 7 October 2017, with [[Zlatko Dali\u0107]] being named as his successor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.index.hr/sport/clanak/cacic-dobio-otkaz-hrvatska-trazi-novog-izbornika/999303.aspx|title=\u010cA\u010cI\u0106 DOBIO OTKAZ! Hrvatska tra\u017ei novog izbornika|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/sport/zlatko-dalic-novi-je-izbornik-vodi-hrvatsku-vec-protiv-ukrajine-1199449|title=\u010ca\u010di\u0107 smijenjen, Zlatko Dali\u0107 novi je izbornik!|access-date=2018-06-02|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n=== Pyramids FC (2019\u2013present) ===\nOn 27 December 2019, he was named the new manager of Egyptian club [[Pyramids FC]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 ima novi anga\u017eman, biv\u0161i izbornik preuzeo egipatski Pyramids |url=https://sportnet.rtl.hr/vijesti/532960/nogomet-nogometni-svijet/ante-cacic-ima-novi-angazman-bivsi-izbornik-preuzeo-egipatski-pyramids/ |website=sportnet.rtl.hr |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{Updated|8 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n|-\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\n|-\n|[[NK Maribor|Maribor]]\n| 5 June 2013\n| 29 September 2013\n{{WDL|18|8|5|5|for=30|against=18|diff=yes}}\n|-\n|[[NK Slaven Belupo|Slaven Belupo]]\n| 4 November 2014\n| 30 May 2015\n{{WDL|22|9|5|8|for=30|against=25|diff=yes}}\n|-\n|[[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]]\n| 3 June 2015\n| 21 September 2015\n{{WDL|14|6|2|6|for=23|against=27|diff=yes}}\n|-\n|[[Croatia national football team|Croatia]]\n| 22 September 2015\n| 7 October 2017\n{{WDL|26|16|6|4|for=48|against=16|diff=yes}}\n|-\n|[[Pyramids FC]]\n| 26 December 2019\n| Present\n{{WDL|14|9|1|4|for=17|against=7|diff=yes}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| Total\n{{WDLtot|94|48|19|27|for=147|against=95|diff=yes}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n=== Manager ===\n\n==== Zadar ====\n\n*Yugoslavian Third Football League: 1990\u201391{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n==== Dubrava ====\n\n*[[Croatian Second Football League]]: 1992\u201393{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n==== Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107 ====\n\n*Croatian Second Football League: [[2002\u201303 Croatian Second Football League|2002\u201303]]{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n==== Dinamo Zagreb ====\n\n*[[Croatian First Football League]]: [[2011\u201312 Croatian First Football League|2011\u201312]]{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n*[[Croatian Football Cup]]: [[2011\u201312 Croatian Football Cup|2011\u201312]]{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n==== Maribor ====\n\n*[[Slovenian Supercup]]: [[2013 Slovenian Supercup|2013]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Matej |last=Leskov\u0161ek |title=Superpokal Maribor\u010danom, v Celju pometli z Olimpijo |url=http://siol.net/sportal/nogomet/superpokal-mariborcanom-v-celju-pometli-z-olimpijo-5385 |website=[[Siol]] |date=6 July 2013 |accessdate=12 June 2016 |language=sl}}</ref>\n\n==== Libya U20 ====\n\n*[[Mediterranean Games]]: [[Football at the 2005 Mediterranean Games|2005]] (bronze medal)<ref name=\"mediterraneangames\"/>\n\n=== Individual ===\n\n* 2016: 7th Best National Team Coach, voted by [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/ante-cacic_prs320278/person.shtml Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107] on [[Eurosport#British Eurosport|British Eurosport]]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Ante \u010ca\u010di\u0107 managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{NK Zadar managers}}\n{{NK Osijek managers}}\n{{NK Slaven Belupo managers}}\n{{NK Lokomotiva managers}}\n{{GNK Dinamo Zagreb managers}}\n{{NK Maribor managers}}\n{{Croatia national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{Croatia squad UEFA Euro 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cacic, Ante}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:N HA\u0160K managers]]\n[[Category:NK Zadar managers]]\n[[Category:NK Osijek managers]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb managers]]\n[[Category:Croatian football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:NK Maribor managers]]\n[[Category:NK Inter Zapre\u0161i\u0107 managers]]\n[[Category:NK Slaven Belupo managers]]\n[[Category:NK Lokomotiva managers]]\n[[Category:Croatia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 managers]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ante_%C4%8Ca%C4%8Di%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Antarah ibn Shaddad", "text_new": "{{Infobox philosopher\n|  region          = [[Uyun AlJiwa|Al Jiwa]], [[Ancient Arabia]], [[Arab world]]\n|  era             = [[Pre-Islamic Arabia]]\n| name        = Antarah ibn Shaddad <br>{{lang|ar|\u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0627\u062f}}\n| fullname        =\u02bfAntarah ibn Shadd\u0101d al-\u02bfAbs\u012b<br>{{lang|ar|\u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u0633\u064a}}\n| image       = File:Antarah on horse.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 525 AD\n| birth_place = Qusaiba [[Al-Qassim Region]], [[Ancient Arabia]] <br/>{{smaller|(present-day [[Saudi Arabia]])}}\n| death_date  = 608 AD (aged 83)\n| death_place = \n| main_interests   =  [[Arabic poetry]]\n| influences  =  \n| influenced  =  [[Saleh]], [[Muhammad Mahdi al-Jawahiri]], [[Abd al-Wahhab Al-Bayati]], [[Mohammed Ridha Al-Shabibi]]\n}}\n'''Antarah ibn Shaddad al-Absi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u0633\u064a}}, ''\u02bfAntarah ibn Shadd\u0101d al-\u02bfAbs\u012b''; {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;525\u2013608), also known as '''\u02bfAntar''', was a [[pre-Islamic Arabia|pre-Islamic]] Arab knight and poet, famous for both his poetry and his adventurous life.  His chief poem forms part of the ''[[Mu'allaqat|Mu'allaq\u0101t]]'', the collection of seven \"hanging odes\" legendarily said to have been suspended in the [[Kaaba]]. The account of his life forms the basis of a long and extravagant romance.\n\n{{anchor|Biography|History}}\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Antarah ibn Shaddad & Abla.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Antarah and Abla depicted on a 19th-century Egyptian tattooing pattern.]]\n[[File:\u0635\u062e\u0631\u0629 \u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629.jpg|200px|right|thumb|A recent photo of what is said to be the famous Rock where Antarah used to meet Abla. Taken in [[Uyun AlJiwa Governorate|al Jiwa]], [[Saudi Arabia]]]]\n\u02bfAntarah was born in [[Najd]] in [[Arabia]]. His father was Shadd\u0101d al-\u02bfAbs\u012b, a respected warrior of the [[Banu Abs]] under their chief Zuhayr.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} His mother was an [[People of Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] woman named Zabeebah.{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} She was a princess taken as a captive by his father as a [[slavery in the Middle East|slave]] during one of the tribe's raids against [[Kingdom of Axum|Axum]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}  Described as an \"Arab crow\" (''al-aghribah al-'Arab'') owing to his dark complexion,{{sfn|Lewis|1992|p=28}}\u02bfAntarah grew up a slave as well. He fell in love with his cousin \u02bfAblah, but could not hope to marry her owing to his position.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} He also gained the enmity of his father's wife Shammeah.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}\n\nHe gained attention and respect for himself by his remarkable personal qualities and courage in battle, excelling as an accomplished poet and a mighty warrior. He earned his freedom after another tribe invaded the lands of the Banu \u02bfAbs. When his father said to him, \"\u02bfAntarah, fight with the warriors\", he replied that \"the slave doesn't know how to invade or how to defend, but is only good for milking goats and serving his masters\". His father answered him: \"Defend your tribe, O \u02bfAntar, and you are free\". After defeating the invaders, he sought to gain permission to [[cousin marriage|marry his cousin]]. To secure allowance to marry, Antarah had to face challenges including getting a special kind of camel from the northern Arab kingdom of the [[Lakhmids]], then under [[Al-Nu'man III ibn al-Mundhir]]. \u02bfAntarah took part in the great war between the related tribes of \u02bfAbs and Dhuby\u0101n,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} which began over a contest of horses, and was named after them the war of D\u0101his and Ghabr\u0101.\n\nThe time and manner of his death are a matter of dispute. Ibn Doreid has him slain by Wasr-ben-Jaber{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} or in battle against the Tai,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}, while according to Abu Obeida he died a natural death in old age.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}\n\n\u02bfAntarah's poetry is well preserved and often talks of [[chivalry|chivalrous]] values, courage and heroism in battle as well as his love for \u02bfAbla. It was immortalized when one of his poems was included in the [[Mu'allaqat]], the collection of poems legendarily said to have been suspended in the [[Kaaba]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}  His poetry's historical and cultural importance stems from its detailed descriptions of battles, armour, weapons, horses, desert and other themes from his time.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Antarah bin shadad old manuscript.jpg|200px|left|thumb|A painting on glass of Antara ibn Shaddad.]]\n\nThe story of \u02bfAntar and \u02bfAbla was embroidered into a poetic saga traditionally credited to [[al-Asma\u02bfi]], a poet in the court of [[H\u0101r\u016bn al-Rash\u012bd]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} It is still recited by traditional story-tellers in Arab coffee houses. Its importance has been compared with [[English literature]]'s [[Arthurian romance]]s.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} His house and his stable were particularly legendary.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} One of the seven clans of [[Bethlehem]] is called the ''Anatreh'', named after  \u02bfAntarah. It formerly acted as the guardians of the [[Church of the Nativity]].\n\nThe Russian composer [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] wrote his Symphony No. 2 based on the legend of \u02bfAntar. In 1898 the French painter [[\u00c9tienne Dinet]] published<ref name=\"Pouillon\">Pouillon, Francois (1997), ''Les deux vies d'\u00c9tienne Dinet, peintre en Islam: L'Algerie et l'heritage colonial'', Paris: Editions Balland.</ref> his translation of a 13th-century epic Arab poem ''Antar'', which brought Antar bin Shaddad to European notice.<ref name=\"Pouillon\"/>  It has been followed by a number of [[derivative work]]s such as Diana Richmond's ''Antar and Abla''<ref>Richmond, Diana (1978), ''Antar and Abla: a Bedouin romance'', London: Quartet Books, {{ISBN|0-7043-2162-9}}.</ref> which furthered [[Western world|western]] exposure to the Antar bin Shaddad legends. \"Antar\" is the title of the first Palestinian opera, composed by the Palestinian musician Mustapha al-Kurd in 1988.\n\nLebanese painter [[Rafic Charaf]] developed from the 1960s a series of paintings depicting the epics of Antar and Abla. These works that show interest on popular the region are considered as a keystone in the artist's oeuvre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mokbelartcollection.com/rcartist.htm |title= Rafic Charaf |author= |year=2011 |work= |publisher=The Mokbel Art Collection |accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nAntara's poems are published in [[Wilhelm Ahlwardt]]'s ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001338280 The Divans of the six ancient Arabic poets]'' (London, 1870); they have also been published separately at Beir\u00fbt (1888). As regards their genuineness, cf. W. Ahlwardt's ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001337984 Bemerkungen \u00fcber die Aechtheit der alten arabischen Gedichte]'' (Greifswald, 1872), pp.&nbsp;50ff.  ''The Romance of 'Antar'' (S\u012brat 'Antar ibn Shadd\u0101d) is a work which was long handed down by oral tradition only, has grown to immense proportions and has been published in 32 vols. at Cairo, 1307 (A.D. 1889), and in 10 vols. at Beir\u00fbt, 1871. It was partly translated by [[Terrick Hamilton]] under the title '' '[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001854443 Antar, a Bedoueen Romance]'' (4 vols, London, 1820).{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} In addition,  S\u012brat 'Antar was translated into Turkish by order of Fatih Sultan Mehmed in 1477.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u0130kb\u00e2l G\u00dcLER|first=Muhammed|date=2020-01-01|title=KISSA-\u0130 ANTER: TOPKAPI SARAYI M\u00dcZES\u0130 K\u00dcT\u00dcPHANES\u0130'NDEK\u0130 EL YAZMASI N\u00dcSHALARIN TANITIMI VE DE\u011eERLEND\u0130R\u0130LMES\u0130|url=http://www.tekedergisi.com/DergiTamDetay.aspx?ID=4620|journal=International Journal Of Turkish Literature Culture Education|language=en|volume=9|issue=9/1|pages=48\u201379|doi=10.7884/teke.4620|issn=2147-0146}}</ref> The translator of the Turkish translation in three volumes is unknown. The manuscript copies of the Turkish translation known as \"[http://www.tekedergisi.com/DergiTamDetay.aspx?ID=4620&Detay=Ozet Q\u0131ssa-i 'Antar]\" are available in the Topkap\u0131 Palace Museum Library.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arabic literature]] & [[Arabic romance literature|romance literature]]\n* [[Banu Abs]]\n* [[Thornycroft Antar]] - British pipeline tractor named after his strength and endurance\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Antara |volume=2  |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |page=100 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Bernard |year=1992 |title=Race and Slavery in the Middle East: An Historical Enquiry |page=[https://archive.org/details/raceslaveryinmid0000lewi/page/ <!-- quote=crows. --> 28] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-505326-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/raceslaveryinmid0000lewi/page/ }}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n* {{EB1911 |mode=cs2 |last=Thatcher |first=Griffithes Wheeler |wstitle='Antara ibn Shadd\u0101d |volume=2 |ref={{harvid|EB|1911}} |pages=88\u201389 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Antarah ibn Shaddad}}\n*[http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/hanged/hanged2.htm English translation of Antara's Hanged Poem]\n*[http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/source/640hangedpoems.html another link to the same]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040416161130/http://www.khayma.com/salehzayadneh/moalaqat/antarah.htm The Hanged Poem of Antara (Arabic)]\n*[http://adab.com/modules.php?name=Sh3er&doWhat=shqas&qid=10745 The Hanged Poem of Antara \"another version\" (Arabic)]\n*[http://www.cwo.com/~lucumi/antara.html Antara the Lion: Father of Heroes]\n*[http://elfinspell.com/Masterpieces1Antar.html Antar of Antarah, translated by Terrick Hamilton]\n*[https://www.scribd.com/doc/240432779/Abla-and-Antarah-Ibn-Shaddad-erotic-poetry Abla's laments for Antarah Ibn Shadd\u0101d al-'Abs\u012b]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antarah, Ibn Shaddad}}\n[[Category:6th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Pre-Islamic Arabian poets]]\n[[Category:Arab poets]]\n[[Category:Arab people of Ethiopian descent]]\n[[Category:Medieval Arabic literature]]\n[[Category:Love in Arabic literature]]\n[[Category:525 births]]\n[[Category:608 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ghatafan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox philosopher\n|  region          = [[Uyun AlJiwa|Al Jiwa]], [[Ancient Arabia]], [[Arab world]]\n|  era             = [[Pre-Islamic Arabia]]\n| name        = Antarah ibn Shaddad <br>{{lang|ar|\u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0627\u062f}}\n| fullname        =\u02bfAntarah ibn Shadd\u0101d al-\u02bfAbs\u012b<br>{{lang|ar|\u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u0633\u064a}}\n| image       = File:Antarah on horse.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 525 AD\n| birth_place = Qusaiba [[Al-Qassim Region]], [[Ancient Arabia]] <br/>{{smaller|(present-day [[Saudi Arabia]])}}\n| death_date  = 608 AD (aged 83)\n| death_place = \n| main_interests   =  [[Arabic poetry]]\n| influences  =  \n| influenced  =  [[Saleh]], [[Muhammad Mahdi al-Jawahiri]], [[Abd al-Wahhab Al-Bayati]], [[Mohammed Ridha Al-Shabibi]]\n}}\n'''Antarah ibn Shaddad al-Absi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u0633\u064a}}, ''\u02bfAntarah ibn Shadd\u0101d al-\u02bfAbs\u012b''; {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;525\u2013608), also known as '''\u02bfAntar''', was a [[pre-Islamic Arabia|pre-Islamic]] Arab knight and poet, famous for both his poetry and his adventurous life.  His chief poem forms part of the ''[[Mu'allaqat|Mu'allaq\u0101t]]'', the collection of seven \"hanging odes\" legendarily said to have been suspended in the [[Kaaba]]. The account of his life forms the basis of a long and extravagant romance.\n\n{{anchor|Biography|History}}\n\n==Life==\n[[File:Antarah ibn Shaddad & Abla.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Antarah and Abla depicted on a 19th-century Egyptian tattooing pattern.]]\n[[File:\u0635\u062e\u0631\u0629 \u0639\u0646\u062a\u0631\u0629.jpg|200px|right|thumb|A recent photo of what is said to be the famous Rock where Antarah used to meet Abla. Taken in [[Uyun AlJiwa Governorate|al Jiwa]], [[Saudi Arabia]]]]\n\u02bfAntarah was born in [[Najd]] in [[Arabia]]. His father was Shadd\u0101d al-\u02bfAbs\u012b, a respected warrior of the [[Banu Abs]] under their chief Zuhayr.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} His mother was an [[People of Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] woman named Zabeebah.{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} She was a princess taken as a captive by his father as a [[slavery in the Middle East|slave]] during one of the tribe's raids against [[Kingdom of Axum|Axum]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}  Described as an \"Arab crow\" (''al-aghribah al-'Arab'') owing to his dark complexion,{{sfn|Lewis|1992|p=28}}\u02bfAntarah grew up a slave as well. He fell in love with his cousin \u02bfAblah, but could not hope to marry her owing to his position.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} He also gained the enmity of his father's wife Shammeah.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}\n\nHe gained attention and respect for himself by his remarkable personal qualities and courage in battle, excelling as an accomplished poet and a mighty warrior. He earned his freedom after another tribe invaded the lands of the Banu \u02bfAbs. When his father said to him, \"\u02bfAntarah, fight with the warriors\", he replied that \"the slave doesn't know how to invade or how to defend, but is only good for milking goats and serving his masters\". His father answered him: \"Defend your tribe, O \u02bfAntar, and you are free\". After defeating the invaders, he sought to gain permission to [[cousin marriage|marry his cousin]]. To secure allowance to marry, Antarah had to face challenges including getting a special kind of camel from the northern Arab kingdom of the [[Lakhmids]], then under [[Al-Nu'man III ibn al-Mundhir]]. \u02bfAntarah took part in the great war between the related tribes of \u02bfAbs and Dhuby\u0101n,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} which began over a contest of horses, and was named after them the war of D\u0101his and Ghabr\u0101.\n\nThe time and manner of his death are a matter of dispute. Ibn Doreid has him slain by Wasr-ben-Jaber{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} or in battle against the Tai,{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}}, while according to Abu Obeida he died a natural death in old age.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}\n\n\u02bfAntarah's poetry is well preserved and often talks of [[chivalry|chivalrous]] values, courage and heroism in battle as well as his love for \u02bfAbla. It was immortalized when one of his poems was included in the [[Mu'allaqat]], the collection of poems legendarily said to have been suspended in the [[Kaaba]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}}  His poetry's historical and cultural importance stems from its detailed descriptions of battles, armour, weapons, horses, desert and other themes from his time.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Antarah bin shadad old manuscript.jpg|200px|left|thumb|A painting on glass of Antara ibn Shaddad.]]\n\nThe story of \u02bfAntar and \u02bfAbla was embroidered into a poetic saga traditionally credited to [[al-Asma\u02bfi]], a poet in the court of [[H\u0101r\u016bn al-Rash\u012bd]].{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} It is still recited by traditional story-tellers in Arab coffee houses. Its importance has been compared with [[English literature]]'s [[Arthurian romance]]s.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} His house and his stable were particularly legendary.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} One of the seven clans of [[Bethlehem]] is called the ''Anatreh'', named after  \u02bfAntarah. It formerly acted as the guardians of the [[Church of the Nativity]].\n\nThe Russian composer [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] wrote his Symphony No. 2 based on the legend of \u02bfAntar. In 1898 the French painter [[\u00c9tienne Dinet]] published<ref name=\"Pouillon\">Pouillon, Francois (1997), ''Les deux vies d'\u00c9tienne Dinet, peintre en Islam: L'Algerie et l'heritage colonial'', Paris: Editions Balland.</ref> his translation of a 13th-century epic Arab poem ''Antar'', which brought Antar bin Shaddad to European notice.<ref name=\"Pouillon\"/>  It has been followed by a number of [[derivative work]]s such as Diana Richmond's ''Antar and Abla''<ref>Richmond, Diana (1978), ''Antar and Abla: a Bedouin romance'', London: Quartet Books, {{ISBN|0-7043-2162-9}}.</ref> which furthered [[Western world|western]] exposure to the Antar bin Shaddad legends. \"Antar\" is the title of the first Palestinian opera, composed by the Palestinian musician Mustapha al-Kurd in 1988.\n\nLebanese painter [[Rafic Charaf]] developed from the 1960s a series of paintings depicting the epics of Antar and Abla. These works that show interest on popular the region are considered as a keystone in the artist's oeuvre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mokbelartcollection.com/rcartist.htm |title= Rafic Charaf |author= |year=2011 |work= |publisher=The Mokbel Art Collection |accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nAntara's poems are published in [[Wilhelm Ahlwardt]]'s ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001338280 The Divans of the six ancient Arabic poets]'' (London, 1870); they have also been published separately at Beir\u00fbt (1888). As regards their genuineness, cf. W. Ahlwardt's ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001337984 Bemerkungen \u00fcber die Aechtheit der alten arabischen Gedichte]'' (Greifswald, 1872), pp.&nbsp;50ff.  ''The Romance of 'Antar'' (S\u012brat 'Antar ibn Shadd\u0101d) is a work which was long handed down by oral tradition only, has grown to immense proportions and has been published in 32 vols. at Cairo, 1307 (A.D. 1889), and in 10 vols. at Beir\u00fbt, 1871. It was partly translated by [[Terrick Hamilton]] under the title '' '[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001854443 Antar, a Bedoueen Romance]'' (4 vols, London, 1820).{{sfnp|''EB''|1911}} In addition,  S\u012brat 'Antar was translated into Turkish by order of Fatih Sultan Mehmed in 1477<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u0130kb\u00e2l G\u00dcLER|first=Muhammed|date=2020-01-01|title=KISSA-\u0130 ANTER: TOPKAPI SARAYI M\u00dcZES\u0130 K\u00dcT\u00dcPHANES\u0130'NDEK\u0130 EL YAZMASI N\u00dcSHALARIN TANITIMI VE DE\u011eERLEND\u0130R\u0130LMES\u0130|url=http://www.tekedergisi.com/DergiTamDetay.aspx?ID=4620|journal=International Journal Of Turkish Literature Culture Education|language=en|volume=9|issue=9/1|pages=48\u201379|doi=10.7884/teke.4620|issn=2147-0146}}</ref>. The translator of the Turkish translation in three volumes is unknown. The manuscript copies of the Turkish translation known as \"[http://www.tekedergisi.com/DergiTamDetay.aspx?ID=4620&Detay=Ozet Q\u0131ssa-i 'Antar]\" are available in the Topkap\u0131 Palace Museum Library.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arabic literature]] & [[Arabic romance literature|romance literature]]\n* [[Banu Abs]]\n* [[Thornycroft Antar]] - British pipeline tractor named after his strength and endurance\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |mode=cs2 |wstitle=Antara |volume=2  |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |page=100 }}\n*{{cite book |last=Lewis |first=Bernard |year=1992 |title=Race and Slavery in the Middle East: An Historical Enquiry |page=[https://archive.org/details/raceslaveryinmid0000lewi/page/ <!-- quote=crows. --> 28] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-505326-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/raceslaveryinmid0000lewi/page/ }}\n\n'''Attribution'''\n* {{EB1911 |mode=cs2 |last=Thatcher |first=Griffithes Wheeler |wstitle='Antara ibn Shadd\u0101d |volume=2 |ref={{harvid|EB|1911}} |pages=88\u201389 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Antarah ibn Shaddad}}\n*[http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/hanged/hanged2.htm English translation of Antara's Hanged Poem]\n*[http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/source/640hangedpoems.html another link to the same]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040416161130/http://www.khayma.com/salehzayadneh/moalaqat/antarah.htm The Hanged Poem of Antara (Arabic)]\n*[http://adab.com/modules.php?name=Sh3er&doWhat=shqas&qid=10745 The Hanged Poem of Antara \"another version\" (Arabic)]\n*[http://www.cwo.com/~lucumi/antara.html Antara the Lion: Father of Heroes]\n*[http://elfinspell.com/Masterpieces1Antar.html Antar of Antarah, translated by Terrick Hamilton]\n*[https://www.scribd.com/doc/240432779/Abla-and-Antarah-Ibn-Shaddad-erotic-poetry Abla's laments for Antarah Ibn Shadd\u0101d al-'Abs\u012b]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antarah, Ibn Shaddad}}\n[[Category:6th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Pre-Islamic Arabian poets]]\n[[Category:Arab poets]]\n[[Category:Arab people of Ethiopian descent]]\n[[Category:Medieval Arabic literature]]\n[[Category:Love in Arabic literature]]\n[[Category:525 births]]\n[[Category:608 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ghatafan]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antarah_ibn_Shaddad"}
{"title_page": "Antaeus", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} \n{{Infobox mythical creature\n|name              = Antaeus<br/>{{lang|grc|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2}}\n|AKA               = \n|image             = H\u00e9rcules luchando con Anteo, por Zurbar\u00e1n.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = ''Hercules Fighting Antaeus'' (1634), by [[Francisco de Zurbar\u00e1n]]\n|Mythology         = [[Greek mythology|Greek]]\n|Grouping          = [[Legendary creature]]\n|Sub_Grouping      = \n|Parents           = [[Poseidon]] <br/> [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]]\n|Country           = \n|Region            = Africa\n|Habitat           = In the interior desert of Libya.\n|First_Reported    = \n|Last_Reported     = \n|Similar_creatures = \n}}\n\n'''Antaeus''' ({{IPAc-en|\u00e6|n|\u02c8|t|i\u02d0|\u0259|s}}, {{lang-grc-gre|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Anta\u00eeos'', <small>{{abbr|lit.|literally}}</small>&nbsp;\"Opponent\", derived from {{lang|grc|\u1f00\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac\u03c9}}, antao \u2013 I face, I oppose), known to the Berbers as Anti, was a figure in [[Berber mythology|Berber]] and [[Greek mythology]].<ref name=\"trail_odysseus\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=R-wKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151&dq=antaeus+berber&source=bl&ots=ve4NjeMC0X&sig=ACfU3U1qUEUT3AXxUkVZANNwa3ZoELbsrQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqj5evkKvmAhX4wMQBHVU1DfsQ6AEwBnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=antaeus%20berber&f=false|title=A Travel Guide to Homer: On the Trail of Odysseus Through Turkey and the Mediterranean, by John Freely, page 151|work=Google Books|access-date=2019-12-11|language=en}}</ref> In Greek sources, he was the giant son of [[Poseidon]] and [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]], who lived in the interior desert of Libya.<ref>Apollodorus, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+2.5.11 2.5.11]</ref><ref>Hyginus, ''Fabulae'' [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusFabulae1.html#31 31].</ref> His wife was the [[Tinjis|goddess Tinge]], for whom the city of [[Tangier]] in [[Morocco]] was named, and he had a daughter named Alceis or Barce. He was famed for his loss to [[Heracles]] as part of his [[Labours of Hercules|twelve Labours]].\n\n==Mythology==\n[[File:Herakles Antaios Louvre G103.jpg|thumb|left|[[Heracles]] and Antaeus, red-figured [[krater]] by [[Euphronios]], 515\u2013510&nbsp;BC, [[Louvre]] (G 103)]]\n[[File:Herakles erw\u00fcrgt Antaios Mirabellgarten 01.jpg|thumb|Heracles crushing Antaeus by Ottavio Mosto (1690)]]\n\nAntaeus would challenge all passers-by to [[Greek wrestling|wrestling matches]] and remained invincible as long as he remained in contact with his mother, the earth.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} As Greek wrestling, like its [[wrestling|modern equivalent]], typically attempted to force opponents to the ground, he always won, killing his opponents.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} He built a [[Greek temple|temple]] to his father using their [[skull]]s.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} Antaeus fought [[Heracles]] as he was on his way to the [[Garden of Hesperides]] as his [[Labours of Hercules|11th Labour]]. Heracles realized that he could not beat Antaeus by throwing or pinning him. Instead, he held him aloft and then crushed him to death in a [[bear hug]].<ref>Pseudo-Apollodorus, ''[[Bibliotheke]]'' ii. 5.</ref><ref>Hyginus, ''Fabula'' 31.</ref>\n\nThe contest between Heracles and Antaeus was a favored subject in [[Greek sculpture|ancient]]{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} and [[Renaissance sculpture]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5QzQ3W4VjvsC&lpg=PA550&dq=The%20contest%20between%20Heracles%20and%20Antaeus%20Renaissance%20sculpture.&pg=PA550#v=onepage&q=The%20contest%20between%20Heracles%20and%20Antaeus%20Renaissance%20sculpture.&f=false|title=Gardner's Art Through the Ages: V. 2: A Global History|last=Kleiner|first=Fred S.|date=2008-02-01|publisher=Cengage Learning EMEA|isbn=0495410608|location=|pages=550|language=en|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Location in Africa===\nAntaeus is placed in the interior desert of [[ancient Libya|Libya]].<ref>I. Malkin, ''Myth and Territory in the Spartan Mediterranean'', 1994:181-87, giving sources, noted in Robin Lane Fox, ''Travelling Heroes in the Epic Age of Homer'', 2008:182 and note 51.</ref> He was probably incorporated into Greek mythology after the Greek conquest of Libya in the mid-seventh century.<ref name=\"trail_odysseus\"/>\n\nA location for Antaeus somewhere far within the [[Berber world]] might be quite flexible in longitude: when the Roman commander [[Quintus Sertorius]] crossed from Hispania to North Africa, he was told by the residents of [[Tingis]] ([[Tangier]]), far to the west of Libya, that the gigantic remains of Antaeus would be found within a certain [[tumulus]]; digging it open, his men found giant bones; closing the site, Sertorius made propitiatory offerings and \"helped to magnify the tomb's reputation\".<ref>Fox 2008:182, noting [[Plutarch]], ''Sertorius''9.3\u20134.Fox 2008:182</ref> In Book IV of [[Marcus Annaeus Lucanus]]' [[epic poem]] ''[[Pharsalia]]'' (c.&nbsp;AD&nbsp;65-61), the story of [[Heracles]]' victory over Antaeus is told to the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[Gaius Scribonius Curio (praetor 49 BC)|Curio]] by an unnamed Libyan citizen. The learned client king [[Juba II of Numidia]] (died 23&nbsp;BC), husband of the daughter of Antony and Cleopatra, claimed his descent from a liaison of Heracles with Tinga, the consort of Antaeus.<ref>Pliny, ''Natural History'', 5. 2\u20133; [[Strabo]] 17. 3. 8 noted in D.W. Roller, ''The World of Juba II and Kleopatra Selene'', 2003:54 and 154, and by Fox 2008:182.</ref> In his ''Life of Sertorius'' cited above, [[Plutarch]] recounts what he says to be a local myth, according to which Heracles consorted with Tinge after the death of Antaeus and had by her a son [[Sufax|Sophax]], who named a city in North Africa Tingis after his mother. Sophax in his turn was father of Diodorus who conquered many Libyan peoples with his army of [[Olbia]]ns and [[Mycenae]]ans brought to Libya by Heracles.<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''Life of Sertorius'', 9. 4</ref> Moreover, some related that Heracles had a son Palaemon by Iphinoe, the daughter of Antaeus and (presumably) Tinge.<ref>[[Tzetzes]] on [[Lycophron]] 662</ref>\n\n[[Scholia]]sts on [[Pindar]]'s Pythian Ode 9 also recorded a story which made Antaeus king of the city Irassa in Libya, and father of a daughter named either Alceis or Barce. Antaeus promised her hand to the winner of a race, just like [[Danaus]] did to find new husbands for [[Dana\u00efdes|his daughters]]. Alexidamus beat all the other suitors in the race and married the daughter of Antaeus. Three versions of this story, with minor variations, were collected by the scholiasts; one of those versions made Antaeus, king of Irassa, a figure distinct from the Antaeus killed by Heracles, while another one suggested that they were one and the same.<ref>Scholia on Pindar, Pythian Ode 9, 185, referring to [[Pherecydes of Athens|Pherecydes]], [[Pisander of Camirus]] and other unspecified writers</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |wstitle=Ant\u00e6us |volume=2  |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |page=100 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Antaeus |volume=2  |page=88 |short=x}}\n* {{cite NSRW|wstitle=Ant\u00e6us|short=x}}\n* {{cite Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology|title=Antaeus |volume=1 |url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aentry%3Dantaeus-bio-1 |short=x}}\n* [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], ''Apollodorus, The Library, with an English Translation by Sir James George Frazer, F.B.A., F.R.S. in 2 Volumes.'' Cambridge, Massachusetts, Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1921.\n* [[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus, Gaius Julius]], [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusFabulae1.html ''The Myths of Hyginus'']. Edited and translated by Mary A. Grant, Lawrence: University of Kansas Press, 1960.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscatinline|Antaeus}}\n* [http://www.theoi.com/Gigante/GiganteAntaios.html \"ANTAIOS\"], ''The Theoi Project''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Libya in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Greek giants]]\n[[Category:Offspring of Poseidon]]\n[[Category:Offspring of Gaia]]\n[[Category:Mythology of Heracles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} \n{{Infobox mythical creature\n|name              = Antaeus<br/>{{lang|grc|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2}}\n|AKA               = \n|image             = H\u00e9rcules luchando con Anteo, por Zurbar\u00e1n.jpg\n|image_size        = \n|caption           = ''Hercules Fighting Antaeus'' (1634), by [[Francisco de Zurbar\u00e1n]]\n|Mythology         = [[Greek mythology|Greek]]\n|Grouping          = [[Legendary creature]]\n|Sub_Grouping      = \n|Parents           = [[Poseidon]] <br/> [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]]\n|Country           = \n|Region            = Africa\n|Habitat           = In the interior desert of Libya.\n|First_Reported    = \n|Last_Reported     = \n|Similar_creatures = \n}}\n\n'''Antaeus''' ({{IPAc-en|\u00e6|n|\u02c8|t|i\u02d0|\u0259|s}}, {{lang-grc-gre|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Anta\u00eeos'', <small>{{abbr|lit.|literally}}</small>&nbsp;\"Opponent\", derived from {{lang|grc|\u1f00\u03bd\u03c4\u03ac\u03c9}}, antao \u2013 I face, I oppose), known to the Berbers as Anti, was a figure in [[Berber mythology|Berber]] and [[Greek mythology]]<ref name=\"trail_odysseus\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=R-wKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151&dq=antaeus+berber&source=bl&ots=ve4NjeMC0X&sig=ACfU3U1qUEUT3AXxUkVZANNwa3ZoELbsrQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqj5evkKvmAhX4wMQBHVU1DfsQ6AEwBnoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=antaeus%20berber&f=false|title=A Travel Guide to Homer: On the Trail of Odysseus Through Turkey and the Mediterranean, by John Freely, page 151|work=Google Books|access-date=2019-12-11|language=en}}</ref>. In Greek sources, he was the giant son of [[Poseidon]] and [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]], who lived in the interior desert of Libya.<ref>Apollodorus, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+2.5.11 2.5.11]</ref><ref>Hyginus, ''Fabulae'' [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusFabulae1.html#31 31].</ref> His wife was the [[Tinjis|goddess Tinge]], for whom the city of [[Tangier]] in [[Morocco]] was named, and he had a daughter named Alceis or Barce. He was famed for his loss to [[Heracles]] as part of his [[Labours of Hercules|twelve Labours]].\n\n==Mythology==\n[[File:Herakles Antaios Louvre G103.jpg|thumb|left|[[Heracles]] and Antaeus, red-figured [[krater]] by [[Euphronios]], 515\u2013510&nbsp;BC, [[Louvre]] (G 103)]]\n[[File:Herakles erw\u00fcrgt Antaios Mirabellgarten 01.jpg|thumb|Heracles crushing Antaeus by Ottavio Mosto (1690)]]\n\nAntaeus would challenge all passers-by to [[Greek wrestling|wrestling matches]] and remained invincible as long as he remained in contact with his mother, the earth.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} As Greek wrestling, like its [[wrestling|modern equivalent]], typically attempted to force opponents to the ground, he always won, killing his opponents.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} He built a [[Greek temple|temple]] to his father using their [[skull]]s.{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} Antaeus fought [[Heracles]] as he was on his way to the [[Garden of Hesperides]] as his [[Labours of Hercules|11th Labour]]. Heracles realized that he could not beat Antaeus by throwing or pinning him. Instead, he held him aloft and then crushed him to death in a [[bear hug]].<ref>Pseudo-Apollodorus, ''[[Bibliotheke]]'' ii. 5.</ref><ref>Hyginus, ''Fabula'' 31.</ref>\n\nThe contest between Heracles and Antaeus was a favored subject in [[Greek sculpture|ancient]]{{sfnp|''EB''|1878}} and [[Renaissance sculpture]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5QzQ3W4VjvsC&lpg=PA550&dq=The%20contest%20between%20Heracles%20and%20Antaeus%20Renaissance%20sculpture.&pg=PA550#v=onepage&q=The%20contest%20between%20Heracles%20and%20Antaeus%20Renaissance%20sculpture.&f=false|title=Gardner's Art Through the Ages: V. 2: A Global History|last=Kleiner|first=Fred S.|date=2008-02-01|publisher=Cengage Learning EMEA|isbn=0495410608|location=|pages=550|language=en|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Location in Africa===\nAntaeus is placed in the interior desert of [[ancient Libya|Libya]].<ref>I. Malkin, ''Myth and Territory in the Spartan Mediterranean'', 1994:181-87, giving sources, noted in Robin Lane Fox, ''Travelling Heroes in the Epic Age of Homer'', 2008:182 and note 51.</ref> He was probably incorporated into Greek mythology after the Greek conquest of Libya in the mid-seventh century.<ref name=\"trail_odysseus\"/>\n\nA location for Antaeus somewhere far within the [[Berber world]] might be quite flexible in longitude: when the Roman commander [[Quintus Sertorius]] crossed from Hispania to North Africa, he was told by the residents of [[Tingis]] ([[Tangier]]), far to the west of Libya, that the gigantic remains of Antaeus would be found within a certain [[tumulus]]; digging it open, his men found giant bones; closing the site, Sertorius made propitiatory offerings and \"helped to magnify the tomb's reputation\".<ref>Fox 2008:182, noting [[Plutarch]], ''Sertorius''9.3\u20134.Fox 2008:182</ref> In Book IV of [[Marcus Annaeus Lucanus]]' [[epic poem]] ''[[Pharsalia]]'' (c.&nbsp;AD&nbsp;65-61), the story of [[Heracles]]' victory over Antaeus is told to the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[Gaius Scribonius Curio (praetor 49 BC)|Curio]] by an unnamed Libyan citizen. The learned client king [[Juba II of Numidia]] (died 23&nbsp;BC), husband of the daughter of Antony and Cleopatra, claimed his descent from a liaison of Heracles with Tinga, the consort of Antaeus.<ref>Pliny, ''Natural History'', 5. 2\u20133; [[Strabo]] 17. 3. 8 noted in D.W. Roller, ''The World of Juba II and Kleopatra Selene'', 2003:54 and 154, and by Fox 2008:182.</ref> In his ''Life of Sertorius'' cited above, [[Plutarch]] recounts what he says to be a local myth, according to which Heracles consorted with Tinge after the death of Antaeus and had by her a son [[Sufax|Sophax]], who named a city in North Africa Tingis after his mother. Sophax in his turn was father of Diodorus who conquered many Libyan peoples with his army of [[Olbia]]ns and [[Mycenae]]ans brought to Libya by Heracles.<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''Life of Sertorius'', 9. 4</ref> Moreover, some related that Heracles had a son Palaemon by Iphinoe, the daughter of Antaeus and (presumably) Tinge.<ref>[[Tzetzes]] on [[Lycophron]] 662</ref>\n\n[[Scholia]]sts on [[Pindar]]'s Pythian Ode 9 also recorded a story which made Antaeus king of the city Irassa in Libya, and father of a daughter named either Alceis or Barce. Antaeus promised her hand to the winner of a race, just like [[Danaus]] did to find new husbands for [[Dana\u00efdes|his daughters]]. Alexidamus beat all the other suitors in the race and married the daughter of Antaeus. Three versions of this story, with minor variations, were collected by the scholiasts; one of those versions made Antaeus, king of Irassa, a figure distinct from the Antaeus killed by Heracles, while another one suggested that they were one and the same.<ref>Scholia on Pindar, Pythian Ode 9, 185, referring to [[Pherecydes of Athens|Pherecydes]], [[Pisander of Camirus]] and other unspecified writers</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite EB9 |wstitle=Ant\u00e6us |volume=2  |ref={{harvid|EB|1878}} |page=100 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Antaeus |volume=2  |page=88 |short=x}}\n* {{cite NSRW|wstitle=Ant\u00e6us|short=x}}\n* {{cite Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology|title=Antaeus |volume=1 |url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aentry%3Dantaeus-bio-1 |short=x}}\n* [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Apollodorus]], ''Apollodorus, The Library, with an English Translation by Sir James George Frazer, F.B.A., F.R.S. in 2 Volumes.'' Cambridge, Massachusetts, Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1921.\n* [[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus, Gaius Julius]], [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusFabulae1.html ''The Myths of Hyginus'']. Edited and translated by Mary A. Grant, Lawrence: University of Kansas Press, 1960.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commonscatinline|Antaeus}}\n* [http://www.theoi.com/Gigante/GiganteAntaios.html \"ANTAIOS\"], ''The Theoi Project''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Libya in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Greek giants]]\n[[Category:Offspring of Poseidon]]\n[[Category:Offspring of Gaia]]\n[[Category:Mythology of Heracles]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antaeus"}
{"title_page": "Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[New Riders of the Purple Sage]]\n| cover      = NRPSVeneta.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Startdate|2004|9|21|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = August 27, 1972\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]\n| length     = 70:23\n| label      = Kufala\n| producer   = Rob Bleetstein\n| prev_title = [[Boston Music Hall, 12/5/72]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Armadillo World Headquarters, Austin, TX, 6/13/75]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n}}\n\n'''''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''''' is an [[album]] by the [[country rock]] band the [[New Riders of the Purple Sage]].  It was recorded live on August 27, 1972, at the Springfield Creamery Benefit concert, at Temple Meadow, near [[Veneta, Oregon]].  It was released on September 21, 2004.  It was the third complete New Riders concert that was recorded in the 1970s and released in the 2000s as an album on the Kufala Recordings label, and the only one to be released as one disc instead of two.<ref>[http://www.deaddisc.com/disc/NRPS_Veneta.htm ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at the Grateful Dead Family Discography</ref><ref>[http://www.nrpsmusic.com/music/livearchives.html Live Archive Releases] at the NRPS official website</ref>\n\n==Springfield Creamery Benefit==\nThe Springfield Creamery Benefit, sometimes called the Field Trip, was a benefit concert for a dairy owned by Chuck Kesey, the brother of [[Ken Kesey]], and his wife Sue.<ref>[http://www.nancysyogurt.com/our_creamery/history.php Springfield Creamery \u2014 Our History] at Nancy's Yogurt</ref>  The New Riders of the Purple Sage were the warm up band for the [[Grateful Dead]].<ref>Robbins, Brian (November 14, 2013). [http://www.jambands.com/features/2013/11/14/the-new-riders-buddy-cage-a-sunshine-daydream-prequel/ \"The New Riders' Buddy Cage: A ''Sunshine Daydream'' Prequel\"], Jambands.com. Retrieved September 26, 2016.</ref>  Despite challenging technical conditions \u2014 the weather was unusually hot, and many of the people present were under the influence of [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] \u2014 the Dead's performance that day is highly regarded by tape traders.<ref>{{cite book |title=DeadBase VIII: The Complete Guide to Grateful Dead Song Lists |last=Scott |first=John W. |author2=Dolgushkin, Mike |author3=Nixon, Stu.  |year=1994 |publisher=DeadBase |location=Cornish, NH |isbn=1-877657-15-8 |pages=356, 450\u2013451}}</ref>  The concert is documented in a film and an album, both called ''[[Sunshine Daydream]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Long Strange Trip: The Inside History of the Grateful Dead |url=https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0 |url-access=registration |last=McNally |first=Dennis |year=2002 |publisher=Broadway Books |location=New York |isbn=0-7679-1186-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0/page/440 440\u2013441]}}</ref>\n\n==CD production==\nAccording to the CD liner notes, ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72'' \"was produced from the original 16-track analog master tapes running at 15 i.p.s.  We've tried to preserve this day as it was.... An outdoor event on an extremely hot day with an assortment of [[Merry Pranksters]] on the loose.\"  The album includes several sets of stage announcements that were made during the course of the New Riders' performance, as well as some onstage remarks by members of the band.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>Lankford, Jr., Ronnie D. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/veneta-oregon-august-27-1972-mw0000643600 ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved August 23, 2013.</ref>\n}}\n\nOn [[Allmusic]], Ronnie D. Lankford, Jr. said, \"While the New Riders were always much more straightforward in concert than the [[Grateful Dead|Dead]], and thus lacked the [[jam band]] appeal, they were nonetheless a formidable force. And while they are often remembered for combining [[country music|country]] and [[rock music|rock]], they sound like a good old-fashioned rock band here, even on a country song like \"[[Truck Drivin' Man]]\". Specifically, [[David Nelson (musician)|David Nelson's]] [[electric guitar|guitar]] work and [[Buddy Cage|Buddy Cage's]] [[pedal steel guitar|steel]] work add pizzazz to even the most mundane song, while [[Dave Torbert|Dave Torbert's]] [[bass guitar|bass]] adds infinite bottom end. For whatever reason, ''Veneta'' seems even tighter, more musically together, than previous [live archival] releases.\"<ref name=Allmusic/>\n\nOn Jambands.com, Mike Greenhaus wrote, \"While more polished live packages and reissued studio sessions still define their canon, rough-edged live releases like ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72'' are essential in capturing both the sound and the feel of the New Riders' golden age.... the country quintet stemmed from the Dead's ''[[American Beauty (album)|American Beauty]]'' studio peak, layering gentle psychedelic touches into their concise rock songs. Always more comfortable playing the tripped-out country-folk [[Gram Parsons]] trademarked during his tenure in [[The Byrds]], the NRPS offer unique live versions of cuts like \"Louisiana Lady\" and \"[[Hello Mary Lou]]\", without necessarily jamming such tracks. And, with the exception of the country-rock workout \"[[Willie and the Hand Jive]]\", this bare bones release is stacked with short, tight songs, not epic jams.\"<ref>Greenhaus, Mike (December 1, 2004).[http://www.jambands.com/CDReviews/content_2004_12_01.09.phtml ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at Jambands.com. Retrieved August 23, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn Earvolution, Jim McCoy said, \"Cage's playing is the highlight throughout, with his trademark solo on the late [[Gene Pitney|Gene Pitney's]] \"Hello Mary Lou\" blazing like a rocket up his 10-string [[E9 tuning|E9]] neck; similarly, his twangy, pronounced double stops bring great life to \"Groupie\" and \"Whatcha Gonna Do\". It's not that the other musicians are slackers; in fact, the opposite is true.... for those already familiar with the New Riders \u2014 especially fans of Buddy Cage \u2014 this recording is an essential. Those Deadheads for which 8/27/72 holds a special place in their collections would also be wise to pick up this disc not just for the sake of having a complete representation of the day in their hundreds of hours of material, but because it is a solid example of live early-seventies rock music in its own right.\"<ref>McCoy, Jim (May 8, 2006).[http://www.earvolution.com/2006/05/new-riders-of-purple-sage-veneta.asp ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at Earvolution. Retrieved August 23, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"[[Truck Drivin' Man]]\" ([[Terry Fell]]) \u2013 2:56\n#\"Rainbow\" ([[John Dawson (musician)|John Dawson]]) \u2013 3:40\n#\"Lochinvar\" (Dawson) \u2013 4:51\n#\"Groupie\" ([[Dave Torbert]]) \u2013 3:08\n#Stage Announcement \u2013 White Bird Tent \u2013 2:08\n#\"Whatcha Gonna Do\" (Dawson) \u2013 3:40\n#\"[[Dim Lights, Thick Smoke (And Loud, Loud Music)]]\" (Max Fidler, [[Joe Maphis]], Rose Lee Maphis) \u2013 3:37\n#\"[[Hello Mary Lou]]\" ([[Gene Pitney]]) \u2013 3:08\n#Stage Announcement \u2013 Field Tripping \u2013 0:56\n#\"Whiskey\" (Dawson) \u2013 3:52\n#Stage Announcement \u2013 Salt Tabs & Blue Acid \u2013 1:35\n#\"Runnin' Back to You\" (Dawson) \u2013 4:14\n#\"[[I Don't Need No Doctor]]\" ([[Jo Armstead]], [[Nick Ashford]], [[Valerie Simpson]]) \u2013 6:25\n#\"Linda\" (Dawson) \u2013 5:21\n#\"Louisiana Lady\" (Dawson) \u2013 3:56\n#\"Last Lonely Eagle\" (Dawson) \u2013 6:07\n#\"[[Willie and the Hand Jive]]\" ([[Johnny Otis]]) \u2013 10:38\n\n==Personnel==\n\n;New Riders of the Purple Sage\n*[[Buddy Cage]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[pedal steel guitar]]\n*[[John Dawson (musician)|John Dawson]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[rhythm guitar]], [[vocals]]\n*[[Spencer Dryden]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n*[[David Nelson (musician)|David Nelson]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitar]], vocals\n*[[Dave Torbert]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]], vocals\n\n;Technical personnel\n*Produced by Rob Bleetstein\n*Mixed and mastered by [[Stephen Barncard]]\n*16\u2013track transfer by Jeffrey Norman\n*Recorded by Bob Matthews and [[Betty Cantor]]\n*Bus blotter art by Zane Kesey\n*Event photos from the film ''Sunshine Daydream'' courtesy of Canis Major / Sam Field\n*Stage announcements by [[Ken Babbs]]\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Sunshine Daydream]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New Riders of the Purple Sage}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veneta, Oregon, 8 27 72}}\n[[Category:New Riders of the Purple Sage live albums]]\n[[Category:2004 live albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72\n| type       = live\n| artist     = [[New Riders of the Purple Sage]]\n| cover      = NRPSVeneta.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Startdate|2004|9|21|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = August 27, 1972\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]\n| length     = 70:23\n| label      = Kufala\n| producer   = Rob Bleetstein\n| prev_title = [[Boston Music Hall, 12/5/72]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Armadillo World Headquarters, Austin, TX, 6/13/75]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n}}\n\n'''''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''''' is an [[album]] by the [[country rock]] band the [[New Riders of the Purple Sage]].  It was recorded live on August 27, 1972, at the Springfield Creamery Benefit concert, at Temple Meadow, near [[Veneta, Oregon]].  It was released on September 21, 2004.  It was the third complete New Riders concert that was recorded in the 1970s and released in the 2000s as an album on the Kufala Recordings label, and the only one to be released as one disc instead of two.<ref>[http://www.deaddisc.com/disc/NRPS_Veneta.htm ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at the Grateful Dead Family Discography</ref><ref>[http://www.nrpsmusic.com/music/livearchives.html Live Archive Releases] at the NRPS official website</ref>\n\n==Springfield Creamery Benefit==\nThe Springfield Creamery Benefit, sometimes called the Field Trip, was a benefit concert for a dairy owned by Chuck Kesey, the brother of [[Ken Kesey]], and his wife Sue.<ref>[http://www.nancysyogurt.com/our_creamery/history.php Springfield Creamery \u2014 Our History] at Nancy's Yogurt</ref>  The New Riders of the Purple Sage were the warm up band for the [[Grateful Dead]].<ref>Robbins, Brian (November 14, 2013). [http://www.jambands.com/features/2013/11/14/the-new-riders-buddy-cage-a-sunshine-daydream-prequel/ \"The New Riders' Buddy Cage: A ''Sunshine Daydream'' Prequel\"], Jambands.com. Retrieved September 26, 2016.</ref>  Despite challenging technical conditions \u2014 the weather was unusually hot, and many of the people present were under the influence of [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] \u2014 the Dead's performance that day is highly regarded by tape traders.<ref>{{cite book |title=DeadBase VIII: The Complete Guide to Grateful Dead Song Lists |last=Scott |first=John W. |author2=Dolgushkin, Mike |author3=Nixon, Stu.  |year=1994 |publisher=DeadBase |location=Cornish, NH |isbn=1-877657-15-8 |pages=356, 450\u2013451}}</ref>  The concert is documented in a film and an album, both called ''[[Sunshine Daydream]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Long Strange Trip: The Inside History of the Grateful Dead |url=https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0 |url-access=registration |last=McNally |first=Dennis |year=2002 |publisher=Broadway Books |location=New York |isbn=0-7679-1186-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/longstrangetripi00mcna_0/page/440 440\u2013441]}}</ref>\n\n==CD production==\nAccording to the CD liner notes, ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72'' \"was produced from the original 16-track analog master tapes running at 15 i.p.s.  We've tried to preserve this day as it was.... An outdoor event on an extremely hot day with an assortment of [[Merry Pranksters]] on the loose.\"  The album includes several sets of stage announcements that were made during the course of the New Riders' performance, as well as some onstage remarks by members of the band.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>Lankford, Jr., Ronnie D. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/veneta-oregon-august-27-1972-mw0000643600 ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at [[Allmusic]]. Retrieved August 23, 2013.</ref>\n}}\n\nOn [[Allmusic]], Ronnie D. Lankford, Jr. said, \"While the New Riders were always much more straightforward in concert than the [[Grateful Dead|Dead]], and thus lacked the [[jam band]] appeal, they were nonetheless a formidable force. And while they are often remembered for combining [[country music|country]] and [[rock music|rock]], they sound like a good old-fashioned rock band here, even on a country song like \"[[Truck Drivin' Man]]\". Specifically, [[David Nelson (musician)|David Nelson's]] [[electric guitar|guitar]] work and [[Buddy Cage|Buddy Cage's]] [[pedal steel guitar|steel]] work add pizzazz to even the most mundane song, while [[Dave Torbert|Dave Torbert's]] [[bass guitar|bass]] adds infinite bottom end. For whatever reason, ''Veneta'' seems even tighter, more musically together, than previous [live archival] releases.\"<ref name=Allmusic/>\n\nOn Jambands.com, Mike Greenhaus wrote, \"While more polished live packages and reissued studio sessions still define their canon, rough-edged live releases like ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72'' are essential in capturing both the sound and the feel of the New Riders' golden age.... the country quintet stemmed from the Dead's ''[[American Beauty (album)|American Beauty]]'' studio peak, layering gentle psychedelic touches into their concise rock songs. Always more comfortable playing the tripped-out country-folk [[Gram Parsons]] trademarked during his tenure in [[The Byrds]], the NRPS offer unique live versions of cuts like \"Louisiana Lady\" and \"[[Hello Mary Lou]]\", without necessarily jamming such tracks. And, with the exception of the country-rock workout \"[[Willie and the Hand Jive]]\", this bare bones release is stacked with short, tight songs, not epic jams.\"<ref>Greenhaus, Mike (December 1, 2004).[http://www.jambands.com/CDReviews/content_2004_12_01.09.phtml ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at Jambands.com. Retrieved August 23, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn Earvolution, Jim McCoy said, \"Cage's playing is the highlight throughout, with his trademark solo on the late [[Gene Pitney|Gene Pitney's]] \"Hello Mary Lou\" blazing like a rocket up his 10-string [[E9 tuning|E9]] neck; similarly, his twangy, pronounced double stops bring great life to \"Groupie\" and \"Whatcha Gonna Do\". It's not that the other musicians are slackers; in fact, the opposite is true.... for those already familiar with the New Riders \u2014 especially fans of Buddy Cage \u2014 this recording is an essential. Those Deadheads for which 8/27/72 holds a special place in their collections would also be wise to pick up this disc not just for the sake of having a complete representation of the day in their hundreds of hours of material, but because it is a solid example of live early-seventies rock music in its own right.\"<ref>McCoy, Jim (May 8, 2006).[http://www.earvolution.com/2006/05/new-riders-of-purple-sage-veneta.asp ''Veneta, Oregon, 8/27/72''] at Earvolution. Retrieved August 23, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"[[Truck Drivin' Man]]\" ([[Terry Fell]]) \u2013 2:56\n#\"Rainbow\" ([[John Dawson (musician)|John Dawson]]) \u2013 3:40\n#\"Lochinvar\" (Dawson) \u2013 4:51\n#\"Groupie\" ([[Dave Torbert]]) \u2013 3:08\n#Stage Announcement \u2013 White Bird Tent \u2013 2:08\n#\"Whatcha Gonna Do\" (Dawson) \u2013 3:40\n#\"[[Dim Lights, Thick Smoke (And Loud, Loud Music)]]\" (Max Fidler, [[Joe Maphis]], Rose Lee Maphis) \u2013 3:37\n#\"[[Hello Mary Lou]]\" ([[Gene Pitney]]) \u2013 3:08\n#Stage Announcement \u2013 Field Tripping \u2013 0:56\n#\"Whiskey\" (Dawson) \u2013 3:52\n#Stage Announcement \u2013 Salt Tabs & Blue Acid \u2013 1:35\n#\"Runnin' Back to You\" (Dawson) \u2013 4:14\n#\"[[I Don't Need No Doctor]]\" ([[Jo Armstead]], [[Nick Ashford]], [[Valerie Simpson]]) \u2013 6:25\n#\"Linda\" (Dawson) \u2013 5:21\n#\"Louisiana Lady\" (Dawson) \u2013 3:56\n#\"Last Lonely Eagle\" (Dawson) \u2013 6:07\n#\"[[Willie and the Hand Jive]]\" ([[Johnny Otis]]) \u2013 10:38\n\n==Personnel==\n\n;New Riders of the Purple Sage\n*[[Buddy Cage]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[pedal steel guitar]]\n*[[John Dawson (musician)|John Dawson]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[rhythm guitar]], [[vocals]]\n*[[Spencer Dryden]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[drum kit|drums]]\n*[[David Nelson (musician)|David Nelson]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitar]], vocals\n*[[Dave Torbert]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]], vocals\n\n;Technical personnel\n*Produced by Rob Bleetstein\n*Mixed and mastered by [[Stephen Barncard]]\n*16\u2013track transfer by Jeffrey Norman\n*Recorded by Bob Matthews and Betty Cantor\n*Bus blotter art by Zane Kesey\n*Event photos from the film ''Sunshine Daydream'' courtesy of Canis Major / Sam Field\n*Stage announcements by [[Ken Babbs]]\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Sunshine Daydream]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New Riders of the Purple Sage}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veneta, Oregon, 8 27 72}}\n[[Category:New Riders of the Purple Sage live albums]]\n[[Category:2004 live albums]]\n", "name_user": "Mudwater", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonnel:Linked Betty Cantor.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veneta,_Oregon,_8/27/72"}
